<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly Democrats say they will block sportsman fee increase  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Two Assembly Democrats say they won't let
hunting and fishing license fees go up in New York until the state
Department of Environmental Conservation is willing to sit down and
discuss why the increase is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until there is a full discussion, we're not proceeding,'' said
Assembly Majority Leader Michael Bragman of Onondaga County. He and
Democratic Assemblyman Richard Brodsky said Monday the Assembly
will not include a license fee increase in their budget to be
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There probably is a need for a license increase but they need
to justify it,'' Bragman said.
</P>
<P>
   This came as state Comptroller H. Carl McCall released an audit
of the state's Conservation Fund, which state officials say is
running out of money and needs hunting and fishing license
increases to keep in the black.
</P>
<P>
   But ''this audit shows that there may be more funds available
and more options to consider before a final decision is made to
raise those fees,'' McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, though, also proves that the fee increase that state
officials have been asking for is needed, said Jennifer Post,
spokeswoman for the Department of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The audit confirms that revenues do not meet expenditures and
that lawmakers need to address the situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The $32.7 million Conservation Fund pays for about half of the
state's fish and wildlife programs. The rest comes from federal
aid, state taxes and other funds.
</P>
<P>
   The DEC has said it would have to cut $2 million worth of state
programs by April to keep the fund in the black. It has also said
the state Conservation Fund will have an almost $30 million deficit
by April 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The DEC has asked for an increase in sportsmen's fees by 19.9
percent to help make up for the difference and Gov. George Pataki
included the increase in his budget.
</P>
<P>
   After not getting an increase last year, the department closed a
state-run game farm that provides pheasants for hunters. It already
has announced a nine-point contingency plan for further cuts this
year if it doesn't get its increase, including scaling back on some
fish production efforts, reducing forest management, reducing some
fish hatcheries and reducing some law enforcement efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups have been pushing for the increase. ''New York state
already has one of the lowest sportsman license fees in the nation,
and it has not been increased for close to a decade,'' said David
Miller, executive director of the National Audubon Society of New
York State. ''The proposed increase will support critical wildlife
habitat conservation efforts that benefit all New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   State law requires the money in the Conservation Fund to go only
to fish and wildlife programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you read the audit, you will see that it confirms that the
fund has been properly managed,'' Post said.
</P>
<P>
   While McCall says DEC has been spending the Conservation Fund's
money appropriately, not all of the fund's revenue from the sale of
licenses has been accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sporting licenses are sold by nearly 1,800 vendors around the
state,'' McCall said. ''DEC has not reconciled its books since 1994
to ensure that the state has received all of the revenues for
licenses sold by those vendors.''
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller also said DEC underestimated the fund's balance
by $1.5 million when it said a fee increase was needed. That
includes $700,000 in fund interest from the sale of lifetime
licenses that had not been calculated by the department.
</P>
<P>
   Despite McCall's findings, Brodsky says DEC won't sit down and
talk with them about whether a fee increase is needed. ''We found
close to $2 million! They ought to come out of their bunkers,''
Brodsky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0019 </TRAILER>
