<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate leader wants to eliminate gas sales tax completely  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Another tax cutting war may be starting in
the state Capitol, but this time it is over gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate's Republican majority leader on Monday
suggested that the state eliminate its sales tax on gasoline
completely, instead of for just two months like the state
Assembly's Democratic leader has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Bruno called for eliminating the 4 percent sales tax
on May 1, saving drivers more than $300 million a year. That means
drivers would save 8 cents a gallon if gas hits $2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the sales tax helps ''ensure that government doesn't
profit from drivers' pain,'' the Republican leader said.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers have been hit with a double whammy of sorts on
energy prices. OPEC's decision to curtail oil production caused
crude oil prices to climb, and a harsh stretch of weather in
January and early February caused demand and the price of home
heating oil to soar in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have followed suit, with unleaded regular now
routinely costing $1.50 or more a gallon. There have been
predictions of continued price escalation into the summer tourist
months.
</P>
<P>
   The state would make up the money lost from the increase in tax
revenues due to record bonus payments to Wall Street traders, Bruno
said. ''What better use can we make of those additional dollars
than to return those dollars to the taxpayers of this state?'' the
Senate leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver had called Sunday for
eliminating the sales tax on gasoline for just two summer months.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great idea,'' Bruno said Monday. ''I'm glad that he
focused on that. We just want to make a great idea even greater.''
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly plan would cost some $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki said he was generally in favor of eliminating
the state's gas sales tax but delivered a warning to legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the strength of the state economy we could afford a tax
cut that would get rid of the state sales tax on gasoline for years
to come, but not if we go on spending binges in other areas, not if
we're going to pass other massive tax cuts,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Silver proposed a $967 million increase in education
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, Silver and Bruno are in the middle of hashing out the
state budget. It has been 16 years since lawmakers and the governor
completed passage on a new budget prior to the April 1 start of the
new state fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate GOP proposal would give counties and municipalities
which also impose a local gas tax -- their add-ons are generally
between 3 percent and 4 percent -- the option of also waiving those
levies.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruno proposal is similar to the state's elimination of its
portion of sales taxes on clothing purchases worth $110 or less.
That went into effect on March 1. A handful of localities -- most
significantly New York City -- also decided to give up their portion
of sales taxes on those purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed sales tax eliminations from Silver would only cover
gas and diesel fuel for automobiles, not diesel fuel for large
trucks. Bruno's proposal would include diesel for trucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0020 </TRAILER>
