<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki proposes opening New York's GOP prez primary ballot  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Just days after defending the state's
Republican presidential primary system, Gov. George Pataki has
proposed a massive overhaul of the system before the next one comes
around.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of widespread criticism that he had tried to stack
the deck in Texas Gov. George W. Bush's favor, Pataki on Monday
unveiled a four-point ballot reform proposal that, if approved by
the state Legislature, would allow all nationally recognized
candidates onto the New York GOP ballot. It would also make the
state's GOP primary a winner-take-all contest and allow New York
Republicans to vote directly for the candidates, not for delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also have primary polls open from 6 a.m. to 9
p.m. statewide. Those hours are currently in force only for New
York City, the suburban counties surrounding the city and in Erie
County where Buffalo is located. In the rest of the state, primary
polls are only open from noon to 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''Campaigns should not get bogged down needlessly by
technicalities that draw attention away from the candidates'
ideas,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The call to make the GOP primary a winner-take-all affair drew
immediate fire from state Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's just another way of rigging the primary'' for the party
favorite, Hope said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, state GOP Chairman William Powers, citing the results
of last week's primary, said Monday that ''winner-take-all looks
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   In last week's New York GOP primary, Bush won at least 67 of the
93 delegates at stake. Sen. John McCain took the rest. Pataki had
run the Texas governor's campaign in New York. Had the Pataki
reform been in place, Bush would have captured all 93 delegates at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and Powers had led an unsuccessful effort to use the
state's complex ballot access rules to keep everyone but Bush off
the New York primary ballot this year. McCain took to calling
Pataki and Powers ''comrade'' and compared the New York ballot
access rules to the old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge's order eventually opened up the ballot to
McCain, who suspended his campaign in the wake of Bush's Super
Tuesday primary victories in a host of states including New York,
California and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pataki's plan, all GOP presidential candidates who had
qualified for matching federal funds would have spots on the New
York GOP ballot. Also, the two Republican members of the
four-person state Board of Elections could add other Republicans to
the ballot by designating them nationally recognized candidates.
Other candidates seeking to get on the GOP ballot would have to
collect the signatures of 5,000 party members.
</P>
<P>
   This year, GOP candidates had to collect signatures from party
members in any of the state's 31 congressional districts in which
they wanted to field delegate slates. GOP voters then got to vote
for the delegate slates, but not the candidates. There were, in
effect, 31 mini-primaries with three GOP delegates elected in each
congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Pataki proposal, GOP voters would cast ballots
directly for the candidates and the winner of the popular vote
statewide would win all the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP primary ballot rules were eased somewhat in the wake of
the 1996 contest when Pataki and Powers also got roundly criticized
for their unsuccessful effort to keep everyone off the ballot that
year but Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't go far enough,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a little late, isn't he?'' Hope said with a laugh Monday
when asked Pataki's plan. ''It's a disgrace the way the Republicans
have manipulated the ballot to their own backroom purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's Democrats vote directly for the candidates in their
party's primary and delegates are then awarded proportionately in
accordance with the percentage of the primary vote, above 15
percent, won by each candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0021 </TRAILER>
