<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York City vies with upstate town in zoning decision  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN BREZOSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- An all-year resort planned for a picturesque
mountain valley pits stewardship of New York City's drinking water
source against local zoning authority.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the Catskill watershed agreement was
signed in 1997, New York City petitioned the state to become the
lead agency in the environmental quality review, or SEQR, of plans
for the Belleayre resort. That resort would include 1,900 acres of
hotels, time-share housing, markets and golf greens surrounding the
state-run Belleayre ski mountain in Ulster and Sullivan counties.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Shandaken, population 3,000, sees the city's
application as an affront. Town officials feel are seen as unable
to protect the drinking supply of 9 million New York City residents
and that the city is violating the spirit of the watershed
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very fundamental and very important issue, not just
for Shandaken but really for the Catskill region and the whole
Hudson Valley,'' said Joel Sachs, attorney for the Coalition of
Watershed Towns. ''The issue really is are the municipalities going
to make the fundamental decisions as to what type of land use there
should be, or is New York City?''
</P>
<P>
   State Environmental Conservation Commissioner John Cahill is
expected to decide in a week whether the city will become the lead
agency in the environmental review of the development project.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's drinking water comes from three upstate
watersheds -- the Catskill, Delaware and Croton systems.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to some who live in the region, the city's
interest in the watershed is strangling the region's attempts to
recover from the economic doldrums left by its faded resort
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''You dig a hole here, they're right here checking where the
hole is,'' said Robert DeKalb, a member of Shandaken's planning
board. ''I moved away from New York City to be in the mountains.
Now I'm right here in the middle of a conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Sachs, ''New York City agreed they would not do anything
to impede the municipalities in upstate New York from proceeding in
their own land use decisions. They're getting in the way of
economic development in the town of Shandaken.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of legal battles between upstate and downstate
interests and environmentalists and developers, the 1997 watershed
agreement required the city to spend $1.5 billion on watershed
protection upstate, including buying land to keep it from
development.
</P>
<P>
   In return, upstate officials agreed to allow the city to
regulate development in certain swaths of the watershed. The U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency waived an order requiring the city
to build an $8 billion filtration plant to ensure the quality of
the city's drinking water supply.
</P>
<P>
   That waiver expires in 2002, when the EPA will again review the
city's management of the water.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Department of Environmental Protection has an
ally in James Tierney, assistant attorney general to state Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer. Tierney urged Cahill to approve the city's
request on Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ''Polluted and heated runoff could significantly add to the
degradation of this unfiltered drinking water supply,'' Tierney
said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   He added that a number of trout streams in the region could be
harmed by runoff during construction and later by pollution such as
fertilizers and pesticides from golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney said that while the Shandaken planning board has
consultants and engineers to provide advice and technical
assistance, DEP's watershed expertise and experience as lead agency
for numerous large-scale projects makes it the better choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''The project really needs to be reviewed from both the local
and regional perspective,'' said Adirondack Mountain Club spokesman
Neil Woodworth. The club's hikers who also trek the Catskills
envision mountaintops marred by hotels and vacation housing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the issue particularly sensitive is the economics of
the proposal, so far estimated at around $200 million while
creating 300 permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   According to DeKalb, Belleayre Mountain is all the town has to
draw tourists and their dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0022 </TRAILER>
