<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver proposes $967 million more than Pataki for education  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver says he
wants to pump at least $1.3 billion into the state's public school
system, despite urgings from Gov. George Pataki to put less money
into the state system.
</P>
<P>
   Silver on Monday proposed to add $1.3 billion in general support
for state schools and a one-time $500 million boost for school
construction and minor repairs. The extra money can be funded out
of the state's surplus, which totals about $4.2 billion, the
Manhattan Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Considering that our education system and our workforce are
some of our greatest assets ... we believe that this state owes it
to them and their parents to make this kind of investment,'' Silver
said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's proposal is $967 million more than what Pataki had
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In his budget proposal in January, Pataki had asked the
Legislature to put an additional $353 million into elementary and
secondary education, a 3 percent increase over the current-year aid
levels.
</P>
<P>
   That would have brought education spending up to about $12.9
billion, a continuation of record amounts of spending on education
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki did not sound supportive when asked about Silver's plan,
saying the Legislature already is proposing massive tax cuts and
other spending programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we didn't do anything else, we could do this, but it's a
question of everything being added together,'' he said. ''Record
increases in education, increases in local assistance, increases in
highway and transportation funding and at the same time record tax
cuts -- any one of these or any combination can be done within a
context of a balanced budget, but they can't all be done within the
context of a balanced budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said the Assembly will present a balanced budget plan
with their education proposals. ''Therefore, it makes sense,'' he
said. ''It makes sense to invest in our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver, Republican Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno and state
Education Commissioner Richard Mills have all said that more money
is needed than Pataki proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Assembly proposal for a $1.3 billion increase is welcome
news and should help direct the discussion toward ways to improve
learning standards and student achievement,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said the additional funding will be used to provide for
smaller class sizes and universal pre-kindergarten, better teacher
training, improved academic standards and promotion of summer
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly leader also suggested that increased education
spending could reduce local property taxes, which go toward
supporting schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every dollar that New York state invests in education is a
dollar that the property taxpayers will not have to contribute,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Education spending is often at the center of budget negotiations
and is expected to be there again this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0022 </TRAILER>
