<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malcolm Wilson, former New York governor, dead at age 86  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Malcolm Wilson, who had a resume that
included 20 years in the state Assembly, 15 years as lieutenant
governor and one year as New York's chief executive, has died.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who served as governor of New York for a year after the
resignation of the late Nelson A. Rockefeller, died Monday morning
at the New Rochelle home of his daughter, Katherine Wilson Conroy.
He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Family friend William O'Shaughnessy, head of WVOX radio in
Westchester County, said the former governor died in his sleep.
Wilson had long been a resident of Scarsdale, Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative Republican, Wilson had a lengthy career in
banking and maintained a private law practice after losing the 1974
governor's race to Democrat Hugh Carey. It was the only election
Wilson has ever lost.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had undergone surgery for an aortic aneurysm in September
1991 and had been in failing health in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a real loss for New York,'' Gov. George Pataki told a
state Capitol news conference. ''He was a wonderful governor and a
great person.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he had gotten to know Wilson while working on
Rockefeller's 1970 re-election campaign and said the
then-lieutenant governor often put ''politics completely aside'' in
favor of policy ''whether or not it was in his interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was a loyal and self-effacing No. 2 during his four terms
as Rockefeller's heir apparent beginning in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   He achieved his lifelong ambition of being governor when
Rockefeller, deciding his way to the White House did not lie
through Albany, resigned in December 1973 with a year to go in his
final term. Eight months later, President Gerald Ford appointed
Rockefeller vice president in the wake of Richard Nixon's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had 12 months as a largely caretaker 50th governor of New
York and enjoyed the advantages of incumbency when he ran on his
own in November 1974. But Wilson was overwhelmed by Democrat Carey
in the post-Watergate electoral disaster that brought down
Republican candidates all across the country.
</P>
<P>
   After serving as lieutenant governor longer than any man in
state history, Wilson's tenure as governor was the shortest since
the 29-day reign of Democrat Charles Poletti in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was only 24 years old and two years out of Fordham Law
School when he was elected to the Assembly from Yonkers in 1938. He
was elected to nine more two-year terms in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed as a young man with a bright political future, Wilson
found paths to power blocked by other Republicans with
gubernatorial ambition and decided in 1958 to cast his lot with
Rockefeller, a relative newcomer who needed pull with the
Republican regulars.
</P>
<P>
   As a conservative, organization counterweight to Rockefeller's
perceived liberalism and inexperience, Wilson helped line up the
support of county leaders for Rockefeller's first run.
</P>
<P>
   While remaining in the background, Wilson was known among his
colleagues for narrow ties, a dry wit and using at least two long
words where one short one would do.
</P>
<P>
   Once, talking about a coincidence, he called it a ''fortuitous
concatenation of felicitous circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a devout Roman Catholic and one of the few issues on
which he ever publicly differed with Rockefeller was liberalizing
state abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who styled himself ''a human-rights liberal and an
economic conservative,'' served two years in the Navy in World War
II, seeing action at the Normandy invasion.
</P>
<P>
   From 1977 to 1986, he was chairman of the Manhattan Savings Bank
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He was born near Columbia University in New York City on Feb.
26, 1914. The family moved to Yonkers, where Wilson's schoolteacher
mother became a Republican district leader.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 he married Katharine McCloskey, who died in 1980. They
had two daughters, Katherine and Anne.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be held Thursday morning at the Holy
Family Church in New Rochelle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
