<HEADLINE> Pataki, CSEA reach agreement  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's largest union has a tentative
agreement with annual raises of up to 3.5 percent that could end
acrimonious negotiations with the Pataki administration.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the 77,000-strong Civil Service Employees Association
will soon vote on the proposed four-year contract recommended by
their negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative deal follows more than a year of contentious
contract negotiations and union protests across the state. The
members have worked without a contract since April 1, 1999. Members
will vote on this offer in April.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract, which CSEA leaders will recommend to members,
includes across-the-board salary increases of: 3 percent
retroactive to October 1999; 3 percent effective April 2000; 3.5
percent effective in April 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   A contract offering smaller raises over the four years was
rejected by the union last March.
</P>
<P>
   ''A combination of the mobilization of members and persistence
at the bargaining table is what made this possible,'' said Stephen
Madarasz, spokesman for the CSEA. ''Members were energized as we've
never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of the mostly blue-collar union had been angry over
what they felt was a substandard contract offer from the state,
particularly after state lawmakers and Gov. George Pataki approved
38 percent pay raises for themselves in December 1998. Then in
March 1999, the state ended its fiscal year with a multi-billion
dollar surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no question that was the reason the contract was
rejected last March,'' Madarasz said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the CSEA's $1 million advertising budget over the last
year was shifted to cover radio and television ads aimed at
mobilizing union members. During the same time, protests staged by
members of CSEA and other state worker's unions met Pataki at
appearances across the state and as far away as Michigan. One rally
at the capital drew 20,000 members, according to Madarasz.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could not have had the results at the table without the
individual efforts of our members who stood up in every part of the
state,'' said Danny Donohue, CSEA's president.
</P>
<P>
   For state employees who have worked 10 years or more, the
contract also eliminates the 3 percent yearly pension contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the contract demonstrates a commitment to CSEA
members, ''as well as our efforts to safeguard the interests of
taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also includes:
</P>
<P>
   --A $500 lump sum payment to be counted toward pensions.
</P>
<P>
   --The elimination of an additional premium cost for prescription
coverage and increased funding for dental and eyeglass benefits.
</P>
<P>
   --Increases in the downstate salary adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   --Improvements in hazardous duty pay, inconvenience pay, overtime
meal allowances and standby pay.
</P>
<P>
   Members of New York's second-largest public employees union,
Public Employees Federation, are still working without a contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0024 </TRAILER>
