<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reservation gas, cigarette prices looking even better lately  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CATTARAUGUS INDIAN RESERVATION, N.Y. (AP) -- There have been a
lot of new faces at JR's Smokeshop lately, well ahead of the usual
warm-weather crowds.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Morgan Reid only expects to get busier as more
consumers seek relief from the highest cigarette and gasoline
prices many have ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 1, the cost of cigarettes off the reservation has
jumped to $4 a pack or more while gasoline has soared a record 12
cents per gallon to an average of $1.59.
</P>
<P>
   On the reservation, where Native American vendors pay no tax on
cigarettes and only federal tax on gasoline, cigarettes sell for
about $2.29 a pack and gas for $1.29 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Palczwski expected to save about $15 Monday during a
minutes-long stop at JR's, where he filled the tank and picked up a
carton of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a day off so I decided to go for a ride,'' said
Palczwski, who lives about 25 minutes away in West Seneca, just
outside Buffalo. ''It's definitely worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reservation vendors say the increased traffic that normally
comes with the warm weather seems to have started already. Reid
estimated business is up about 10 percent at JR's.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette increase was the work of the state, which raised
the cigarette tax by 55 cents a pack effective March 1 to a
highest-in-the-nation $1.11. The high gas prices come amid rising
crude oil costs.
</P>
<P>
   Off-reservation convenience store owners say they are already
feeling the effects of charging more for cigarettes and worry
things will only get worse when smokers who stocked up before the
hike look to replenish their supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The early information we're getting is there is a very large
exodus of business from our member convenience stores,'' said Jim
Calvin, executive director of the New York Association of
Convenience Stores. ''I expect we'll have a clearer idea by the end
of March but I wouldn't be surprised to see some stores lose 30 to
50 percent of their cigarette business and potentially more.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, fuel sales seem to be holding steady, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The association wants the state to repeal the March 1 cigarette
tax increase, saying the state has to level the playing field or
risk putting stores out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said reservation stores have raised the price of cigarettes
by about $3 a carton in recent weeks to close the gap between on-
and off-reservation stores. But cigarettes are still between $9 and
$13 cheaper by the carton on the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not trying to take all the business from off the
reservation,'' he said. ''We've never said we want all the sales,
but (the state) keeps pushing the people toward us every time they
raise their prices.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rossell detoured off the Thruway on his way from Jamestown
to Buffalo to stock up on cigarettes at the Seneca Hawk truck stop.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not normally do that,'' he said, ''but now that
cigarettes are $4.25 a pack I thought I'd save a dollar or two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
