<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facility will develop strategies and hi-tech training vs.cybercrime  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- A $300,000 federal grant will help create a
high-tech lab at the former Griffiss Air Force Base to train police
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Criminals have clearly gone high-tech, with more cybercrimes
being reported every day,'' Sen. Charles Schumer, D-NY, said in a
statement Monday. ''I am pleased to announce that now
crime-fighting has gone high-tech, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal grant from the National Institute of Justice, the
research and technology development arm of the U.S. Department of
Justice, enabled the project to move forward. The goal is to
develop five such facilities across the nation as the influence of
computers grows.
</P>
<P>
   Several projects already are in the works, including development
of a system for the rapid electronic dissemination of photos of
missing or exploited children. A low-power radar gun that can
detect concealed weapons made of any material is expected to be
available within a year. Law-enforcement officials are hopeful it
will greatly limit the potential for violence in schools and
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ''The threats to our national security are growing and taking on
many new forms,'' said Delores Etter, Deputy Undersecretary of
Defense for Science and Technology in the Clinton administration.
''Information warfare is something we have to look at seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The facility will work closely with Rome Laboratory, one of the
Air Force's top high-technology facilities. One of the major goals
is to enable overlapping law-enforcement agencies to share vital
information much more easily than they can now.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has local implications, but it reaches far beyond,'' said
U.S. Representative Sherwood Boehlert, R-NY. ''The things that they
can do here are exciting. James Bond looks like a piker compared to
them. Their challenge is working to stay one step ahead of the
criminal -- whether he's on the streets or in cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Citarella has been a prosecutor for 18 years in Westchester
County, and news of the formation of the new lab had him more
excited than he's been in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sort of partnership between technology and industry and
law enforcement is very critical at the local level,'' Citarella
said. ''We need to be able to proceed from the seizure of the
computer to completed forensics really within a week or less in 99
percent of the cases. That gives us the capability to do computer
crime. It's terribly exciting. Without this, it's much more
difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0027 </TRAILER>
