<HEADLINE> Sonics 113, Grizzlies 103  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Gary Payton led a
third-quarter charge and finished with 40 points as the Seattle
SuperSonics rolled to a 113-103 win Monday over the Vancouver
Grizzlies, who absorbed their ninth straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   Payton keyed an 18-6 Seattle run to begin the second half,
hitting five of his first seven shots to offset Vancouver center
Bryant Reeves's season-high 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was virtually unstoppable in the opening 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his first 11 field goal attempts, setting a franchise
record, and had 25 points and eight rebounds at intermission. The
Sonics started with Jelani McCoy guarding Reeves, switched to Greg
Foster and then to Horace Grant. None were effective defensively.
</P>
<P>
   But once the Sonics began to double-team Reeves, they slowed
him, and built an 81-64 lead by the midway point of the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Vancouver assigned Doug West, its best defensive
player, to guard Payton.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies got as close as 96-92 with 6:49 left, but the
Sonics held on for their third win in four outings.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Barry added 14 for Seattle and helped the Sonics'
backcourt outscore Vancouver's guard tandem of Mike Bibby and
Michael Dickerson, 54-24.
</P>
<P>
   Payton finished one point shy of the career-high 41 he scored
against Washington on Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Shareef Abdur-Rahim had 17 points for Vancouver, the fifth
straight game he has been held to 20 points or less.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver shot 59 percent in the first half but still trailed
60-58 at the break.
Notes: Sonics coach Paul Westphal would not comment before the
game on the $100,000 fine levied Monday against the club when he
refused to wear a microphone during Sunday's contest against
Toronto. ... Seattle forward Vin Baker (strained left hamstring)
was a scratch for the second straight game. ... The Grizzlies
entered Monday's game allowing opponents to make 47.3 percent of
their field goal attempts, last in the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
