<HEADLINE> Thrashers Trade Buchberger, Emerson  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Thrashers, who have lost 21 of 22
games, shook up their team late Monday night by trading captain
Kelly Buchberger and winger Nelson Emerson to the Los Angeles Kings
for winger Donald Audette and minor-league defenseman Frantisek
Kaberle.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger, 33, was the cornerstone of the Thrashers franchise,
a right winger who played on three Stanley Cup championship teams
in Edmonton before he was taken in the expansion draft by Atlanta
and given a three-year, $2.85 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very tough,'' Thrashers general manager Don Waddell
said. ''Honestly, I wrestled with this one the last four days.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wouldn't pass up a chance to land a 26-year-old
defenseman like Kaberle, who had nine assists in 37 games for the
Kings and has been playing with Long Beach of the IHL. The Czech
native is expected to join the Thrashers for Thursday night's game
against the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a very skilled defenseman who moves the puck well,''
Waddell said. ''He's going to jump right into this team and become
one of our top defensemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger had five goals and 12 assists while playing in all 68
games for the Thrashers. The trade was announced a couple of hours
after his final game in Atlanta, a 3-0 loss to his previous team,
the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, 32, signed with the Thrashers as a free agent and had
14 goals and 19 assists in 58 games, making him the team's
third-leading scorer. When Los Angeles asked for him in the deal,
the Kings agreed to give up Audette, 29, who has 12 goals and 20
assists in 49 games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta coach Curt Fraser said he wouldn't name a new captain
until next season out of respect to Buchberger.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kelly was special to me,'' Fraser said. ''He was a leader and
we did a lot of work to build this team together. It was very tough
on him. I think I put him in a role that was maybe too much for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger and Emerson already had left Philips Arena when the
trade was announced and were not available for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
