<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiat May Outlast it's Founders  </HEADLINE>
By ELLEN KNICKMEYER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TURIN, Italy (AP) -- Starting it as little more than an
aristocratic hobby 101 years ago, ex-cavalry officer Giovanni
Agnelli built Fiat automaker into a family dynasty that outlasted
kings, innumerable Italian governments and one envious dictator.
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, annoyed at the reverence Italy was paying the Agnelli
clan, Benito Mussolini grumbled that Fiat was on its way to
becoming ''an untouchable and sacred state institution, on par with
royalty, the church, a regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Mussolini fell, and the Agnellis and the reverence endured, so
much so that Gianni Agnelli, the patriarch at the start of Fiat's
third century, is widely known today as Italy's uncrowned king.
</P>
<P>
   But the king is 79, with no family heir-apparent. Fiat,
strengthened now through its $2.4 billion alliance Monday with
General Motors Corp., now may well thrive beyond the Agnelli auto
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've given us life. They've given us labor,'' Giorgio
Gziva, a native-born Turino, said of the Agnellis. ''But today in
2000, you have to develop, you have to look outward.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiat in a sense always looked outward, to America -- and
flourished from it.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni Agnelli, starting Fiat with some aristocratic friends
and $400 in capital in 1899, made the company's fortune by doggedly
melding Detroit production principles with Italian style.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat meant jobs for entire generations of Italian families,
drawing epic migrations of workers from the poorer south in
previous decades.
</P>
<P>
   Italy today still is second only to the state in giving
Italians' employment, with 221,000 jobs in all.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the alliance with GM, Fiat said the best guarantee
of jobs was economic success -- suggesting that almost unthinkable
job cuts may well be ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat clearly has to do something to stop the decline that has
afflicted the company, as well as the family, since the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1990s, Fiat saw its share of the Italian auto market
fall from 60 percent to 39 percent. Even in its backyard, Western
Europe, Fiat's auto share barely made the double digits.
</P>
<P>
   Italian industrial leaders are said to have made humiliatingly
clear the waning influence of Fiat and the uncrowned king this
month when they passed over his candidate to lead Italy's key
business lobbying bloc.
</P>
<P>
   The dynasty itself suffered what may be its irrecoverable blow
in 1997, when cancer robbed Fiat of its chosen leader for the next
generation, a 33-year-old grandnephew of Giovanni Agnelli.
</P>
<P>
   The death forced Fiat to turn outside to American industry for
leadership, picking as chairman Paolo Fresco, a former
second-in-command at General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is once again turning to America as it looks to
its future.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal gives GM a 20 percent stake in Fiat Auto, while
Fiat acquires 5.1 percent of GM. Both companies hope to save
billions of dollars through shared supply and labor and make
billions through shared entries into international markets.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat said the partnership preserves untouched its beloved
Ferrari and Maserati sports car lines -- and its equally beloved
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We laid down two goals: an alliance as strong as possible and
autonomy,'' said Gianni Agnelli, who approved the deal with GM on
his birthday Sunday, after earlier reportedly rebuffing other
partnerships that might have meant surrendering control.
</P>
<P>
   But the accord gives GM first choice at buying a bigger stake of
Fiat at some undisclosed time in the future -- most likely years
from now, after the end of its last Agnelli leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 0059 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000314.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, March 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Embraces GOP Congresional Leaders
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- George W. Bush cast himself as a Washington outsider Monday
even as he embraced Republican congressional leaders after months of keeping his
distance. As primary voting headed into a Southern ''Super Tuesday'' with all
the suspense gone, the two remaining major candidates -- Al Gore from Florida,
Bush from stops in Mississippi and Louisiana -- dueled over which of them has
the makings of a president. Gore said Bush offers only ''risky'' tax cuts that
no one but special-interest campaign donors want.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
3 Japanese Banks Announce Merger
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Three Japanese banks -- Sanwa, Tokai and Asahi -- announced a
merger on Tuesday to create the world's third-largest bank, further
consolidating the country's recovering financial industry. The three banks said
they will set up a joint holding company in April 2001, under which they will
''swiftly'' reorganize their retail, wholesale, international, computer systems
and other operations. They will have combined assets of $1 trillion to become
the second-largest Japanese bank, and the third-largest in the world.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Finland Marks Post Winter War Peace
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Finns on Monday marked the 60th anniversary of a
truce that followed 105 days of fierce fighting against Stalin's Red Army in the
Winter War, possibly one of the coldest in history. Finland lost, but the small
country's resistance against the Soviets helped secure its independence in
post-war Europe. Some 23,000 Finnish soldiers were killed, and 45,000 wounded,
in a population of 3.7 million. But Finland's white-clad troops on skis, which
became famous as the ''ghost army,'' proved a stronger force than expected. The
Soviet Union put its losses at 217,500 dead or wounded, but Finland estimated
enemy casualties at up to 400,000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Utility Industry Reliability Questioned
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson Monday said rapid change
in the electricity industry is causing reliability problems that could increase
the likelihood of power outages this summer. Richardson said Congress must pass
legislation to restructure the electric utility industry as it becomes
competitive or risk ''more long, hot summers of outages in America's cities.''
An Energy Department report says the transition to competition has caused some
utilities to focus on competing for markets, cutting costs and maximizing
prices, instead of assuring that power is kept flowing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Annan Warns on Iraqi Oil Industry
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned in a report today
that Iraq's oil industry will continue to deteriorate, jeopardizing U.N. relief
operations, unless more spare parts are allowed into the country immediately.
The 63-page report details how low oil prices, bureaucratic delays and blocked
contracts have undermined efforts to improve life for 22 million Iraqis living
under U.N. trade sanctions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russians: Chechen Leader Captured
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   URUS-MARTAN, Russia (AP) -- Russia said Monday it had finally captured senior
Chechen warlord Salman Raduyev, an elusive fighter who once raided Russia and
seized hundreds of hostages and claims to have set bombs at Russian rail
stations. Raduyev was the first high-level rebel leader seized by Russia in the
six-month-old Chechen war. The Russians say they are questioning him at a Moscow
prison. He was charged Monday with terrorism, which carries a possible sentence
of 50 years, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise Moderately
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei gained 41.15 points to 19,231.08 at the end of
morning trading. In New York, the Nasdaq on Monday fell 141.38 to close at
4,907.24, its fourth-worst point drop ever. The Dow rose 18.31 to 9,947.13,
reversing an early loss of 190.49.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jazz 87, Bulls 79
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Karl Malone and John Stockton, making their first appearances
at the United Center since the 1998 NBA Finals, led Utah's big third-quarter run
Monday night as the Jazz beat the punchless Chicago Bulls 87-79 for their eighth
straight win. Malone scored 31 points and had 13 rebounds, while his longtime
running mate Stockton added 19 points with six steals and nine assists. Elton
Brand led the Bulls with 26 points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Beat Nuggets 118-108
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers, coming off a narrow victory 24 hours
earlier, ran their winning streak to 19 games as they held off the Denver
Nuggets 118-108 Monday night. Shaquille O'Neal had 40 points, nine rebounds and
seven assists for the Lakers, whose run is the third-best in NBA history. Kobe
Bryant, coming off a career-high 40 points in Sunday's three-point win over
Sacramento, scored 22, and Glen Rice added 20 for Los Angeles.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
