<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Milford officer convicted of manslaughter in suspect's death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- Civil Rights leaders were closely
watching the murder trial of New Milford Police Officer Scott
Smith, a white police officer accused of killing an unarmed black
man.
</P>
<P>
   It came in the wake of highly publicized acquittals of New York
City police officers charged in the shooting death of African
immigrant Amadou Diallo, and the decision not to prosecute a white
Hartford police officer, Robert Allan, who killed a 14-year-old
black mugging suspect, Aquan Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a jury found Smith guilty of intentional manslaughter
for shooting Franklyn Reid in the back at point-blank range on Dec.
29, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Vann, the president of the state chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said he would
have preferred that Reid was convicted of murder. But he said the
guilty verdict should send a message to all police officers who
''needlessly take lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This verdict ought to be a cue to those involved to improve
the relationship between the community and police to open up a
dialogue about how things can change,'' said Vann.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 28, was the first Connecticut police officer to be
charged with murder for an action committed in the line of duty. He
said he fired the fatal shot because he believed Reid was reaching
for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, 27, was unarmed. A small folding knife was discovered in
the pocket of a jacket found a few feet away from Reid's body.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was shot once in the back. Prosecution witnesses testified
that they saw him sitting or lying on his stomach in surrender
moments before the shooting; an expert testified for prosecutors
that Smith's bootprint was present on Reid's shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Reid made a sudden motion at the belt line. ''When he
made that classic move, I thought 'Oh (expletive), I'm dead,''
Smith testified last week.
</P>
<P>
   Jury forewoman Mary Cranouski told The News Times of Danbury the
panel did not accept that Smith feared for his life, but did not
believe the shooting was premeditated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure he didn't get up in the morning and say he was going
to kill someone,'' Cranouski said. ''He made the wrong decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith shook his head ''no'' when the verdict was read, but made
no other comment. He left the courthouse with his family. He faces
from 5 years to 40 years in prison at his May 5 sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight and Pearlylyn Reid, who moved with their three sons from
Jamaica to New Milford in 1986, did not seek to make race the focus
of the case. They rejected an offer of assistance from the Rev. Al
Sharpton, the New York activist involved in the Diallo case.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they highlighted the number of police shootings in the
state. Between December 1998 and November 1999, nine people were
killed and a 10th wounded in police shootings in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a public execution,'' Mrs. Reid said after the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ''A trillion, trillion, trillion thanks to the jury, for your
courage to do the right thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen McGrady, a New Milford resident and the only black juror
told The News Times that race played no roll in their
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't brought up once,'' he said. ''That doesn't mean it
wasn't in the back of minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of Smith's lawyers, Superior Court Judge
Charles D. Gill had allowed the jury to consider the less serious
charges of intentional manslaughter and reckless manslaughter in
addition to murder.
</P>
<P>
   In the moments before the shooting, Reid -- who was well-known to
area police and wanted for failure to appear in court -- had led
Smith on a brief foot chase.
</P>
<P>
   Reid had also eluded another officer earlier in the day,
witnesses testified.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's partner testified that he was in the car at the time
of the shooting and did not see what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors began considering the case on Thursday, deliberating
about 2{ hours that day and all day on Friday. The verdict was
returned about 4 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Smith initially brought protests from
hundreds of police officers, who denounced Waterbury State's
Attorney John Connelly as a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a police officer and a young man was killed -- this
was a difficult case for everyone involved,'' Connelly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
