<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Son of Sam Sheppard testifies for Ross in death penalty hearing  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- The son of a famous murder victim says
serial killer Michael Ross is worth more to society alive than
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of murder victims and psychological experts can use
lives such as Ross' to better understand what makes people kill,
said Sam Reese Sheppard, the son of Marylin and Dr. Sam Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   His father was convicted -- and later acquitted -- in the 1954
beating death of his mother, a case that inspired ''The Fugitive''
television show.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard, who was 7 at the time of his mother's death, met Ross
and corresponded with him for about two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The effect of knowing Mr. Ross has been profound on my life,''
Sheppard testified Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He said that executing convicted killers is inhumane and would
be ''literally killing resources.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the information he got from Ross ''has helped me put the
pieces together of the shattered experience of losing my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers are trying to show why Ross should be spared the
death penalty for killing four teen-age girls in eastern
Connecticut in the 1980s. An earlier death sentence was overturned
on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Ross already is serving two life sentences for killing two other
young women in Windham County. He has confessed to killing two
women in New York state but has not been prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Sheppard is currently suing the state of Ohio,
seeking a formal declaration of his father's innocence and
compensation for the time the elder Sheppard spent in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Monsignor John Gilmartin of Long Island, N.Y.,
testified that Ross is truly sorry for his crimes and feels badly
that the relatives of his victims must go through the anguish of
another court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Ross was baptized Roman Catholic as a child and was confirmed in
prison. Gilmartin is Ross' spiritual advisor.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmartin arranged for an article Ross wrote about the death
penalty to be published in a Catholic Charities magazine -- an
article Gilmartin said he has used in his work since.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Barry Butler asked whether the religious
conversion was genuine or a ''rent-a-Bible'' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really felt Michael was growing spiritually, in a really
deep and significant way,'' Gilmartin said.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, State's Attorney Kevin Kane asked if
Gilmartin found it presumptuous that Ross tried to decide what was
best for his victims' families when he signed an agreement to be
executed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he did it out of sensitivity to the families,''
Gilmartin replied.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was thrown out by a judge, who ordered the new
penalty hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The defense played for the jury a tape of Ross' speech to the
court in February 1998, the day he and former prosecutor Robert
Satti signed the execution agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Ross' voice was choked with emotion at times as he
tried to explain why he tried to sign his life away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm so sorry. I know those words don't mean much,'' he said on
the tape. ''I wish I could bring back the women I killed. I wish I
could trade my life for them.''
</P>
<P>
   As the tape was played, Ross wiped his eyes and face and sniffed
softly.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Shelley, the father of one of the victims, testified the
first day of the trial and stands vigil in the courthouse corridor,
wearing a button with his 14-year-old daughter's face on it.
</P>
<P>
   Because Shelley is a witness, he is barred from the courtroom
and is not allowed to speak with the media about his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Judge Thomas Miano warned Shelley not to speak with
the media. Last week Shelley was quoted in a newspaper interview
and wrote a letter to the editor of another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
