<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton speaks to Irish group -- again  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Irish America magazine's annual award
celebration gave Hillary Rodham Clinton an opportunity to praise an
old friend while courting an important voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady presented Britain's former Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam with the magazine's Peace Award. Clinton called
Mowlam a good, reassuring friend who worked for a safe resolution
in Northern Ireland. She said Mowlam's efforts included making
women's voices stronger in the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday night's event honoring the top 100 Irish-Americans
of 2000, the Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate seat in New
York promised to support those who have fought, died ''and, yes,
voted'' for peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people in the room have worked for a lifetime to make
hope and history rhyme,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration also showed there's one constituency in New York
that no one can accuse Clinton of ignoring: Irish-Americans. In
December, she spoke at a dinner sponsored by Irish America magazine
honoring the top 100 Irish-Americans of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's publisher, Niall O'Dowd, founded Irish-Americans
for Clinton in 1991 and said he was happy to help Clinton increase
her visibility among voters of Irish extraction because both
Clintons have been such strong supporters of the Irish peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Clintons, O'Dowd said, ''No president or first lady
ever particularly cared about this issue. She's the first first
lady to ever go to Northern Ireland, she knows the issue extremely
well, and she deserves a tremendous amount of credit for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's 100 honorees included several individuals who
have to go back generations to pinpoint their Irish ancestors --
among them, Vice President Al Gore and President Clinton, who has
said his mother was descended from an 18th-century Northern Irish
farming family. Neither man attended the event.
</P>
<P>
   The list also included several members of the Kennedy family,
including Sen. Ted Kennedy, filmmaker Rory Kennedy and Ambassador
Jean Kennedy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's involvement with Irish issues gives her an in
with a large segment of Catholic voters. Catholics made up 45
percent of New York voters in 1998 and 1996 elections but are a
group Clinton will have to work to court. She supports abortion
rights and opposes school vouchers and is running against a
Catholic opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Irish America magazine has a circulation of about 100,000 and is
published six times a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 0114 </TRAILER>
