<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Farmers Won't Accept Limits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) -- Ed Geest plans to be farming, on the same
land where he grew up, when he's 90.
</P>
<P>
   He's 64 now, just shy of the average age of an Iowa farmer. That
aging population has created new concerns for farm safety
officials.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study released by Iowa's Center for Agriculture
Safety and Health, older farmers often are unwilling to recognize
or accept their physical limitations. Daily farming can pose
enormous risks to those with arthritis, limited vision and hearing,
depression and other conditions associated with age.
</P>
<P>
   Geest, who farms in Blue Grass just west of the Quad Cities, has
been fortunate in his more than 40 years of farming. The worst of
his injuries has been a cut leg after a fall from a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   But he's had to change how he goes about things as he gets
older.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's pretty obvious I'm not as agile as I used to be. I still
might run around on the barn roof, but I hang on more than I used
to,'' he said. ''I wouldn't jump from one barn to another. I used
to do that stuff. I wouldn't do it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That realization that with age comes limits is key to safety,
said Tracy Keninger, from Easter Seals of Iowa. She is working with
the Iowa Center for Agriculture Safety and Health and is chairwoman
of a task force on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''This means we need to heighten awareness among farmers of the
risks in farming as they grow older,'' she said. ''They need to
learn what adjustments they may need to make, such as changes in
equipment they use or certain behaviors.''
</P>
<P>
   Depression is also common among the aging farmer -- especially
because of the current economic downturn in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Katey Geest, Ed's wife, said she understands the risks of
farming -- which are exacerbated by the 12- to 14-hour day,
seven-day-a-week schedule that her husband and son, Dieter, work to
keep up with the family's 500-acre soybean, corn and hog farm.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very dangerous. We've been lucky,'' she said. ''I pray a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ABERDEEN, S.D. (AP) -- Don Roehr doesn't like the thought of
applying more chemicals to his crops, but that may be a cheaper
alternative this year, given the high cost of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   It takes only one pass through the field to apply chemicals.
Cultivating row crops means repeated trips that burn up fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Premium diesel fuel cost $1.08 per gallon last week for bulk
delivery to farms, compared to about 70 cents a year ago, said Ed
Stauch, petroleum manager for South Dakota Wheat Growers' northern
division.
</P>
<P>
   A big tractor that's tilling uses easily 180 gallons of fuel
daily, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to do everything without chemicals,'' said Roehr, a
Britton-area farmer. ''But this year I'm going the lazy man's way --
the chemical way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stauch said that even an immediate increase in petroleum
production would be too late to lower prices for spring planting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe by May,'' he said. ''But it's all up in the air. OPEC is
really going to be the one to decide all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Most farmers did not fill their bulk tanks before prices rose,
he said. ''They were waiting for the price to drop. My inkling is
that a lot of tanks out there are not full. It's one of those deals
where hindsight is better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
