<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge finds U.S. law extends to foreigners who attack Americansabroad  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge sided with prosecutors in ruling
that the U.S. government did not reach beyond its authority when it
charged Osama bin Laden and 16 others in the bombing of two U.S.
embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for six men charged in the case had argued that U.S.
Attorney Mary Jo White sought an unprecedented expansion of federal
jurisdiction over crimes committed on foreign soil.
</P>
<P>
   The men are accused of conspiring to attack Americans in the
Aug. 7, 1998, bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. The
attacks killed 224 people, including 12 Americans. Six men are in
custody in the United States and three abroad, and the rest are
fugitives.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand said it would make little sense
to restrict enforcement of U.S. laws overseas to suspects who are
U.S. citizens or lawful residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find it difficult to conceive of Congress saying we want to
protect our interests abroad against attacks by Americans but not
against attacks by non-Americans,'' the judge said two weeks ago
during a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling Monday, the judge wrote that ''foreign nationals
are in at least as good a position as are United States nationals
to carry out such attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a law written to prosecute anyone who conspires to use a
weapon of mass destruction against a U.S. resident or citizen
outside the United States ''unambiguously applied to offenders who
are foreign nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors dismissed the arguments made by lawyers for Mohamed
Sadeek Odeh, a 34-year-old furniture salesman charged in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''Odeh cannot be surprised to learn that his conduct was
criminal under the laws of every civilized nation, and (thus) he
has no right to complain about the particular forum in which he is
brought to trial,'' they argued.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Odeh did not immediately return a telephone call
for comment on the ruling. Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for the U.S.
attorney, said he had no comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
