<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Men Out of Touch With Health Care  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gil Purisch never went to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his life, the New York City optician would only have
physicals or checkups if it was required for his work or insurance.
Purisch, 55, said he was the kind of man ''who wouldn't go to the
dentist unless my tooth hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Then 10 years ago his vision started to fail and his feet began
to swell, signs of diabetes. Even then he just lived with his
illness until his sister forced him to get medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''After a year's worth of symptoms I was still regarding it like
it would just go away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many men have similar stories, and an independent survey,
confirming what frustrated wives and mothers long have known, finds
that far too often men fail to seek out health care until it's too
late.
</P>
<P>
   ''Society's demand that men be strong and stoic can be harmful
to their health if it causes them to ignore what their bodies are
telling them and avoid seeking needed medical care,'' said David
Sandman, lead author of the study sponsored by The Commonwealth
Fund, a philanthropic foundation that promotes health awareness.
</P>
<P>
   The life spans of both sexes have increased dramatically in the
past century, but men, who once lived just as long as women, now
die on average six years earlier. Men are far more likely to
experience deaths related to violence, but other leading causes of
male death like heart disease and certain cancers can be treated if
caught early.
</P>
<P>
   The survey released Monday found that in the past year a quarter
of men had not seen a doctor and more than half had not had a
physical exam or a cholesterol test. More than a third of men over
50 had not been tested in the past five years for colon cancer or
prostate cancer, potentially fatal diseases that require early
detection for successful treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''You got a boy when he's 8 years old being told 'big boys don't
cry' when he skins his knee -- when he's 50 and he's got chest pains
he says it's just indigestion, '' said Dr. Jean Bonhomme, an
Atlanta physician who works with the Men's Health Network, a
national group that advises on male health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Since most women visit gynecologists or obstetricians, they have
regular exposure to health care throughout their lives, something
that men lack, Bonhomme said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the things that keeps men out of the health care system
is that there's nothing with a male face on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But getting men into doctor's offices doesn't solve all their
problems. Men in the study rated their doctors highly overall, but
few said they received counseling on ways to improve their health
or to prevent illness or injury. While men with a family history of
prostate cancer are at greater risk for contracting the disease,
less than a third of men over 40 said their doctors had ever asked
them about their family's medical history.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sensitizing physicians to male health concerns could bring
about improvements in men's longevity and well-being,'' Sandman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey of more than 1,000 men and 2,000 women was
conducted from May to November 1998. The margin of error was plus
or minus 4 percentage points for the men and 3 percentage points
for the women.
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth Fund, a nonprofit foundation established in
1918 that received the assets of the James Picker Foundation in
1986, promotes better health behavior for minorities, older people
and children.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that men with low incomes or no health
insurance were even less likely to see doctors,
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Miller, 42, a free-lance writer and single father from
Vienna, Va., said he insists on good care for his 12-year-old son,
but he often just lives with his own bouts of pain and illness
because he has no insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can feel in my body that there are things wrong, but I don't
dare go to the doctor because of the expense involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that even if he could afford it, he and many men
only get medical help when money or a job is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ''You go to the doctor to get fixed so you can go back to work
again,'' he said. ''You don't go to the doctor because you want to
take care of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Department of Health and Human Service's men's
health information page:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.healthfinder.gov/justforyou/men
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 0142 </TRAILER>
