<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Want To Be Reformers  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore says he's learned from
his campaign finance mistakes and wants to rid the nation of
big-money politics. George W. Bush calls himself a ''reformer with
results.'' Pat Buchanan insists he is the truest reformer of all.
</P>
<P>
   Without John McCain and Bill Bradley, where do reform-minded
voters turn?
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nobody,'' says John Longmire, the Reform Party's
Kentucky chairman. ''Every time you turn around these days,
somebody's claiming to be a reformer. It's enough to make you want
to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Warren Rudman of New Hampshire, McCain's national
co-chairman, says attracting such independent-minded voters won't
''be terribly easy for anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the ''R-word'' is a minefield for all three
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's and Bush's finances in particular raise the issue of
credibility, while Buchanan's focus on cultural and social changes
has led members of both parties to brand his call for reform as
extremist.
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury's recent conviction of Maria Hsia, a Gore friend
a political supporter, for arranging more than $100,000 in illegal
donations during the 1996 campaign resurrects Gore's questionable
attendance at a fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says the public doesn't have ''amnesia'' about the episode
and alludes to it on the stump.
</P>
<P>
   The reform mantle is a risk for Bush as well. He declined
federal subsidies for the primary campaign, which freed him from
federal limits on campaign spending. He then went on to set a new
fund-raising record by raking in more than $73 million.
</P>
<P>
   And some Republicans cringed upon learning that two Texas
businessmen and supporters of Bush financed $2.5 million in TV ads
criticizing McCain's environmental record and touting Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was not good,'' acknowledged Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.,
who had endorsed McCain but announced Sunday -- days after McCain
pulled out of the race -- that he is supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a reform advocate who chaired Senate hearings into the
fund-raising abuses of the Clinton-Gore re-election campaign,
nonetheless recommended that Bush focus on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we ought to spend all our time talking about
Gore's fund-raising,'' Thompson said. ''We're not going to win if
that's all we talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sidelines, the Reform Party is somewhat amused.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody's getting a great chuckle out of them,'' said
Russell Verney, the party's former chairman and top aide to Ross
Perot, who founded the party on a vision of campaigns run without
the influence of large, unregulated contributions to the political
parties, known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who is seeking the party's presidential nomination,
would push for vast political and social change, from scrapping
free trade pacts to banning abortion. Party Chairman Pat Choate,
Perot's 1996 running mate, said Buchanan will soften his rhetoric,
especially on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he has learned from his mistakes and now wants to
overhaul the very system that allowed money to be raised in
questionable ways. He also has challenged Bush, the Texas governor,
to give up campaign ads in favor of regular debates. Bush has
refused.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush favors faster, more complete disclosure of
campaign donors on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man is willing to forgo their parties' soft money
operations in the upcoming election, though each supports
legislating such bans for future campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bush say he is reaching out for McCain's support and
may end up adopting some of the Arizona senator's campaign finance
legislation as part of his own agenda, or support it becoming part
of the GOP platform at the national convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and the lawmakers who backed his challenge to Bush have
indicated they ultimately will back the Texas governor in spite of
seemingly limitless fund raising. Thompson said Bush ''has not been
a part of an operation that turned out in many respects to have a
lot of people engaged in illegal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley, who both campaigned as reformers, both
pulled out of the race last week.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Bush campaign site: http://www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign site: http://www.gore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan campaign site: http://www.buchananreform.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 0204 </TRAILER>
