<DOCNO> APW20000314.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Puerto Rico's Publico Faces Threat  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGUAS BUENAS, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Under an early morning sky,
Miguel Molina rolls his 1979 Ford van into the main square of this
mountain town and waits. Passengers come, dropping 60 cents into
his hand and squeezing inside, until Molina thinks he has made a
small profit.
</P>
<P>
   A slam of the door, a cough of the engine, and a breakneck dive
into the darkness begins. The rattling Ford swerves around slower
traffic to the bleats of Molina's horn, bleary-eyed passengers
bracing against doors and windows to keep steady on vinyl seats as
Molina tears through another red light.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the hill, it's another wait to fill up the
''publico'' -- Puerto Rico's once-ubiquitous, declining but still
beloved brand of public transport.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot of work and not much pay,'' Molina sighed. ''But
the customers know me, and I'm providing them a good service.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicos were once a staple of life on the island, and they are
still prized by many as an emblem of more patient, rustic times.
But things are changing in this U.S. territory, which has rapidly
developed since the 1950s and is now packed with new cars and
highways and offers commuters sleek, air-conditioned buses.
</P>
<P>
   The number of publicos in operation has declined by 20 percent
in the 1990s, according to the island's Public Service Commission --
but some 10,000 remain.
</P>
<P>
   Lovingly maintained and often adorned with good luck charms,
hand-painted slogans and statuettes of the Virgin Mary, they run
along set routes at rates fixed by the government -- never departing
until the driver has collected enough.
</P>
<P>
   The system began in 1907, when entrepreneurs launched a route
between the capital, San Juan, and the mountain town of Caguas.
</P>
<P>
   It intrigued the U.S. government, which helped build more than
100 publico terminals and commissioned a study in 1986 on applying
the concept in the mainland United States. The result, said Alex
McNeil, an administrator at the Federal Transit Administration, was
the ''vanpool'' concept in cities like Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''What they have down there is really a fabulous system,'' said
McNeil. ''It doesn't cost the taxpayers anything, which is
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   It costs passengers little too: $2.50 pays for the 40-mile ride
from the bustling capital to the town of Humacao on the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   But the system has its disadvantages: crowded seats, no
air-conditioning and long waits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm always getting to class late,'' said Betzaida Vegas, 20,
who rides publicos to her university every day.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Juan area, home to half of Puerto Rico's 4 million
people, publicos are losing business to a bus system that has
introduced private contractors, streamlined routes and added new
buses with federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, people are increasingly driving themselves. The
island now has 146 automobiles per mile of road -- three times
higher than in the U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, one of every ten trips taken by travelers in San Juan
was by publico; that has fallen to 3.5 percent of trips in 1990,
according to official figures. Drivers say usage has declined
considerably since.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in absence of an island-wide train system or good
mass transit systems in other cities, publicos still carry 40
percent of the public transport traffic in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The ranks of the drivers -- who earn between $35 and $60 a day --
are thinning, and aging.
</P>
<P>
   Carmelo Otero, 56, is reminded of the changing times every day
as he parks his publico in his traditional spot at San Juan's Plaza
del Carmen.
</P>
<P>
   A giant earth-eating machine recently punched a new subway
tunnel underneath the square where hundreds of publicos gather.
Otero fears the $1.5 billion Urban Train, due to open next year,
may be the coup de grace.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he said, ''we still manage to survive ... but it's
getting harder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 0209 </TRAILER>
