<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Plane Makes Emergency Landing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A Delta Air Lines flight bound from San
Francisco to Salt Lake City made an emergency landing Monday
evening after experiencing problems with its landing gear,
according to an airport spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 727-200 landed without any injuries to the 77
passengers, although the pilots could not use their right landing
gear, said airport spokeswoman Kim Dickie. Emergency crews were
waiting for the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot informed the passengers of the landing gear problems
soon after takeoff. The plane then circled the airport for an hour
and dumped fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was so silent on the plane, except for a baby crying, which
made us mothers even more tense,'' passenger Jane Vaughn of Utah
told KTVU-TV in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane landed, its right wing dragged on the runway and
broke. Passengers exited by an inflatable slide.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seemed like an eternity from the time we went to the braced
position until the time we finally touched the ground. And as we
touched the ground, we could hear the wings dragging along the
ground,'' said Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Some planes bound for San Francisco were routed instead to
Oakland or San Jose because the runway where the emergency landing
took place was temporarily closed.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1972 was scheduled to leave at 6:35 p.m. and arrive in
Salt Lake at 9:08 p.m. It was then scheduled to travel on to
Kalispell, Mont., arriving 11:45 p.m. The flight landed back in San
Francisco at 8:01 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 0217 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000314.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oscar Season Continues With Lunch  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- There were no winners or losers at
the annual Oscar nominees luncheon. Those distinctions are two
weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   Collegiality ruled Monday among contenders for honors at the
72nd annual Oscars, to be presented March 26. In the interview room
before lunch, actors and directors echoed the theme.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Oscars are not really a competition,'' commented Haley
Joel Osment, the 11-year-old nominee for Best Supporting Actor in
the ''Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It isn't a competition,'' said Michael Mann, nominated for
directing ''The Insider.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The stiffest competition is to make the picture. If you're
attracted to this work with awards in mind, you wouldn't last one
week of photography,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't call it a competition,'' insisted Denzel Washington,
named for best actor in ''The Hurricane.'' ''People do the best
they can. And a lot of the actors this year have done good work.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left the room, Washington was asked if he was rooting for
anyone. ''Yes,'' he replied with an enigmatic smile.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the 20 acting nominees and four of the five
directors, along with 80 other achievers mounted a row of bleachers
for the ''class picture.'' All stood while the photo was taken a
dozen times for safety's sake.
</P>
<P>
   An endearing scene appeared at the middle of the front row. It
was Richard Farnsworth, the 79-year-old nominee as Best Actor for
''The Straight Story,'' who fondly held his hands on the shoulders
of the diminutive Haley Joel.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon ended with the usual warning.
</P>
<P>
   The show's producers Richard and Lily Zanuck instructed the
nominees that if they should be lucky enough to win, please avoid
filibusters as acceptance speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences:
http://www.oscars.com
</P>
</TEXT>
