<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Release China Trade Text  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supporters of legislation to implement an
accord opening trade barriers between China and the United States
are hoping the law will be easier to sell with release of the text
of the landmark agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the document's text would be sent
today to each member of Congress and released to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William Daley, the administration's point man
on the lobbying effort, said Monday that once people examine the
fine print, ''They will see a very positive deal'' for American
exporters.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to release the text, reported by officials who
spoke on condition of anonymity, represents a turnabout for the
Clinton administration. It has insisted the deal could not be made
public because China is negotiating with Europe and other countries
over terms under which it will enter the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the agreement between the United States and China, reached in
November, China agreed to remove, in return for U.S. support of its
membership in the WTO, barriers that American exporters have long
complained are keeping billions of dollars' worth of their products
out of the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   But under WTO rules, Congress must scrap its annual review of
China's trade status and grant it permanent normal trade relations
in order for U.S. exporters to receive the trade benefits China is
offering. Permanent normal trade relations status, formerly known
as most-favored-nation status, is enjoyed by almost all countries
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the November agreement has been available to members
of the House and Senate and staff members with appropriate security
clearances for reading in secure reading rooms. But lawmakers
complained the secrecy was difficult to justify to their
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have insisted that all the agreement's
details were released in November when the deal was announced, even
though the exact text of the document was withheld. But opponents
in the labor and environmental movements have said the public
deserved the right to examine the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   A major business group said Monday that release of the full text
will make their lobbying job in support of the agreement easier.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the general public will be able to see what a terrific
deal this is for America. The text of the agreement contains page
after page of concessions that will improve our access to China's
huge market,'' said Calman J. Cohen, co-chairman of the Business
Coalition for U.S.-China Trade, an umbrella lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents insist, however, that Congress will make a big mistake
if it ends the annual congressional review. To do so would
surrender leverage the United States has to force China to improve
its human-rights record, opponents say.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, speaking to reporters, said the administration still
faces an uphill battle in the House, where strong opposition from
labor unions is making it difficult for President Clinton to
attract Democratic votes.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley said he believes momentum on the issue is beginning to
shift. Daley and Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman will lead
delegations of undecided lawmakers on trips to China next month.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said Republican leaders need to schedule votes in both the
House and Senate so the matter can be decided before the end of
May. Delays past that time, he said, would make it much harder to
win passage because the issue would become embroiled in fall
election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Daley conceded that China's recent belligerent statements
regarding Taiwan, which it considers a renegade province, are not
helping in the lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   He said government leaders in Beijing are ''very capable of
doing something very stupid'' that could cost important votes in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Daley stressed that Clinton is working hard to round up votes
for what the administration has called its biggest remaining
foreign policy objective.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Dennis Hastert said in a separate appearance
Monday the agreement has the backing of the ''Republican leadership
and a large majority of Republicans'' in the House. He said if
Democratic support was as weak as had been reported, ''I cannot
solve this problem for the president.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to boost bipartisan support, the administration
released a letter from six former secretaries of state saying
permanent normal trade relations with China and China's membership
in the WTO are ''critically important tools'' for moving China to a
more open society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 0220 </TRAILER>
