<DOCNO> APW20000314.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scott Smith trial jurors say they didn't believe officer feared forhis life  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW MILFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The jury in New Milford police officer
Scott Smith's murder trial didn't buy the officer's story that he
feared for his life when he shot and killed an unarmed black
suspect, The News Times of Danbury reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Allen McGrady, a New Milford resident and the only black juror,
and jury forewoman Mary Cranouski of Barkhamsted told the paper the
evidence was clear that Franklyn Reid did not pose a threat to
Smith when he was shot in the back on the afternoon of Dec. 29,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   McGrady and Cranouski said they were strongly influenced by
testimony from the motorists who witnessed the episode because they
didn't know each other and had no stake in the outcome, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Although police officers at the scene said they didn't witness
the shooting, prosecutor John Connelly called numerous civilian
witnesses who testified Reid appeared to have surrendered. Early in
their deliberations, the jurors asked to rehear testimony from
eight civilians who were either driving by or were in a nearby gas
station as the episode unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   The two jurors told the News Times that the panel pieced
together a picture of the shooting that didn't fit with Smith's
account.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you have all the framework in the film that seems to follow
sequence, and then you hit a blip in one of the frames that doesn't
fit anything, then you have to make a decision to credit it or
discredit it,'' McGrady said. ''That's what we did with Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of convicting Smith of murder, jurors chose a lesser
charge of first-degree manslaughter with a firearm. The two jurors
said it was the best fit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure he didn't get up in the morning and say he was going
to kill someone. He made the wrong decision,'' Cranouski said.
</P>
<P>
   There were some aspects of the deliberations that both Cranouski
and McGrady declined to discuss. They refused to say whether jurors
took any votes on the murder charge, or whether there was a
straight-up vote to acquit Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Both jurors they labored over their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do respect police, but we had to make a decision based on
the evidence we had,'' McGrady said. ''I feel for Scott and his
family. I feel for the Reids and I feel for Franklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel for both sides. One lost a child, and now the other
has,'' Cranouski said. ''It was a tough decision. ''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors also said they never discussed whether the shooting
was a racial incident, although Smith is white and Reid was black.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't brought up once,'' McGrady said. ''That doesn't mean
it wasn't in the back of minds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
