</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Three Japanese banks -- Sanwa, Tokai and Asahi -- announced a
merger on Tuesday to create the world's third-largest bank, further
consolidating the country's recovering financial industry. The three banks said
they will set up a joint holding company in April 2001, under which they will
''swiftly'' reorganize their retail, wholesale, international, computer systems
and other operations. They will have combined assets of $1 trillion to become
the second-largest Japanese bank, and the third-largest in the world.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Finland Marks Post Winter War Peace
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Finns on Monday marked the 60th anniversary of a
truce that followed 105 days of fierce fighting against Stalin's Red Army in the
Winter War, possibly one of the coldest in history. Finland lost, but the small
country's resistance against the Soviets helped secure its independence in
post-war Europe. Some 23,000 Finnish soldiers were killed, and 45,000 wounded,
in a population of 3.7 million. But Finland's white-clad troops on skis, which
became famous as the ''ghost army,'' proved a stronger force than expected. The
Soviet Union put its losses at 217,500 dead or wounded, but Finland estimated
enemy casualties at up to 400,000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 48.09 points to close at 19,141.84. 
</P>
