<HEADLINE> GOP Plans Senior Prescription Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republicans are preparing a plan
to allocate $40 billion to help low-income elderly people pay for
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is simply unacceptable that 13 million seniors do not have
prescription drug coverage,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla.,
chairman of the House Republican Conference. ''Republicans are
committed to helping these most vulnerable seniors, offering a plan
to get prescription drugs to them while, at the same time,
preparing Medicare for the next generation of retirees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal announced Monday would cost about the
same as President Clinton's plan, whose price tag is an estimated
$35 billion over five years and $149 billion over the next decade.
The administration's plan also includes an additional $35 billion
in its final five years to help seniors with catastrophic drug
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president wants to create a big-government health system
that offers no competition or options for individual states,''
Watts said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, who are drafting their budget for next year,
still have to work out the details of their proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
