<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   ''Tanglewood Tree'' (Signature Sounds) -- Dave Carter
and Tracy
Grammer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Tanglewood Tree'' is simply brilliant, a skyrocket of an album
that should establish this Oregon duo as stars, at least in the
firmament of contemporary folk. Dave Carter's songwriting embraces
the mythic, the metaphoric and the surreal. He writes songs that
can stand with the best of contemporary singer-songwriters or sound
like they were written 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Carter's songs ring like tales from the past. ''Hey
Conductor'' could have been on a Merle Travis record, and ''Cat-Eye
Willie Comes to Claim His Lover'' sounds like it was written by
some muleskinner-poet 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carter writes more standard singer-songwriter material, as well,
such as ''Walkin' Away From Caroline,'' a vivid and heartbreaking
slice of a conversation between a couple breaking up.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Grammer's instrumental prowess and lovely voice (she
handles lead vocals on four songs as well as singing harmony) and
Carter's songwriting combine to make this album great.
</P>
<P>
   -- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ''Wandering Moon'' (Sony Classical) -- Terence Blanchard
</P>
<P>
   Terence Blanchard's new disc captures the ear from the opening
bars, when a languid counterpoint pairs a piano/bass line against
three bluesy horns playing in harmony to create a captivating mood.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what follows is just as good, showing that while
Blanchard has been hailed as a composer and orchestrator, leading a
small jazz group may be what he does best. On ''Wandering Moon,''
the New Orleans trumpeter has stellar help from his touring group
and such guests as saxman Branford Marsalis and bassist Dave
Holland, and Blanchard is generous in sharing the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   His eight compositions include tributes to trumpeter Harry
''Sweets'' Edison, who died last year, and to jazz legend Sidney
Bechet. The quality of the set dips only on ''If I Could, I
Would,'' which flirts with free form and isn't for the faint of
heart. But there are also plenty of highlights, capped by a
beautiful rendition of the Johnny Mercer/Jimmy Van Heusen ballad
''I Thought About You.''
</P>
<P>
   -- By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ''Trio 99-00'' (Warner Bros.) -- Pat Metheny
</P>
<P>
   Pat Metheny plays the kind of jazz that people who don't like
jazz like.
</P>
<P>
   Is that a compliment? Not necessarily. The talented guitarist is
prolific to a fault, and the quality of his catalog would be higher
if his output were lower. But when Metheny is good, he's terrific,
and that's the case on ''Trio 99-00.''
</P>
<P>
   Metheny teamed up with bassist Dave Holland and drummer Roy
Haynes to record 11 tunes in just two days, and the group meshed
beautifully. Metheny can sometimes be guilty of New Age noodling,
but here every note he plays has a purpose as he shows off a
remarkable vocabulary on both electric and acoustic guitar. His
playing is impressively fast on the opening ''(Go) Get It,''
playful on ''Soul Cowboy,'' and just plain lovely on ''Just Like
The Day'' and the closing ''Travels.'' He finds a Latin groove by
slowing the tempo on John Coltrane's ''Giant Steps'' and makes the
most of the Wayne Shorter standard ''Capricorn.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland and Haynes are terrific, too, and deserve credit for
bringing out the best in Metheny. Even people who do like jazz can
applaud ''Trio 99-00.''
</P>
<P>
   -- By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 0820 </TRAILER>
