<HEADLINE> Giuliani blames Clinton administration for rising gas prices  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.Y. (AP) -- New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani blamed
the Clinton administration for the high cost of gasoline, saying,
''their failure to act has caused this crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This administration is napping, hibernating, asleep,
unfocused, whatever you want to call it, with regard to what's
going on with gasoline,'' said Giuliani, a Republican candidate for
the U.S. Senate running against Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spoke Monday at a gas station in the affluent
Westchester County community of Bedford, where the prices marked at
the full-service island were $2.03.9 a gallon for regular gasoline,
$2.13.9 for medium and $2.23.9 for premium.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can say, 'Thank you, President Clinton, thank you, Vice
President Al Gore and thank you, (U.S. Energy Secretary) Bill
Richardson for these prices,''' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani called for a repeal of the 1993 federal gas tax
increase and said he supported State Senate Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno's proposal to eliminate the 4 percent state sales tax on
gasoline on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices were as low as 85 cents a gallon last year in some
parts of the country and have since risen to an average of $1.59 a
gallon, according to the Lundberg Survey of 10,000 stations.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the increase was a March 1999 decision by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to reduce production
as a means of driving up prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
