<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 82; Dow Gains 19  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mostly higher in early trading on
Wall Street on Tuesday as technology shares bounced back from their
single-day decline and financial stocks led blue-chip issues
higher.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average
was up 19.46 at 9,966.59.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 82.12 at 4,989.36, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 5.50 at 1,389.12.
</P>
<P>
   After sending technology stocks down sharply on Monday,
investors returned to buy shares of the companies that have led the
market all year. Oracle rose 3} to 82{, Applied Materials rose 2[
to 190 1/16 and Biogen rose 3[ to 83\.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which lists most of the world's leading technology
companies, tumbled 141 points on Monday as investors collected
profits from the sector's continuing rally. The Nasdaq is up more
than 21 percent since the start of 2000, while the Dow and the
broader S&AMP;P 500 are down for the year to date.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, investors have determined that technology
companies, with their rapid growth, are best prepared to thrive if
the Federal Reserve continues raising interest rates this year. The
Fed has raised interest rates four times since June in an effort to
slow the economy to a more sustainable pace.
</P>
<P>
   The latest evidence that higher rates haven't yet slowed the
economy came today from the Commerce Department, which reported
that retail sales rose by 1.1 percent in February. With Americans
continuing to spend freely, feeding the surging economy, many
analysts expect the Fed will raise rates again when they meet next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates can be bad for financial stocks, but today, those
issues led the Dow's advance. J.P. Morgan rose 1 3/16 to 113 3/16
after saying Monday that business has been robust in the first two
months of the year. American Express rose 1 11/16 to 128\.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 169.44 million
shares, ahead of Monday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 9.11 to 599.25.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.3 percent,
narrowing its losses from Monday, when it fell 2.8 percent on the
news that the nation's gross domestic product declined for a second
consecutive quarter. The report, which meant Japan's economy is
officially back in recession, unsettled markets around the world on
Monday and contributed to weakness on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.6 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
