<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 82.12; Dow Gains 45.91  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mostly higher on Wall Street today
as technology shares bounced back from Monday's steep decline and
financial stocks led blue-chip issues higher.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
45.91 at 9,947.13.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 82.12 at 4,989.36, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 5.50 at 1,389.12.
</P>
<P>
   After sending technology stocks down sharply on Monday,
investors returned to buy shares of the companies that have led the
market all year. Oracle rose 3 to 81}, Applied Materials rose 2 to
189 15/16 and Biogen rose 3 5/16 to 83 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   BroadVision rose 8 1/32 to 84 17/32.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just as fast as people were selling tech stocks yesterday,
they're buying them today,'' said Don Selkin, chief investment
strategist at Joseph Gunnar in New York. ''The growth prospects for
many of these companies are so strong. I think that's the place to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which lists most of the world's leading technology
companies, tumbled 141 points on Monday as investors collected
profits from the sector's continuing rally. The Nasdaq is up more
than 21 percent since the start of 2000, while the Dow and the
broader S&AMP;P 500 are down for the year to date.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were not significantly affected by the latest evidence
that the economy continues to grow rapidly. The Commerce Department
reported today that retail sales rose by 1.1 percent in February.
With Americans continuing to spend freely, feeding the surging
economy, many analysts expect the Federal Reserve will raise
interest rates when they meet next week.
</P>
<P>
   An increase at the March 21 meeting would be the fifth since
last June. Higher rates tend to be particularly damaging to
financial stocks, but today, those issues led the Dow's advance.
J.P. Morgan rose 1 13/16 to 113 13/16 after saying Monday that
business has been robust in the first two months of the year.
American Express rose 3 9/16 to 130[.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 353.12 million
shares, ahead of Monday's moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.51 to 595.65.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.3 percent,
narrowing its losses from Monday, when it fell 2.8 percent on the
news that the nation's gross domestic product declined for a second
consecutive quarter. The report, which meant Japan's economy is
officially back in recession, unsettled markets around the world on
Monday and contributed to weakness on Wall Street.
</P>
