<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impasse over, land claim negotiations to resume  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Confusion led to a breakdown in
negotiations in the Oneida Indian Nation land claim. Now that the
confusion is cleared up, a court-appointed mediator said a
settlement could be just around the corner in the decades-old
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Settlement Master Ronald Riccio said Tuesday the parties were
''90 percent of the way home'' and could reach a settlement within
weeks once they return to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of the extraneous issues that were sidetracking us are
off the table. What's left are only the issues germane to the land
claim,'' said Riccio, a Seton Hall University law professor
assigned last year to mediate the 26-year-old dispute.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Neal McCurn called an impasse in
negotiations on Friday after state officials refused to sign a
letter to extend the talks until April 30. It appeared that the
claim was headed back to court for what promised to be years and
years of legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Riccio said the state's refusal resulted from confusion about
the stipulation letter. Riccio spent Monday on the telephone and
resolved the misunderstanding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hated to see it fall apart on a mistake,'' Riccio said. ''If
we can't agree on an issue, and it falls apart, that's one thing.
But it shouldn't fall apart based on confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Settlement talks over the past year under Riccio's guidance have
produced significant progress, according to the parties involved.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a huge disappointment to see all that hard work go down
the drain,'' said Madison County Supervisor Harry Hatton, chairman
of the county's Native American Affairs committee. ''We are so
close to a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue was a lawsuit filed in 1995 by the state against the
Oneidas over slot-like video gaming machines at the nation's
Turning Stone casino in Verona.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Friday to state officials that the extension
agreement would have required them to drop the lawsuit, something
they were unwilling to do, said Mike McKeon, a spokesman for Gov.
George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reworded to make it clear the lawsuit was not
being dropped. With that, the state was willing to return to
negotiations, McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Once all the parties have signed the stipulation letter, McCurn
must give it his final approval before negotiations can resume.
McCurn is spending the month as a visiting judge in Florida but
will act on the letter immediately, Riccio said.
</P>
<P>
   The land claim stems from the state's purchase of 250,000 acres
from the Oneidas in the late 18th and early 19th centuries. The
U.S. Supreme Court found in 1985 that the land was seized in
illegal transactions and ruled the Oneidas were entitled to
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the federal government sided with the Oneidas and filed
an amended complaint asking that 20,000 landowners in Madison and
Oneida counties be added as defendants. McCurn postponed a decision
on that motion while negotiations are pending.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the issues on which the Oneida Nation and the counties
have come to general agreement include: a cap on the amount of land
the Oneidas will purchase in the two counties; some type of
reimbursement to local governments for losing property and sales
tax revenues to the Oneidas; and the issue of sovereignty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 1301 </TRAILER>
