<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25 years later, Skakel arrainged in Moxley case  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- After nearly 25 years, reading the murder
charge against a nephew of the late U.S. Sen. Robert F. Kennedy
will likely take only a few moments.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skakel, now 39, was to be arraigned Tuesday afternoon as
a juvenile in the 1975 slaying of a 15-year-old neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was 15 on the October 1975 night Martha Moxley was
bludgeoned to death with a golf club traced to a Skakel family set.
He denies any involvement in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding -- being held in a Superior Court courtroom to
accommodate a crush of media and family -- is expected to last just
a few minutes. The charge will be read and Skakel advised of his
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Michael Sherman said it was unclear whether
Skakel would be asked to enter a plea. Sherman said he expected
state prosecutors to ask that the case be transferred to adult
court, which would require a hearing at a later date and would
probably delay any plea.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and members of Skakel's high-profile family were
expected to attend the arraignment. About 75 news organizations
requested seats in the courtroom, but because of limited space only
about 30 reporters were given spots.
</P>
<P>
   Martha's older brother, John, and her mother, Dorthy, said they
also planned to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I never had to see him, it would be fine with me,'' said
John Moxley, who was 17 when his sister was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't need to look him in the eye,'' he said. ''I'm going
(to the arraignment) for my own peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skakel is the son of Rushton Skakel Sr., who is the
brother of Robert F. Kennedy's widow, Ethel.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley's case was reopened after more than two decades when an
investigative grand jury was appointed in June 1998. The
appointment followed the publication of books about the case,
including one by former Los Angeles police Detective Mark Fuhrman.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman, who gained notoriety during the O.J. Simpson trial for
racist remarks, has been hired by ABC to provide commentary on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   He identified Michael Skakel as the likely killer in his book.
Prosecutors deny that Fuhrman's book had any influence on their
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Because of confidentiality laws surrounding juvenile cases,
Skakel's arraignment would normally be closed to the public. But
Judge Maureen Dennis, acting on a request from five newspapers and
The Associated Press, last week agreed to open the proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis found that Skakel had already effectively waived his
juvenile confidentiality rights, both because he is an adult and
because his name and the charges against him are already
well-known.
</P>
<P>
   Although the grand jury proceedings were closed to the public,
prosecutors have said in court documents that they were told by
former students at a private school in Poland Spring, Maine, that
Skakel made ''admissions as to the murder of Martha Moxley'' while
a student there from 1978 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was arrested in January after Judge George Thim -- acting
as a one-man grand jury -- ruled there was enough evidence to charge
him.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Connecticut Judicial Branch Web site:
http://www.jud.state.ct.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
