<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru TV Has 'Anything for Money'  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- For $20, two women stripped to their underwear
in front of television cameras, then had buckets of slime-covered
toads poured over their bodies to the hoots and whistles of the
studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   For $20, three men raced to gobble down bowls of large,
twitching, maggot-like tree grubs from the Amazon jungle.
</P>
<P>
   For $30, a woman licked the armpits and toes of a sweaty body
builder who had not bathed for two days.
</P>
<P>
   And some people think 50 women vying for a rich husband is a
sick idea for a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   The gross antics were part of ''Laura en America,'' a talk show
that gets great ratings in Peru but enrages critics. This episode,
''Anything for Money,'' aired late last year and has galvanized an
alliance of feminist groups and human rights organizations in a
drive to pull the plug on the program.
</P>
<P>
   Host Laura Bozzo is Peru's highest rated TV talk-show host. She
reigns as the most visible celebrity in a growing lineup of seamy
''reality-based'' tabloid TV shows that are becoming the norm for
Peruvian programming. U.S. television also is experimenting with
more ''reality-based'' shows, including Fox's recent ''Who Wants to
Marry a Multimillionaire,'' which the network said later had gone
over the line.
</P>
<P>
   Wilfredo Ardito, an attorney with Peru's Legal Defense
Institute, a human rights group, says Bozzo's show exploits the
poor Peruvians who appear on it and are her biggest fans. Critics
say the show's ''real life'' depictions of incest, infidelity, teen
pregnancy and prostitution are staged -- charges that Bozzo denies.
</P>
<P>
   Bozzo, a lawyer, insists her show portrays real people's real
problems. She says guests leave with concrete solutions, and are
provided legal, medical and psychological assistance long after
revealing the tragedy of their personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish-speakers in the United States can judge for themselves.
''Laura en America'' (Laura on the America Channel) has been picked
up by the Miami-based Telemundo Spanish-language network. Since
mid-January, it can be seen in 63 cities by an estimated 85 percent
of U.S. Hispanic viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's official human rights advocate has urged President
Alberto Fujimori's government to stop bankrolling Bozzo's show with
public service ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bozzo offers no apology -- although she says she does regret the
''Anything for Money'' episode -- and claims her critics are
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ''The segment of the Peruvian press that is opposed to the
government wants to put me on the cross because I support the
president,'' Bozzo says.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's foes say the government is happy to support Bozzo's
show because it has a direct line to the poor majority that is
considered critical to his bid for an unprecedented -- many say
illegal -- third term in an election next month.
</P>
<P>
   Performing humiliating, dehumanizing tasks for a few dollars
loses its entertainment value when the participants desperately
need the cash, Ardito says. Moreover, Bozzo regularly berates,
lectures and insults her panelists for their moral lapses, and
frequently threatens to pursue legal charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are people who, because of their poverty and lack of
opportunities, believe she can help,'' Ardito says.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my home we have a maid whose sister-in-law went with her
son who has epilepsy. They were told, 'That is not the theme of the
day. You have to say you hate your father, and that guy over there
will be your father.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors abound that the show's producers will pay for a
compelling, albeit fabricated, story of sleazy woe.
</P>
<P>
   Bozzo rejects such accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the public has an immense affectionate love for me, it is
because they know I do not lie and that my job would not require me
to,'' she says between puffs of a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Then she instructs the photographer: ''Please, no photos while
I'm smoking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
