<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices turned mixed on Wall Street on Tuesday as
biotechnology stocks pulled the Nasdaq composite index lower and
Dow stocks wavered in response to a big acquisition by Alcoa.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
4.96 at 9,947.13.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were lower after surrendering early
gains. The Nasdaq composite index was down 45.04 at 4,862.20, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 1.64 at 1,381.98.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stocks, particularly the shares of companies involved in
genetic mapping, brought the Nasdaq lower after the United States
and Britain agreed to openly share data from a project to decode
the human genetic pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement halts several companies' plans to sell genetic
data to drugmakers and researchers. Incyte Pharmaceuticals fell 49\
to 147}, and Human Genome Sciences fell 21 1/16 to 131{. PE Corp.'s
Celera Genomics fell 48 1/16 to 140 15/16 on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in biotech stocks hampered the Nasdaq's efforts to
rebound from Monday's selloff, when the index dropped 141 points as
investors collected profits from the sector's continuing rally. The
Nasdaq is up more than 21 percent since the start of 2000, while
the Dow and the broader S&AMP;P 500 are down for the year to date.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you get something that's gone up to that extent, you're
going to get violent shakeouts,'' said Don Selkin, chief investment
strategist at Joseph Gunnar in New York. ''This year, people are
going to have to get used to the volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were not significantly affected by the latest evidence
that the economy continues to grow rapidly. The Commerce Department
reported today that retail sales rose by 1.1 percent in February.
With Americans continuing to spend freely, feeding the surging
economy, many analysts expect the Federal Reserve will raise
interest rates when they meet next week.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Vitner, economist at First Union Securities, noted that the
retail sales report is less crucial to the Fed than a pair of
reports due out later this week: the Producer Price Index and the
Consumer Price Index. Both are considered barometers of
inflationary pressures in the robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key for the Fed is still the inflation data,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A rate increase at the Fed's March 21 meeting would be the fifth
since last June. Higher rates tend to be particularly damaging to
financial stocks, but today, those issues led the Dow's advance.
J.P. Morgan rose 1 3/16 to 113 3/16 after saying Monday that
business has been robust in the first two months of the year.
American Express rose 4 7/16 to 131.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa outweighed the strength in the financial sector, tumbling
5 11/16 to 62]. The steel company agreed to buy Cordant
Technologies Inc., a major supplier of aluminum airplane parts and
solid-fuel rockets, for $2.3 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Cordant shares were up 25 13/16 to 55].
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 749.27 million
shares, ahead of Monday's moderate pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.33 to 583.81.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.3 percent,
narrowing its losses from Monday, when it fell 2.8 percent on the
news that the nation's gross domestic product declined for a second
consecutive quarter. The report, which meant Japan's economy is
officially back in recession, unsettled markets around the world on
Monday and contributed to weakness on Wall Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
