<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'The Big Bang' Is Funny, Camp  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two men, Jed Feuer and Boyd Graham, have taken
their considerable talents and used them for total fun in ''The Big
Bang.''
</P>
<P>
   The campy, satirical musical show, running at the off-Broadway
Douglas Fairbanks Theater, has something in common with an
improvised-looking college show that happily flails about at
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that the middle-aged Feuer and Graham, in a
borrowed New York apartment, are putting on an audition for
potential backers of a Broadway musical about the history of
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer and Graham, veterans of cabaret and off-Broadway musicals,
have collaborated before. For ''The Big Bang,'' Feuer wrote the
music and Graham the lyrics. Graham also directed.
</P>
<P>
   The two sing the songs and do constant costume changes,
including taking down window drapes to wrap around themselves as
Caesar and a soothsayer. The show opens in the Garden of Eden, with
the duo singing the funny ''Free Food and Frontal Nudity'' to a
calypso beat played by pianist Albert Ahronheim. Then they switch
to Yiddish accents to build the pyramids before moving on to
ancient Rome, the Virgin Mary and Attila the Hun, whose lines are
sung by Graham in Sinatra style.
</P>
<P>
   The show manages to encompass Columbus, Napoleon and Josephine
the U.S. Civil War in its breakneck 90-minute romp through history.
It's seldom risque, but on occasion comes gleefully close to bad
taste, as in the portrayal of Eva Braun, Hitler's lover, singing
''For the longest time I thought his first name was Heil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
