<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beaujolais Vintners Allow Machines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France (AP) -- Makers of famed Beaujolais wine, whose
grapes have been plucked laboriously by hand for centuries, have
decided to allow machines to do the picking for the first time
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Union of Beaujolais Vintners has authorized automated
harvesting of the gamay grapes that go into the light, fruity wine,
although the famed Beaujolais Nouveau will continue to be made from
hand-picked grapes.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Monday, the group said the top 10 Beaujolais
grands crus -- Morgon, Saint-Amour, Chiroubles, Brouilly, Julienas,
Moulin a Vent, Regne, Chenas, Cote de Brouilly and Fleury -- will be
made from machine-harvested grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The group said the automated procedure would not affect the
delicate fragrance of these popular wines. The machines remove only
the grapes, leaving behind the stems and seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Beaujolais Nouveau grapes, which ferment for a shorter period of
time along with their stems and seeds, will continue to be
harvested by hand - as will vineyards on slopes too steep for
machines to climb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
