<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
Tuesday, March 14, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retail Sales Surged in February
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans, unfazed by rising interest rates
and higher gasoline prices, snapped up cars, clothing and groceries
in February and caused retail sales to jump by 1.1 percent, the
Commerce Department reported today. Economists said this fresh
evidence of a strong economy justifies another interest rate boost
by the Federal Reserve next week to slow things down a bit and
prevent an outbreak of inflation. With plentiful jobs, low
inflation and rising incomes, Americans are feeling wealthy and in
the buying mood, economists said. Retail sales rose to a seasonally
adjusted $265.7 billion last month, the Commerce Department said.
The 1.1 percent jump in sales marked the biggest gain since
December and was slightly stronger than many analysts were
predicting.
</P>
<P>
   Feds Issue Rules for Oil Royalties
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today unveiled its
new royalty collection system for oil taken from the Gulf of Mexico
and other federal lands, capping a long-running battle with oil
producers and congressional Republicans. The new royalty valuation
system, which Congress barred from taking effect for nearly two
years, will be implemented on June 1. At issue is a royalty
collection system that brought in $1.2 billion in 1998 for oil
taken from public lands and offshore tracts, mainly in the Gulf of
Mexico. The Interior Department's Minerals Management Service
estimates its new collection system will collect an extra $67
million annually.
</P>
<P>
   EU, U.S. Reach Deal on Data Privacy
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union and U.S. negotiators
reached a breakthrough in the data protection negotiations today,
making it possible for a trans-Atlantic deal on the contentious
issue to be concluded over the summer, the chief EU negotiator
said. EU negotiator John Mogg said he will recommend that the EU
institutions and member states approve a so-called safe-harbor
agreement that would allow U.S. industry to conduct business with
Europe under strict data privacy conditions. Under the proposed
accord, U.S. companies that agree to the safe harbor guidelines
would be regarded as being in compliance with EU privacy concerns,
Mogg said.
</P>
<P>
   3 Japanese Banks Announce Merger
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Three Japanese banks plan to combine, creating a $1
trillion institution that will be the second largest bank in Japan
and third largest in the world in terms of assets. The trio -- Sanwa
Bank Ltd., Tokai Bank Ltd. and Asahi Bank Ltd. -- plan to set up a
joint holding company in April 2001 and reorganize their retail,
wholesale, international and other operations. A number of
cooperative projects will begin before that, the banks said today.
The deal is the latest in a string of mergers as the Japanese
banking industry struggles to regain a competitive edge and
overcome billions of dollars in bad loans from a speculative
lending boom in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa To Buy Cordant Technologies
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Aluminum maker Alcoa Inc. is acquiring Cordant
Technologies Inc., a major supplier of aluminum airplane parts and
solid-fuel rockets, for $2.3 billion in cash. Shares in Ogden,
Utah-based Cordant soared on news of the merger, which values the
company at $57 a share, nearly double the stock's closing price
yesterday of $29.56\. Cordant shares were up $25.68} or 87 percent
at $55.25 in morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
Alcoa's shares were off $5.68} at $62.37{, also on the NYSE. As
part of the merger, which has already been approved by the boards
of both companies, Alcoa will assume $685 million in debt from
Cordant.
</P>
<P>
   Sears, AOL Team on Net Appliances
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. is teaming up with America
Online Inc. in a wide-ranging alliance that includes everything
from marketing each other's services to developing Internet-linked
appliances for the home. Under the deal announced today, Sears, the
nation's second-biggest retailer behind Wal-Mart Stores Inc., will
promote AOL in its 858 large department stores. AOL, in turn, will
feature Sears on its Web sites and market the giant retail chain to
its more than 21 million subscribers. AOL will be Sears' preferred
Internet service provider. The companies also plan to develop a
special co-branded edition of AOL, which will offer special Sears
promotions and links to Sears' Web sites. That service is expected
to be launched later this year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Plans Another $1B Debt Buyback
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Treasury, brimming with cash, plans to buy
back another $1 billion of the national debt Thursday, the second
repurchase in a week. The Treasury Department said today that
Thursday's debt buyback operation will involve 11 outstanding
issues of 30-year bonds issued between May 1988 and November 1991.
The bonds carry coupon interest rates ranging from 7.875 percent to
9.125 percent. By buying back some of its older, higher-yielding
securities, the government over the long run expects to save money
on interest payments. On Thursday, the Treasury paid $1.345 billion
to repurchase $1 billion of debt, its first repurchase in 70 years.
That $1 billion is a tiny fraction of the $5.7 trillion national
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Boards Approve German Bank Merger
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The merger of Deutsche Bank and
Dresdner Bank won approval from the boards of both companies today
even as bank workers rallied to protest plans for 16,000 layoffs.
Investors were also expressing reservations about the proposed
merger, which would create a leading global bank with $1.2 trillion
in assets. By selling off shares, they've drained about $3 billion
from the deal's value since it was announced last Thursday.
Originally weighing in at $30 billion, the deal dropped to $26.7
billion Tuesday because of a decline in Deutsche's share price.
Investors backed off mostly on fears that the two banks overlap in
too many areas to make the merger worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   British Internet Co. Soars in IPO
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Shares of Internet retailer Lastminute.com PLC
soared as much as 48 percent as it sold its first stock to the
public today, providing fresh evidence of Britain's continuing
frenzy over dot-com investments. Lastminute.com shares jumped to a
high of 562.5 pence, or $8.89 at current exchange rates, from the
offering price of 380 pence ($6.00) each. The share price settled
back to close at 487.5 pence ($7.70), for a gain of 28 percent. The
company, founded in October 1998, enables consumers to book hotel
rooms and buy theater tickers and other goods and services on short
notice at bargain prices via its Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street Stocks Mixed
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices turned mixed on Wall Street today as
biotechnology stocks pulled the Nasdaq composite index lower and
Dow stocks wavered in response to a big acquisition by Alcoa. In
afternoon trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 39.64
at 9,907.49. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,526-1,355.
Broader stock indicators were lower after surrendering early gains.
The Nasdaq composite index was down 96.72 at 4,810.52, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 9.28 at 1,374.34.
</P>
