<HEADLINE> Closing arguments in arson murder trial of Branford businessman  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Jurors were asked Tuesday to consider
the mindset of a Branford business owner accused of setting a fire
at his store that killed a firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony ''Gene'' Bontatibus was last seen before the fire
leaning against a sample rack and looking out the window of his
Floors &AMP; More business on Thanksgiving Day 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour later, a fire first reported by a passerby
would destroy the business, kill firefighter Edward Ramos, 36, and
injure another firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Bontatibus, 61, is charged with arson murder and three counts of
arson. A trial in July 1998 ended in a hung jury.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments Tuesday to his 2{-week retrial, the
prosecutor insisted the fire was set and defense lawyers pointed to
a gas leak or other accidental cause.
</P>
<P>
   State's Attorney Michael Dearington described Bontatibus as a
man heavily in debt and behind on his taxes. Sales of carpet, tile
and other flooring materials were down, and Bontatibus had just
been told he needed a new furnace.
</P>
<P>
   ''His financial problem was not good,'' Dearington told the
jury. ''You look at his state of mind that afternoon and what was
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Dearington accused Bontatibus of pouring an accelerant on the
floor and setting fire to the business to collect $124,000 in
insurance money.
</P>
<P>
   A state fire inspector testified that a burn pattern was found
on the floor of the business' kitchen. The fire traveled into the
attic and spread, eventually collapsing the roof and trapping Ramos
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there hadn't been a death in the building, the
investigation ... would have been substantially different,''
Dearington said. ''It would have been written off as a gas fire.
What no one anticipated, including Mr. Bontatibus, is that there
would be a death.''
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers said Bontatibus was turning his business
around. He was paying off his taxes and debts and wanted to buy the
building that housed his business.
</P>
<P>
   After the fire Bontatibus put the business back together,
continued to pay his workers and was able to fill customers' orders
on time.
</P>
<P>
   Bontatibus took the stand to say he did not set the fire.
</P>
<P>
   An expert hired by the defense found possible accidental causes
for the fire, including a natural gas leak documented in the two
weeks before the fire. Also, the fluorescent lights in the building
had been malfunctioning, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   No exact cause for the fire was found, attorney Auden Grogins
told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''It means reasonable doubt,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The expert said the fire started in the attic, causing the roof
to collapse and killing Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   Bontatibus' lawyers blamed Ramos' death on the Branford Fire
Department, which did not realize for some time that Ramos was
trapped in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''They underestimated the fire, their equipment malfunctioned,
they mismanaged the fire, and you know, it's a lot easier to blame
someone else,'' attorney Thomas Ullmann said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
