<HEADLINE> Flashlight Mogul Paying Palimony  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- The founder of the multimillion-dollar
Mag-Lite flashlight company has agreed to pay a $29 million
settlement to a former companion he lived and worked with for two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement reached last week is only a fraction of the $84
million an Orange County Superior Court jury ordered Anthony
Maglica to pay Claire Maglica in 1994, which was considered the
highest-ever palimony judgment.
</P>
<P>
   That award was thrown out by an appeals court in September 1998,
and a new trial was ordered.
</P>
<P>
   A month into the new trial, the Maglicas agreed to an
out-of-court settlement after the dismissal of several jurors
threatened to lead to a mistrial and further delay the long-running
case.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Maglica has maintained Anthony Maglica promised her a
share of Mag Instruments during the 21 years they were together.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ms. Maglica views this as peace,'' said John Keker, her
attorney. ''She settled because she decided that peace was more
important than getting all that she deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Maglica started a machine shop business in 1955 and kept it
after a 1971 divorce. That same year, he met interior designer
Claire Halasz. They lived together, she took his last name, and the
couple presented themselves as married. When the company
incorporated in 1974, he became president and she became secretary,
with equal salaries. All the shares were in his name.
</P>
<P>
   The company started making flashlights in 1978 and thrived, and
a court ruled that her work and ideas were partially responsible
for its success.
</P>
<P>
   Mag Instruments is now estimated to be worth as much as $750
million.
</P>
<P>
   The couple broke up in 1992 after Ms. Maglica found Maglica was
trying to transfer stock to his children but not to her, the court
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maglica chose to settle because Ms. Maglica's attempts to claim
half of the Ontario-based company hampered its growth, according to
his attorney, Robert C. Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes sense for him to move forward, and more or less
complete his dream of having a $1 billion company,'' Weiss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
