<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Investors OK Wireless Stock  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. announced Tuesday that its
shareholders approved the company's proposal to create a tracking
stock that will reflect the performance of AT&AMP;T's mobile phone
division and other wireless businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to begin selling the shares this spring in
what may be the biggest initial public offering of stock in U.S.
history.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was approved by 97.6 percent of the shares that
were cast in a special vote and about 65.5 percent of all AT&AMP;T
shares. The preliminary tally was announced at a special meeting of
AT&AMP;T stockholders in Parsippany, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 20 percent of the new wireless shares, worth as much as
$10 billion according to some estimates, would be sold in the IPO.
The remainder would be distributed to AT&AMP;T stockholders later this
year at an undisclosed rate for each AT&AMP;T share.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, trying to jump-start its languishing stock price, is
hopeful the IPO will capitalize on Wall Street's infatuation with
the ongoing convergence of Internet services with wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to unlocking what the company perceives as the
hidden value of its mobile phone operation, the IPO would help fund
the expansion of AT&AMP;T's wireless network, which will also be used
to provide telephone and Internet service to homes and businesses
with special antennas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
