<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Issue Rules for Oil Royalties  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a four-year battle with the oil
industry, the Clinton administration disclosed a new system Tuesday
for collecting royalties on crude oil pumped from the Gulf of
Mexico and federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   While Interior Department officials described the new oil
valuation system as balanced, meeting the needs of both the
taxpayers and industry, producers complained the plan overstates
oil's value and will prove too confusing to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   The system, which Congress barred from taking effect for almost
two years at the behest of disgruntled producers, will be
implemented on June 1. It replaces a system that lets oil companies
set arbitrary values at the wellhead with one that will peg the
value to a market indicator.
</P>
<P>
   The government took in $1.2 billion in 1998 for oil drilled on
public lands and offshore tracts. Interior's Minerals and
Management Service estimates its new oil valuation system will
collect an extra $67 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe we have a rule that strikes a responsible balance
between the interests of the oil and gas industry and the
government's absolute obligation to assure a fair return for the
public's mineral resources,'' the service's director, Walt
Rosenbusch, said.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment wasn't shared by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't view this as a balanced approach,'' said Mark Rubin
of the American Petroleum Institute. ''We are very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry has had problems with the existing system, which
has exposed major oil companies to numerous lawsuits that charged
they were underpaying royalties. Settlements in one case, an
underpayment case filed in Lufkin, Texas, exceed $275 million.
</P>
<P>
   A government watchdog group, the Project on Government
Oversight, estimates the industry has underpaid its royalties by
more than $2 billion over two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The industry fears the new plan may expose oil companies to a
flurry of new litigation. ''We're very concerned that it's going to
lead to more lawsuits in the future because the system is getting
more complex, not less complex,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials now will assess whether to file a federal
suit seeking to block implementation of the new royalty collection
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Minerals and Management Service began rewriting its oil
valuation rules more than four years ago, armed with audits
suggesting the government was not receiving its fair share. The
process was delayed when energy producers successfully lobbied
Congress to delay the final rule for close to two years. A
moratorium barring the service from issuing the final rule expires
Wednesday, and the agency will publish its rule then in the Federal
Register.
</P>
<P>
   The author of that moratorium, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas, slammed the administration for issuing its plan as gas
prices soar.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time this administration stopped depending upon the
goodwill of foreign oil producers and instead focused on creating
the incentives for domestic production that can permanently take
Americans off this gas-price roller-coaster,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Carolyn Maloney, who battled the oil companies on
Capitol Hill, praised the mineral service's action.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's announcement finally brings to an end the decades-old
scam that has permitted big oil companies to rip off the American
taxpayer,'' said Maloney, D-N.Y. ''This is a tremendous win for the
taxpayers, who will now finally get the money they deserve from
companies that produce oil on federal land.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Interior Department's Mineral and Management
Service's Web site: http://www.mms.gov
</P>
<P>
   American Petroleum Institute's Web site: http://www.api.org
</P>
</TEXT>
