<HEADLINE> House Starts Rural Caucus Again  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN BIERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House lawmakers, saying the nation's
prosperity had failed to reach farmers, revived on Tuesday a
members' coalition dedicated to advancing the interests of rural
America.
</P>
<P>
   ''The American economy has been booming, yet many of our rural
and agricultural communities are being left behind,'' said Rep. Jo
Ann Emerson, R-Mo., co-chairwoman of the Congressional Rural
Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rural America gets the short end of the stick on funding from
economic development to education and everything in between,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   They said the caucus, an informal group of legislators with a
common agenda, would take up problems that have contributed to the
crisis in rural America. Among them are changing economic
conditions, foreign competition, taxes and the flight to the cities
of rural areas' most educated young people.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up with the international competition, Rep. John
Peterson, R-Pa., suggested the United States lift food embargoes in
place against some foreign nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic co-chairwoman, Rep. Eva Clayton of North
Carolina, said the 112-member caucus will concern itself with how
to get the government to provide better services to rural
Americans. She said the rural elderly are 66 percent more likely to
live in poverty than other elderly Americans, and many of the
nation's rural hospitals operate at financial losses.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is, rural communities are faced with a Catch-22
situation,'' Emerson said. ''They don't have the infrastructure
needed to attract new and high-tech businesses, and they don't have
the resources needed to invest in the infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., said some rural schools in her
district lack federal free lunch programs for poor students because
the schools don't have the money to employ people to navigate
federal regulations to obtain the benefit.
</P>
</TEXT>
