<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman offers child care plans; parents ask tough questions  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENNINGTON, N.J. (AP) -- Bouncing a baby on her knee, Gov.
Christie Whitman talked to parents Tuesday about her plans to help
them find reliable child care.
</P>
<P>
   She unveiled a hotline they could call for referrals. She
highlighted plans to help some grandparents get subsidized day care
when they're raising their grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   But in answer to some tough questions, the governor told parents
they would still have to rely on their own resourcefulness to find
care for their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman met with about 20 new parents attending a Capital Health
Systems parent support group meeting here, while their babies
played on a mat on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   One asked why so few corporations provide onsite day care and
what the governor plans to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Necowitz, a Princeton resident and mother of a 7-month-old
girl, said her husband works at AT&AMP;T, which does not provide onsite
day care.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have so much money,'' said Necowitz, a marriage
counselor. ''There's really no reason why they can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman told Necowitz that her husband should get other
employees together and convince the corporation to open a center.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something you've got to really lobby the businesses to
make sure they're responsive to your needs,'' said Whitman. ''You
can have a lot of influence, particularly in this tight job
market.''
</P>
<P>
   After the session, Necowitz said it would help if the governor
and Legislature required large companies to provide centers.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need to be doing more,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also highlighted a new program to help grandparents who
are raising their grandchildren, but that, too, promises to fall
short of the need.
</P>
<P>
   The governor wants to earmark 500 subsidized day care slots for
grandparents. More than 100,000 New Jersey grandparents are raising
their grandkids.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just the first piece of many supports we're going to
be offering many kinship caregivers,'' said Wendi Patella,
spokeswoman for the state Department of Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   The day care slots are part of a two-year, $12 million
initiative that will also provide support services, such as respite
care or help buying baby items.
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents have lobbied Whitman to provide the same monthly
payments that non-relative foster parents receive. Earlier this
year, a state task force backed them up, recommending the state pay
grandparents the $400 to $500 per month foster care board rate.
</P>
<P>
   But the Whitman administration has resisted providing payments
to kin, fearing it would cost too much and encourage parents to
place their children with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Human Services Commissioner Michele Guhl, who previously opposed
providing the subsidies, said Tuesday the state is re-examining its
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''DYFS is looking at subsidized guardianship,'' Guhl said,
noting that legislation has been introduced that would require the
state to provide that support.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also plans to use federal welfare funds to add 500 day
care slots to the more than 69,000 currently subsidized for
low-income parents. That will help reduce the current 1,500-parent
waiting list for these slots, according to Beverly Lynn,
administrator of office of child care operations.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman touted the new hotline -- 1-800-332-9227 -- designed to
connect parents with their local child care referral service.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents said it would help.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the phone number will be great,'' said Kirsten
Detrick, a Pennington resident who works at Bristol-Myers Squibb.
The company has an onsite day care center, but there is a waiting
list, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband Herb both took leave to care for their son,
Hadley, 5 months. But soon, they'll be in the market for day care.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the things that has prevented us from moving forward
was not knowing where to turn for answers,'' said Detrick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
