<DOCNO> APW20000314.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Payden &AMP; Rygel Stays Independent  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL WHITE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In a financial world dominated by giants,
California-based money manager Payden &AMP; Rygel is finding success in
global markets while staying small and independent.
</P>
<P>
   Payden &AMP; Rygel's small cap European Aggressive Growth fund is up
58 percent so far this year, with total investment nearly doubling
from $50 million to just over $100 million since the end of
January.
</P>
<P>
   On the domestic front, the company recently sealed a Missouri
state pension fund deal that boosted funds under Payden &AMP; Rygel
management by $1.4 billion to $29 billion. And the company's family
of 25 no-load funds recently has won accolades from such
publications as Barron's, the Wall Street Journal, USA Today and
Morningstar, the mutual fund rating service.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, people value independents,'' said John
Siciliano, one of the company's eight partners.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are not interested in having a manager who is owned by a
large institution and seeks to sell them other financial products.
They want to know who they're dealing with and we're able to engage
with them eyeball to eyeball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of intimacy sets Payden &AMP; Rygel apart in a financial
services landscape dominated in recent years by international
mergers and consolidation. Citigroup was created in 1998 by the
merger of Citicorp and Traveler Group. Dutch insurer Aegon SV
purchased Transamerica Corp. in a deal that combined their mutual
fund management into a new entity, Transamerica Investment
Management.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent combination, the largest U.S. bond manager,
Pimco Advisors Holdings of Newport Beach, Calif., is being acquired
by Germany's Allianz.
</P>
<P>
   Payden &AMP; Rygel has no interest in courting buyers, and no
incentive to do so, Siciliano said. ''The incentive is to stay
independent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The European Aggressive Growth Fund owes its existence in part
to a joint venture formed last year with Metzler Bank, Germany's
oldest private bank. That venture, Metzler/Payden, was an attempt
to take advantage of investment opportunities created by Europe's
adoption of a common currency, the Euro. While the Euro itself has
foundered against the dollar, it has helped open up European
companies to foreign investment. The fund is managed from Payden &AMP;
Rygel's Frankfurt, Germany office.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Euro has caused the single largest market after the dollar
market to develop,'' Siciliano said. ''Having a common currency
causes people to look at Europe in a different way. They're looking
at Europe as a single market rather than a group of companies.''
</P>
<P>
   About 50 percent of Payden &AMP; Rygel's European fund is comprised
of technology and communications stocks, with the rest scattered
across a range of consumer product, financial and industrial
holdings. Companies in the fund include Psion, the British maker of
hand-held computers, German bakery company Kamps and Gruppo
Editorial L'Expresso, publisher of La Republica and other Italian
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The average market capitalization of the fund is between $500
million and $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Europe was kind to investors over the past year, said Geoffrey
Bobroff, an industry consultant in East Greenwich, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear that people look at Europe as a place that is
several years behind the United States in terms of expansion, and
poses a glorious opportunity,'' he said. ''U.S. investors are
underweighted in terms of the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the early part of the year, international
small-capitalization funds have done exceedingly well, in some
cases yielding returns that rival the more-talked about technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Payden &AMP; Rygel fund gets generally good marks from financial
consultant Paul Merriman, operator of Fundadvice.com, although he
worried that its spectacular growth could be driven by the fund's
own reinvestment into a relatively small number of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   At $100 million, Siciliano said, the fund is much too small and
the companies in question too large for that to be a factor in the
fund's growth. The key to the fund's growth, he said, has been the
wealth of good values to be found in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Ticking off the fund's positives, Merriman noted that expenses
are low, below 1 percent, and it fits a hard-to-fill niche by
focusing on small European companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bigger question is whether a family of funds is being run
by the marketing department or run by the people who manage
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This looks to me more like money managers who have funds than
marketing people who are trying to sell funds. You can see that, by
the way, in the pricing. If this was a fund family being run by the
marketing department, my guess is you would have higher expenses,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   End advance for use anytime
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
