<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge calls Hamilton the 'gatekeeper' of the election fraud plan  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The political director for ousted Teamsters
President Ron Carey was sentenced Tuesday to three years in prison
by a judge who credited him for good deeds done prior to his
embezzlement and fraud conviction.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas P. Griesa said it would be
''unreasonable and unmerciful'' not to credit William W. Hamilton
for his devotion to public service and civil rights causes
throughout a 30-year career.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he strayed somewhat reluctantly from the federal
sentencing guidelines calling for a nearly four-year prison term as
he is permitted to do for extraordinary public service.
</P>
<P>
   He described in detail how others relied on Hamilton for
permission to donate $885,000 in Teamsters money to five
organizations in return for donations from individuals to the
effort to re-elect Carey in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Hamilton did not initiate that concept but he agreed to
play a role in it and his role was crucial,'' Griesa said. ''He
was, in effect, the gatekeeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 57, was convicted last November after a three-week
trial of embezzlement, mail and wire fraud and perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was sentenced, he told Griesa that his crimes were
meant to help keep the union out of the hands of those who had
corrupted it in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes when you try to do something you believe in deeply,
you do dumb things, you cross the line, you overreach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he was thrilled in 1989 when the federal
government seized control of the Teamsters through a consent order
meant to separate the powerful union with more than one million
members from mob influence.
</P>
<P>
   He said his trial and conviction had been a ''degrading and
humiliating'' experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am ashamed and deeply angry at myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial featured testimony from Richard Sullivan, former
finance director of the Democratic National Committee. He said
President Clinton's close friend and chief fund-raiser, Terence
McAuliffe, urged him and others to find donors for Carey.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we could get a $50,000 donor to Carey, ... he knew we would
get $500,000 from the Teamsters,'' Sullivan said McAuliffe told
him. The union is not permitted to use its money to fund elections
for union members.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats failed to produce a donor and the Teamsters did
not make a donation. McAuliffe was not charged with any crime and
his lawyer, Richard Ben-Veniste, said he cooperated with
prosecutors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 1708 </TRAILER>
