<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Back Toward 6-Week Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell back toward a six-week low
against the yen Tuesday despite speculation that Japan's central
bank would intervene for the second time in a week to weaken its
currency. The dollar also fell against the euro.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading, the dollar was quoted at 105.05 Japanese yen,
down from 105.55 at the same point on Monday, but still a shade
above Monday's six-week low of 104.83. In dollar-euro trading, the
euro was quoted at 96.73 cents, up from Monday's 96.49 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Traders bought yen despite speculation that the Bank of Japan
would reprise last Wednesday's market intervention, when the bank
sold an estimated $1 billion to $3 billion worth of yen in a bid to
stem the currency's advance.
</P>
<P>
   Some expected the central bank to take aggressive action
following Monday's report that Japan's gross domestic product fell
1.4 percent in the October-December quarter. It was the second
consecutive quarter of GDP decline, meaning the economy was
technically back in recession. A strong yen may exacerbate the
situation by making Japanese exports more expensive in other
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar, meanwhile, was also undermined Tuesday by another
shaky day for the U.S. stock market, where technology shares
tumbled for a second straight day. The tech-heavy Nasdaq composite
index has tumbled nearly 7 percent from Friday's record high.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Tuesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.6668 Swiss
francs, down from late Monday's 1.6698, and 1.4645 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.4617. The British pound fell to $1.5765 compared
with $1.5785 a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0223
German marks, down from 2.0269 on Monday; 6.7824 French francs,
down from 6.7978; and 2,002.04 Italian lire, down from 2,006.60.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
