<HEADLINE> Putin's Economic Plan Defended  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Acting President Vladimir Putin's campaign manager
on Tuesday defended the front-runner's failure to release a
detailed program proposing solutions to Russia's economic morass.
</P>
<P>
   With the election less than two weeks away, Dmitry Medvedev told
a news conference that Putin preferred to take his time developing
thorough proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Putin's opponents have strongly criticized him for being
vague about his strategy for addressing Russia's complex economic
woes -- although the criticism appears not to have affected his
strong popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's understandable that the broad public in Russia and abroad
is waiting to hear answers to the issues faced by the country,''
Medvedev said. ''Vladimir Putin believed it would be wrong to try
and present a conclusive program in such a short time. It would be
more feasible to thoroughly prepare a conclusive program.''
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election polls have consistently shown Putin gaining about
60 percent support in the March 26 vote, with his nearest
challenger, Communist Gennady Zyuganov, commanding about 20 percent
support.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has been generally lackluster and predictable,
although the Central Election Commission added some spice Tuesday
when it renewed efforts to keep ultranationalist firebrand Vladimir
Zhirinovsky off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had to add Zhirinovsky to the list of 11 other
candidates last week after the Supreme Court overturned its
decision to keep him from the March 26 vote for not declaring
property belonging to his son, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court had earlier rejected a Zhirinovsky appeal, but
the court's Board of Appeal said banning Zhirinovsky was unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   Central Election Commission chief Alexander Veshnyakov said
Tuesday he would go to the Prosecutor General's Office to lodge an
appeal to the highest possible court -- the Supreme Court's
Presidium.
</P>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky gained notoriety in the early 1990s with his
firebrand rhetoric, ranging from promises to annex Finland and
Alaska to calls for resettling Jews and napalming Chechnya. He was
elected to parliament and came fifth in the 1996 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his maverick ways and angry rhetoric, Zhirinovsky and
his Liberal Democratic Party consistently backed the government in
showdowns with the parliament, then dominated by Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky, who is now a deputy speaker in parliament, issued
his trademark shocking tirades in the city of Nizhny Novgorod on
Tuesday, promising to establish a ''military-police state,''
increase the size of the army and restore the feared Soviet-era KGB
if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Russia needs a ''firm president who will be feared,'' he said,
according to the Interfax news agency. ''Democracy will lead this
country to an abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the liberal Union of Right Forces, led by former
Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, voted to back Putin in the race
even though one of its leaders, Samara Governor Konstantin Titov,
is running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
