<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sailors Go To Philipines Court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEBU, Philippines (AP) -- Three U.S. sailors went to court on
assault charges Tuesday in what Philippine officials called a test
of a new agreement to try U.S. servicemen in local tribunals for
crimes they commit here while off-duty.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said the case marked an
important step in implementing the U.S.-Philippine Visiting Forces
Agreement, designed to reassure the Philippines and allow the
resumption of joint military exercises here.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be a very important case on the issue of
jurisdiction,'' Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
   Taxi driver Marcelo Batistil said he drove the three sailors
around the port city of Cebu on Sunday, but they refused to pay
him. They then jumped into another taxi and he gave chase, blocking
the car, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three sailors got out and punched him several times in the
face and body, Batistil said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which allowed the two countries to resume
large-scale joint military exercises after a five-year cessation,
has been vehemently opposed by many left-wing groups, which say it
will result in a string of crimes by U.S. troops and a rise in
prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters marched Monday and Tuesday to a pier near the men's
ship, the USS Blue Ridge, and demanded it leave.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Cato, spokesman for a presidential commission overseeing
U.S. military visits to the country, said officials of the vessel,
the flagship of the U.S. Seventh Fleet, ''apologized profusely''
for the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The three sailors appeared somber in casual clothes Tuesday at
the prosecutor's office where Batistil filed criminal and civil
complaints against them. They later were arraigned in court, where
they pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   They face a maximum of 13 months in jail if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rosabella Tormis said she allowed the men to leave with
their ship for Japan on Wednesday after their commanding officer
pledged they would return for all court sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, approved in May by the Philippine Senate,
the United States generally has legal jurisdiction over U.S.
personnel who commit crimes while on duty, and the Philippines has
jurisdiction over those who commit crimes while off duty.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by the USS Blue Ridge followed a month-long joint
military exercise involving thousands of American and Filipino
troops -- the first in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The United States suspended major military exercises in the
Philippines in December 1996 after Manila closed a loophole
shielding U.S. military personnel from prosecution in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Military ties with the United States remain a sensitive topic
more than seven years after the last U.S. base was closed by the
Philippine government, ending nearly a century of heavy U.S.
military presence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 1721 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
