<HEADLINE> Serbs, French Clash Over Bridge  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A Serb official in Kosovo
warned Tuesday of new conflict in this ethnically divided city if
NATO follows through on what he claims are plans to take control of
a bridge and remove its Serb guards.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Ivanovic said French Gen. Pierre de Saqui de Sannes told
him in a meeting that NATO troops would establish a 100-yard
''safety zone'' on the Serb-controlled north bank of the Ibar River
in an ethnically mixed neighborhood called Little Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The only civilians who would be allowed in the zone are those
who live there, Ivanovic quoted the general as saying. That would
require Serb ''bridge guardians'' to leave the area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians who used to live in the neighborhood are afraid
to return as long as the Serb guards remain on the bridge across
the Ibar. The Serbs, however, consider the guards their only
reliable defense against revenge-seeking ethnic Albanians, who
vastly outnumber Serbs here.
</P>
<P>
   ''This measure will create greater tension and I think that it
will lead to a certain amount of conflict and I think it could lead
to the expulsion of Serbs or their fleeing the area,'' Ivanovic
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no comment from NATO spokesmen. However, NATO and U.N.
officials have been saying for more than a week that they plan to
establish such control zones to move out the Serb bridge guards and
reassert international authority in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic said he was told that NATO's commander in Kosovo, Gen.
Klaus Reinhardt, and the chief U.N. administrator, Bernard
Kouchner, were expected here Wednesday to oversee the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic said he tried to talk the French general out of the
plan but failed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The general was very arrogant and decisive,'' Ivanovic said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
