<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Group Outlines China Hurdles  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China has a long way to go in establishing a fair
environment for international business, the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce in China said Tuesday in a report outlining a litany of
troubles faced by foreign investors here.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. businesses find China's legal system ''unpredictable,
undependable and confusing'' and feel that many of the country's
trade policies and business practices are ''fundamentally unfair,''
the group said in its annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the list of recommendations was a need to make laws and
administrative regulations of all kinds public and to enforce and
interpret them in a consistent way, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ''U.S. businesses are in a relatively optimistic mood with
regard to the medium- and long-term prospects,'' said Christian
Murck, general manager for The Chase Manhattan Bank in Beijing and
an editor of the report. ''But you have to recognize that the
situation for many foreign companies is quite difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is to be distributed to members of the U.S. Congress
and the Clinton administration as well as Chinese government
ministries and is part of a growing effort by U.S. companies in
China to directly lobby for changes in policies and business
practices that handicap foreign businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The report indicated that American Chamber of Commerce members
viewed market access restrictions and high taxes and tariffs as
greater barriers to profitability than bottom-line issues such as
high labor costs and competition.
</P>
<P>
   Limits on the sorts of businesses that foreign companies can
engage in were a particularly sore point. China has until now
severely limited foreign involvement in distribution, particularly
of products made by joint ventures, as well as banking, insurance,
securities and the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   The report also suggested:
</P>
<P>
   --Better enforcement of protection of trademarks, copyrights and
other forms of intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   --Allowing foreign business partners greater control over their
technology, including a say in how the technology is used and
better protection of patents, trademarks and copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   --Reducing taxes and other costs associated with hiring Chinese
workers and lifting limits on who can be employed where.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese companies struggling with piracy of their products and
with local protectionism also are pushing for a more equitable
business climate, said Tim Stratford, chairman of the American
Chamber of Commerce and general counsel for General Motors in
China.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really think that China's coming into the WTO will be a
watershed event comparable to U.S. and China normalizing relations
back in 1979,'' Stratford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 1736 </TRAILER>
