<HEADLINE> Blind Vendor Helps Police Nab Woman  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL ZOLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- Richard Fracasso, snack bar vendor at the
state Traffic Court, likes to joke that he's blind -- not stupid.
</P>
<P>
   When a friend told him a bill he accepted was a one and not a
twenty as he thought, he vowed to nab the wrongdoer. Soon after, he
helped police catch the court clerk now charged with trying to take
his money.
</P>
<P>
   ''She thought I was her own private ATM machine,'' Fracasso, 67,
said Tuesday. ''Can you picture some dame coming in here doing
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Bingham, 33, was arrested after she handed Fracasso a
dollar bill for a bottle of apple juice last week and told him it
was $20, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   She was fired Monday, just two months after she started, and has
been charged with misdemeanor obtaining money under false
pretenses.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham could not be reached for comment Tuesday because her
home telephone number in Smithfield is unpublished.
</P>
<P>
   Fracasso, who can only see light and dark, recognizes most of
his customers by voice. They tell him how much they have paid and
he makes change by feeling the coins or grabbing bills from their
assigned slots in his cash drawer.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he was making change when the friend told
Fracasso about the disparity with the bills. Fracasso asked someone
to check some of his other bills and discovered the same
discrepancy with a few more.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried to think who was giving me a lot of twenties and I
remembered (Bingham),'' Fracasso said. ''I guessed it was her.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingham arrived to buy juice a few days later and said she was
giving him $20, Fracasso said. He slid the bill into a small
electronic currency scanner he keeps on hand but rarely uses. The
machine identified the money as $1 and he called security.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was angry because she was trying to take advantage of my
blindness,'' said Fracasso, who lost his sight 22 years ago from a
degenerative eye disease.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed in connection with the other bills
Fracasso questioned due to lack of evidence, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time someone tried to steal from the vendor.
In 1997, another clerk pleaded no contest to taking potato chips
from the snack bar. She was fired, fined and ordered to perform
community service.
</P>
<P>
   Fracasso also said his cane has been stolen several times.
</P>
<P>
   ''People will take anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he pledged not to become bitter.
</P>
<P>
   As customers lined up at the snack bar Tuesday for ham salad
sandwiches and chocolate milk, Fracasso said he would follow the
example his late wife set as she fought cancer: Face problems with
courage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try not to let it change me,'' Fracasso said. ''I don't want
to turn into something else because people treat me this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 1739 </TRAILER>
