<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine set to unleash TV commercial 'air war' to boostrecognition  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- The anticipated ''air war'' is ready
to launch as Jon Corzine begins to deploy his personal millions in
an effort to boost his name recognition among the Democrats he
hopes will nominate him to run for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, a former Wall Street executive with a personal fortune
exceeding $300 million, said a pair of commercials will begin
airing Wednesday on New York and Philadelphia television stations
and probably continue through the next 12 weeks until the June 6
New Jersey primary.
</P>
<P>
   His primary campaign opponent, former Gov. Jim Florio, has no
immediate plans to broadcast TV commercials, according to Michael
Murphy, a co-manager of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are contemplating doing something briefly early on,''
Murphy said, but the heaviest TV spending would not occur until
mid-May with two or three weeks left before the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine and his aides were officially mum about the exact level
of spending. Steve Goldstein, co-manager of his campaign, said it
would be ''in the mid-six figures,'' roughly $500,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat close to the campaign told The Associated Press the
weekly ad buys could reach $1 million a week. At that rate, Corzine
would be spending more of his own money each month on TV
commercials than Florio will spend for the whole primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein would not comment directly on that estimate but did
say, ''Jim Florio has a 30-year head start on Jon Corzine in terms
of name recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   TV stations provide public files on political advertising but
will not share it on the phone, according to officials at the ABC
network affiliates in New York and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   However, a staff member at WABC-TV Channel 7 in New York said
Corzine had placed more than a dozen spots to air through Tuesday
at a cost of $200,000 just at that one station.
</P>
<P>
   There are two commercials, a 60-second biographical spot and a
30-second ad focusing on health insurance. Goldstein said both
would have equal exposure on network-affiliated channels in New
York and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are descriptive of my background, why I am running, the
kinds of things that are important to me,'' Corzine said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Early polls taken last month indicated that only one in three
registered Democrats recognizes Corzine's name, and that only one
in five has formed a favorable view of him.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking during a break at a luncheon he sponsored with union
leaders here, Corzine conceded that he trails Florio in polls and
that his emphasis must be to make his name known.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is that we think we have to make sure we establish
strong name recognition, and the only way you can do that on a
broad basis in New Jersey is by getting out and getting started in
the media,'' Corzine said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the primary campaign does not officially begin until
after candidates file petitions April 13, Florio and Corzine have
been competing for party support since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said he does not believe this is an especially early
start for TV advertising. ''In elections around the country, people
have started a lot earlier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy disagreed, saying never in his political career has he
seen such a heavy dose of TV commercials placed so early.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have expected that he was going to spend an enormous amount
of personal wealth on the airwaves,'' Murphy said. ''Jon Corzine is
engaging in the media equivalent of carpet bombing, and we are
going into be launching smart bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer commercial features photos of his family background
on an Illinois farm followed by narration on five policy points:
health care, long-term care for seniors, gun licensing, access to
education and racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter commercial features Corzine speaking about his idea
of mandating that all employers provide health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Old ideas are not working and we need to bring new
perspectives to bear on a very tough problem,'' Corzine says in the
ad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
