<HEADLINE> Congo Troop Deloyment On Track  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Congolese rebels said Tuesday they had
killed at least 150 government troops in taking a southern town,
even as a top U.N. official claimed a planned 5,000-strong
peacekeeping deployment was on track.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel spokesman Kin-Kiey Mulumba said his forces dealt a heavy
blow to Congolese President Laurent Kabila's army and its
Zimbabwean allies Saturday, killing 150 soldiers and capturing
ammunition in Idumbe, 375 miles east of the capital, Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   In Harare, the Zimbabwean army confirmed the Rwandan-backed
rebels had taken control of the town, and threatened to retaliate
for what it said was a direct threat to Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bernard Miyet, U.N. undersecretary general for
peacekeeping operations, was upbeat after meeting rebel leaders and
Rwandan officials in Kigali, and announced that all the countries
involved in the 1{-year Congolese war had given the go-ahead for
the deployment of more than 5,000 U.N. troops and cease-fire
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the parties have pledged necessary security guarantees and
freedom of movement for U.N. personnel,'' Miyet said before
departing for the Ugandan capital, Kampala. He had traveled already
to Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Miyet did not give a timetable for the deployment of four U.N.
battalions in four cities under the control of government troops
and their backers -- from Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- and of
Congolese rebels and their allies -- Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   But as a result of Miyet's visit, two aircraft carrying 12 U.N.
personnel traveled Tuesday to one of the four base towns, Mbuji
Mayi in the south of Congo, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The guns in Congo were supposed to have fallen silent after an
August peace agreement between the president and the rebels
fighting to oust him. Rwanda, Uganda, Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia
also signed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the United Nations is to deploy observers
and soldiers to protect them. Later it would send a larger U.N.
presence to oversee the disengagement of forces, the withdrawal of
foreign troops and the disarmament of Rwandan Hutu militiamen, who
were responsible for the 1994 genocide in Rwanda and are now
fighting in Kabila's army.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict has continued, with mutual accusations of
cease-fire violations. Last week the United States warned that,
without an end to the fighting, any deployment would be hard to
achieve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
