<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business  </HEADLINE>
By MARIA CODER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONEY MANAGEMENT: Americans expect to spend $15,210 this year on
day-to-day expenses.
</P>
<P>
   A national survey of 800 adults by American Express found the
amount that people spend on items like groceries, gasoline, fast
food, cellular and Internet services will remain relatively
unchanged from 1999 to 2000. In last year's survey, respondents
reported spending $14,917 on household expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that men and women are each involved in
household financial management, but in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that more women (72 percent) than men (52
percent) handle the bill-paying at home, while more men (57
percent) than women (43 percent) make financial investment
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   AND THE WINNER IS ...: The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences may have its opinion of the best pictures, but many
Internet users disagree with its choices for the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 percent of 1,000 Internet users polled agreed with last
year's choice for best picture, ''Shakespeare in Love,'' according
to a Greenfield Online Omnibus study for WebSwap.com. Nearly five
times that, 46 percent, thought ''Saving Private Ryan'' should have
taken the award. Eight percent thought ''Life is Beautiful,''
should have won.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, only 11 percent agreed with the choice of Robert
Benigni as best actor for his role in ''Life is Beautiful.''
Forty-three percent said Tom Hanks deserved the award for ''Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The respondents were kinder to Gwyneth Paltrow, who won the best
actress award for ''Shakespeare in Love.'' Twenty-five percent
agreed with the choice, while 11 percent said Cate Blanchett
deserved the Oscar for ''Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEE ENVY: If you're feeling cheated by your employer,
you're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   A recent telephone survey 1,015 adults found that half of the
respondents feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ''Too many of us have been fed the line that 'work isn't
necessarily about money,'' says author Stephen Pollan, who
commissioned the poll. ''But tell that to Visa next time they send
you your bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The respondents said they felt cheated because they weren't
being paid comparable wages to others in their industry (25
percent), receive inadequate vacation time (16 percent),
insufficient retirement savings (16 percent), aren't paid for
overtime (15 percent) and feel they have no privacy or are spied
upon at work (14 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The poll found women feel cheated more than men 56 percent to 47
percent. And 66 percent of African-Americans felt cheated, versus
47 percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
   End advance for release anytime
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
