<HEADLINE> ABC's Winning Streak Hits 11 Weeks  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC clearly learned what television viewers
weren't interested in watching on Sunday night, when NBA basketball
and the gangster movie, ''Donnie Brasco,'' dragged the network to a
historic low in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The network had its smallest audience of any Sunday evening --
except in the summer rerun season -- since Nielsen Media Research
began its more precise measuring system in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In a gangster face-off, the average audience for ''Donnie
Brasco'' was even smaller than HBO's competing episode of ''The
Sopranos.'' That's remarkable because HBO, a pay cable station, is
available in roughly one-third the number of homes that get NBC.
</P>
<P>
   On basic cable, the Discovery Network's ''Raising the Mammoth''
even beat out the Al Pacino movie. The documentary was by far the
highest-rated show in Discovery's 15-year history, with more than
double the audience of the previous best, a 1997 ''Raising the
Titanic'' special.
</P>
<P>
   It was another bad night for the NBA on NBC, which filled two
hours of prime-time Sunday with either a Sonics-Raptors matchup or
Knicks-Spurs. The NBA's ratings are down 27 percent from last year,
and 31 percent from 1998, Michael Jordan's last season.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is usually the most-watched night of television during
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Two midseason replacement series -- CBS' ''Grapevine'' and NBC's
''God, the Devil and Bob,'' are both doing so poorly that they're
not likely to have a long life.
</P>
<P>
   ABC won its 11th week in a row in the ratings, drawing an
average prime-time audience of 14 million people (9.3 rating, 16
share). As is fast becoming typical, the week's three airings of
''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' were the week's three
most-watched programs.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was second with 11.8 million viewers (8.3 rating, 14 share),
NBC had 9.6 million (6.8, 11), Fox had 8.9 million (5.7, 9), UPN
had 3.7 million (2.6, 4), the WB had 3 million (2.2, 3) and Pax TV
had 1.1 million (0.9, 1)
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ''World News Tonight'' won the evening news ratings race
with 10.5 million viewers last week (7.7 rating, 16 share). NBC's
''Nightly News'' averaged 10 million viewers (7.6, 16), and the
''CBS Evening News'' had 8.2 million viewers (6.3, 13).
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of March 6-12, the top 10 shows, their networks and
ratings were:
</P>
<P>
   ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Tuesday), ABC, 19.5; ''Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Sunday), ABC, 17.5; ''Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire'' (Thursday), ABC, 17.2; ''60 Minutes,'' CBS, 14.7;
''Friends,'' NBC, 13.9; ''The Practice,'' ABC, 13.4; ''ABC News
Special Report: Super Tuesday (8 p.m.), ABC, 13.1; ''Touched By an
Angel,'' CBS, 12.9; ''ABC News Special Report: Super Tuesday (9
p.m.), ABC, 12.0; ''Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS, 11.0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
