<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Aims To Ease First Home Buyers  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Banking Committee approved sweeping
legislation Tuesday designed to make the dream of home ownership
more attainable for millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Expected for a House floor vote this spring, ''The American
Homeownership and Economic Opportunity Act of 2000'' would allow
for reduced down payments for FHA home loans for teachers, as well
as police, fire and other uniformed municipal employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''This completes the last piece of the housing agenda,'' said
Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y. as the committee unanimously passed H.R.
1776 amid an air of bipartisanship. Democrats and Republicans
thanked each other for working through their differences on the
proposed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have produced a very good bill,'' said Rep. John LaFalce,
D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would authorize 1 percent down for FHA mortgage loans
and defers the 2.25 percent up-front FHA premium charged for such
loans until the loan is repaid.
</P>
<P>
   A first-time borrower purchasing a $130,000 home would see their
down payment reduced from $6,300 to $1,300.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm excited about this bill and the homeownership
opportunities it will create,'' said Rep. Darlene Hooley, D-Ore.
''In a lot of communities, teachers and police officers can't
afford to live where they work.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also make it easier for seniors to purchase
long-term care insurance through an FHA reverse mortgage home
program by waiving an up-front fee usually charged by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the bill would allow public housing authorities to
provide low-income housing residents one-time grants for home
purchase down payments instead of monthly Section 8 for rental
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   While the strong economy is credited with boosting home
ownership rates to an all-time high of more than 66 percent,
stubborn gaps exist between sectors of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The rate for whites is at 72.5 percent compared with 45 percent
for blacks and 44 percent for Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the African American and Hispanic communities, for example,
many working families are priced out of the real estate market,''
Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also authorize $25 million in grants for
Homeownership Zones, programs targeted to help low and middle
income people buy homes in large developments to revitalize poor
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require the Department of Housing and Urban
Development to offer some underutilized properties to local
governments or community groups at below market rate prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
