<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Plane Had Not Been De-Iced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The private jet that crashed last week in Moscow,
killing nine people including a prominent journalist and an oil
executive, had not been treated with de-icing liquid before
takeoff, investigators said Tuesday, the news agency ITAR-Tass
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The chartered Yak-40 crashed shortly after taking off from
Moscow's Sheremetyevo-1 airport on March 9. The victims included
noted investigative journalist Artyom Borovik and Ziya Bazhayev,
president of the Oil Alliance company.
</P>
<P>
   Initially there was wide speculation that the plane had been
sabotaged, and a security services spokesman said there was an
indication that the Chechnya-born Bazhayev had been resisting
pressure to give support to Chechen rebels fighting Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Monday that they had ruled out bombing as the
crash cause, but had not excluded sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   ITAR-Tass cited Rudolf Teimurazov, deputy chairman of the
Interstate Aviation Committee, as saying investigators found the
plane had not been de-iced, and that it took off with a
''nonstandard flap position.''
</P>
<P>
   He said these factors may have caused uncontrollable listing
after takeoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
