<HEADLINE> White Farmers Sue Zimbabwe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Farmers' leaders have filed a lawsuit
seeking to force the Zimbabwean government to evict black squatters
who have seized land on white-owned farms, their union said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Commercial Farmers' Union has been urging the government to
remove the squatters, but so far has been ignored, said union
director David Hasluck.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit puts the decision in the hands of the High Court, he
said. The union was awaiting information on when its case will be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters, led by former guerrillas in the country's
independence war, were angered by last month's defeat of a national
referendum that would have empowered President Robert Mugabe to
speed up the seizure of farmland without paying compensation to the
mostly white owners.
</P>
<P>
   Hasluck said squatters were camping on 433 white-owned farms
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with spears, axes, knives and guns, squatters have invaded
549 farms since the beginning of the month, but have since
abandoned 116.
</P>
<P>
   ''There continues to be an escalation in threats against
landowners and demands they sign over land ownership'' or face
death, Hasluck said.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 white farmers own a third of the nation's productive
land.
</P>
<P>
   Though police have promised to remove the occupiers, Mugabe
announced Friday on state television that the squatters could stay.
</P>
<P>
   He said the invasions were a political protest against land
ownership imbalances dating back to the colonial era in Rhodesia,
as Zimbabwe was known before independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers said law and order has since broken down in most farming
districts because Mugabe's remarks, and they argued he should be
impeached for ignoring his presidential oath to uphold the law and
defend the nation's bill of rights, including property rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
