<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow, Nasdaq Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index sustained its
second-worst point drop in history Tuesday, as losses for
pacesetting biotechnology companies spilled over to a broad range
of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq fell 200.61, or 4.1 percent, to close at 4,706.63.
With Monday's 141-point loss, the Nasdaq has shed 6.8 percent in
two sessions; Tuesday's drop was second only to a 229.46-point
slide on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrials followed the Nasdaq, giving up early
gains and closing down 135.89 at 9,811.24. Selling pressure
accelerated in the final half-hour of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Broader market measures also surrendered early gains to finish
lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 24.47 to 1,359.15 and the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies plunged 17.15 to 572.99.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stocks plunged, pulling the rest of the Nasdaq, after
the United States and Britain agreed to openly share data from a
project to decode the human genetic pattern. The agreement halts
several companies' plans to sell genetic data to drugmakers and
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte Pharmaceuticals skidded 53{ to 143{ and Human Genome
Sciences fell 29 3/64. PE Corp.'s Celera Genomics tumbled 47 to 142
on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that while some companies will struggle to find
other sources of revenue, most biotechnology business are involved
in a wide range of projects and won't be adversely affected by the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a bit of an overreaction,'' said Dr. Joseph
Zammit-Lucia, president of Cambridge Pharma Consultancy. ''It's a
little bit of correction in a frothy market.''
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stocks have been among the strongest performers in the
Nasdaq's sharp rise this year, leaving them especially vulnerable
to profit-taking, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you get something that's gone up to that extent, you're
going to get violent shakeouts,'' said Don Selkin, chief investment
strategist at Joseph Gunnar in New York. ''This year, people are
going to have to get used to the volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   As biotech stocks fell, other technology groups succumbed to
profit-taking. Applied Materials, a leading maker of equipment used
in the semiconductor industry, fell 9 3/16 to 178}. Apple Computer
fell 7 1/16 to 114\ and 3Com fell 9{ to 54 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's losses highlighted the extraordinary fluctuations in
the technology-dominated Nasdaq. In the year to date, the index is
up 16 percent, while both the Dow and the S&AMP;P are down. Yet eight
of the Nasdaq's 10 biggest point drops have occurred this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not saying it's straight up, but overall, I think (the
Nasdaq) is the place to be,'' Selkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were not significantly affected by the latest evidence
that the economy continues to grow rapidly. The Commerce Department
reported retail sales rose by 1.1 percent in February. With
Americans continuing to spend freely, feeding the surging economy,
many analysts expect the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates
when they meet next week.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Vitner, economist at First Union Securities, noted that the
retail sales report is less crucial to the Fed than a pair of
reports due out later this week: the Producer Price Index and the
Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   Fears that those reports will show signs of renewed inflation
may be keeping investors off-balance this week. If the Fed does
raise rates at its meeting, it would be the fifth increase since
last June, and the market expects company profits to start showing
the effects of higher borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's weakest component was Alcoa, which fell 6 13/16 to 61\
after agreeing to buy Cordant Technologies Inc., a major supplier
of aluminum airplane parts and solid-fuel rockets, for $2.3 billion
in cash. Analysts said investors were afraid Alcoa was paying too
much for Cordant.
</P>
<P>
   Cordant shares rose 25{ to 55 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
NYSE, where composite volume totaled 1.33 billion shares, compared
with 1.24 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.3 percent,
narrowing its losses from Monday, when it fell 2.8 percent on the
news that the nation's gross domestic product declined for a second
consecutive quarter. The report, which meant Japan's economy is
officially back in recession, has contributed to weakness on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.6 percent, Britain's
FT-SE 100 rose 0.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 1825 </TRAILER>
