<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaw's Supermarkets workers authorize strike  </HEADLINE>
dsfonsho
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Cashiers, clerks, butchers and other
workers at 21 Shaw's Supermarkets around the state Tuesday
authorized a strike over a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 workers will not walk off the job, but their 2-to-1
vote for a strike will be used in a grievance against the company,
union leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract with the United Food and Commercial Workers Union
local 371 expired Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   A new contract was ratified two weeks later, with wage increases
and more benefits, including pensions and health care for full- and
part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, the company and the union have differed on
exactly what the new contract provides.
</P>
<P>
   The company initially agreed the new contract would mean raises
of up to $2.50 an hour for some lower-paid part-time workers and up
to $2 for some full-time workers, said local union president Brian
Petronella.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the company told the union the raises would not
be that large under the new contract, Petronella said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to file a formal grievance on behalf of all
members regarding the company's failure to implement what was
negotiated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's spokesman Bernard Rogan, however, said the company is
interpreting the contract correctly, while the union is not.
</P>
<P>
   ''The union officials apparently misunderstood the proposal,''
Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's strike authorization vote is a violation of the
current and former contract, Rogan said. He did not say what the
company would do about the alleged violation.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to sit back down with the union to ''help them
better understand, since they missed it the first time. It's still
a very good contract,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The union planned to file the grievance with the American
Arbitration Association in Hartford. The case will go to
arbitration if no resolution is reached in 30 days, Petronella
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm prepared to strike, but I'd rather have them go by what
they said in the contract,'' said 20-year-old Adam Ripka of
Stratford, a part-time produce clerk at Shaw's in Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's is based in East Bridgewater, Mass. Its Connecticut
stores are in Bridgeport, Bristol, Clinton, Enfield, Fairfield,
Glastonbury, Hamden, Manchester, New Britain, New Haven, Newington,
Orange, Shelton, Southington, Stratford, Vernon, Wallingford,
Waterbury, Waterford, West Hartford and Willimantic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
