<HEADLINE> By JOHN CURRAN=Associated Press Writer 	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- America's forgotten war will be </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- America's forgotten war will be
forgotten no longer -- at least not in New Jersey. Construction on a
Korean War Memorial is underway.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 Korean War veterans, survivors and friends turned
out Tuesday for the groundbreaking for the $2.5 million memorial to
nearly 800 New Jersey men and women who were killed or lost in the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers plan a brisk construction schedule: A dedication
ceremony is set for July 27.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be a magnificent edifice, a magnificent
tribute to the sacrifices you've made,'' Mayor James Whelan told
war veterans during a sun-splashed ceremony in Brighton Park.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial, which is being built at the intersection of
Boardwalk and Park Place, will feature a 12-foot statue of a
mourning soldier, clutching dog tags. To his left, two soldiers and
a nurse will be seen emerging through a sheet of water that
cascades into a reflecting pool.
</P>
<P>
   Also planned is an eternal flame above a wall featuring the
names of the New Jersey people who died or were missing in action
during the conflict, which lasted from 1950 to 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great that they'll be remembered, especially at such a
prominent location. People from all over the world are going to see
this monument,'' said Bob Moore, 69, of Estell Manor, who served in
the U.S. Navy in the war and was on hand Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some veterans from northern New Jersey had lobbied to have the
memorial built somewhere closer to them. But supporters said the
location, just off the world-famous Boardwalk, was better because
it guarantees pedestrian traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like it right here,'' said Jim Skramovsky, 68, of Elizabeth,
a Korean War veteran. ''More people visit this Boardwalk than go to
Disney World, they tell me. This is the place for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The city donated the land and the casinos, through the state
Casino Reinvestment Development Authority, gave $1 million for the
project. Donations are still being collected to make up a $500,000
shortfall, according to Col. Mike Warner, deputy commissioner of
the state Department of Military and Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are always asking me why we wanted a memorial,'' said
Larry St. Laurent, chairman of the Memorial committee. ''I didn't
want a memorial. I've got it in my head. I wanted it for the
families of those who never came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Maj. Donald Driscoll of Egg Harbor Township, who
disappeared in Korea in December 1950.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, sister-in-law and nephew attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always been known as the forgotten war, but I don't think
it will be forgotten now,'' said Roland Driscoll, his 80-year-old
brother.
</P>
<P>
   For many victims' family members, though, the recognition comes
too late.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm glad we're finally getting one, I just wish it had
happened sooner, so the mothers and fathers could've seen it,''
said Hector Cafferata, 70, who won the Medal of Honor. ''It's a
little late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
