<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Files Complaint Against EU  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States filed a complaint against
the European Union Tuesday, claiming it is unfairly discriminating
against engine mufflers that help older American passenger jets
meet noise standards.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy State Department spokesman James Foley said the complaint
and a request to resolve the long-standing dispute was filed with
the International Civil Aviation Organization in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said the United States remains ready to negotiate to
resolve the issue if the EU suspends its rules and seeks new
international noise standards at the aviation organization.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint seeks the repeal of the EU's noise rules, which
have been adopted but are not slated to take effect until May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States encourages EU member states to join us in
the commitment to uniform global environmental standards for civil
aviation,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the dispute is the use of engine mufflers known
as ''hush kits.''
</P>
<P>
   EU officials say the kits, which reduce noise pollution, do not
meet standards set by the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say the EU rules discriminate against the U.S.
aircraft industry and that Europeans have spurned attempts at
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   If the European regulations are not relaxed, American officials
contend, the U.S. industry faces the potential loss of more than $2
billion, in part because U.S. aircraft equipped with hush kits that
don't meet the European standard won't sell in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Douglass, president and chief executive officer of the
Aerospace Industries Association, called the government's action
''an essential step in ensuring that agreements reached in ICAO
will provide a reliable basis on which the aviation industry can
make investment decisions that will shape the air transport system
for years to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
