<HEADLINE> Conservative PAC to launch anti-Hillary Clinton ads  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A conservative activist from Utah said
Tuesday that his political action committee is about to launch
television ads in New York attacking Senate candidate Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not like Hillary Clinton,'' said Howard Ruff, a ''free
enterprise'' investment guru who has previously helped financed
conservative political causes through his Virginia-based Ruffpac
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a liberal ideologue ... I don't want her to have a power
base in the United States Senate,'' Ruff added.
</P>
<P>
   According to the weekly New York Observer, which reports on the
Ruffpac ads in its Wednesday editions, one of the ads features a
shot of babies and puppies frolicking in New York's Central Park
with a Hillary Clinton-like figure glowering down at them.
</P>
<P>
   ''What do these babies and puppies have in common?'' the ad
asks. ''They have all lived in New York longer than Hillary Rodham
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is running against New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani for the Senate, moved into a house in suburban Westchester
County in January. She had never lived in New York before that.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said Giuliani should
''tell his right-wing friends to stay out of this election.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Right-wing, special-interest groups from around the country
are determined to elect Rudy Giuliani to the Senate because they
know he will be a reliable vote,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said the ad campaign would be run independently of the
Giuliani campaign because coordination would illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on his fund-raising success, Ruff said he hoped to
keep the anti-Clinton spots running throughout the Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's very, very smart and she's tougher than nails,'' Ruff
added.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Giuliani's suppport for abortion and gay
rights, and for gun control, Ruff said there are issues he does not
agree with Giuliani on.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not Hillary Clinton -- that's the best thing about him.''
Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other conservative groups have already aired
anti-Clinton TV spots in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
