<HEADLINE> N. Ireland's Peace Deadline Dead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A May deadline in Northern
Ireland's peace agreement for paramilitary groups to disarm is
effectively dead, the leader of the Irish Republican Army's
political allies said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant unionist politicians quickly accused Sinn Fein
President Gerry Adams of throwing away the only explicit deadline
in the landmark Good Friday agreement reached two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he had little hope that the impasse over disarmament
would be resolved. The IRA's refusal to make any commitment or
gesture on arms prompted Britain to suspend Northern Ireland's new
government on Feb. 11 to avoid a walkout by the pro-British Ulster
Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears very, very obvious that that May 22 deadline no
longer exists,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Other parties were responsible for the deadlock by having
''totally and absolutely confused and subverted the entire
process'' by making demands that were not part of the agreement,
Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McGimpsey, a senior member of the Ulster Unionist Party,
responded that May 22 was ''the only firm date'' included in the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the republican movement is abandoning this important date,
then they must be abandoning their support for the Good Friday
agreement,'' McGimpsey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Friday agreement had pleaded with all the parties ''to
use any influence they may have'' to get paramilitaries to dispose
of their arms by May 22, the second anniversary of the referendum
on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein is under the most pressure on this issue, because of
its close links to the IRA. No other party linked to a paramilitary
group won a seat in the new Northern Ireland assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
