<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Cab Drivers Have Big Brains  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Anyone who's ever taken a taxi in London must have
wondered how the city's cabbies know how to reach even the most
obscure destination without a street map or a hint from their
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   A new study indicates cabbies are working their brains so hard
they become enlarged in the zone associated with navigation -- the
rear hippocampus.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that the drivers' brains adapted to help them store a
detailed mental map of the city, shrinking in one area to allow
growth in another, according to the study, published Tuesday in the
journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that the brain is physically able to change according
to the way it is used could have important implications for people
with brain damage or brain diseases such as Alzheimer's, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in size of parts of the brain have previously been
linked to brain exercises in monkeys and rats. Scientists also have
reported differences in the structure of the brain between
musicians and non-musicians.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest study, researchers at University College, London
University compared the brains of 16 male taxi drivers with those
of 50 other men of a similar age. They found that among the
cabbies, the back of the hippocampus, the part of the brain
associated with spatial memory, was larger than it was in the
comparison group.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the expansion came at the expense of the front of the
hippocampus, which was smaller than normal. Scientists do not know
exactly what that part of the brain does.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very interesting because we now see there can be
structural changes in healthy human brains,'' said the study's lead
author, Dr. Eleanor Maguire, a neurologist at University College.
</P>
<P>
   London taxi drivers are renowned for their encyclopedic
knowledge of the capital's streets. They spend an average of two
years learning the layout of the city's roads by heart before
taking a test to get their licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The study tried to determine whether the drivers' brains were
different because they had to tap their navigation ability more
than other people, thereby causing their brain to change, or
whether they are good at remembering streets because that part of
their brain is enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seems to be a definite relationship between the
navigating they do as a taxi driver and the brain changes,''
Maguire said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings indicate it is more likely that exercising that
part of the brain heavily can lead to changes in its size, because
cabbies who had been on the job 40 years had a larger rear
hippocampus than those who had started more recently, said Malcolm
Brown, a professor of cognitive neuroscience at England's Bristol
University, who was not connected with the study.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the implication down the line would be that an
inactive brain may well eventually lead to loss of brain
function,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire noted it has long been thought that if damage occurs to
the brain, there is only a limited amount of adaptability in an
adult brain that can help people recover.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now direct things in the environment, like navigation, appear
to show changes in the brain so we could in the future see some
rehabilitation programs that use that kind of knowledge,'' Maguire
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 1852 </TRAILER>
