<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. Reach Deal on Data Privacy  </HEADLINE>
By RAF CASERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union and U.S. negotiators
reached a breakthrough in the data protection negotiations Tuesday,
making it possible for a trans-Atlantic deal on the contentious
issue to be concluded over the summer, EU officials said.
</P>
<P>
   EU chief negotiator John Mogg said he will recommend that the EU
parliament and member states back a so-called safe-harbor agreement
that would allow U.S. industry to conduct business with Europe
under strict data privacy conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once definitively agreed by all the parties concerned, this
package will facilitate trans-Atlantic information flows by
providing legal certainty for operators and the safeguards
consumers demand to protect their privacy,'' Internal Market
Commissioner Frits Bolkestein said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 data-privacy law gives EU nations the right to halt
certain information from being sent to countries that do not have
adequate data protection. The United States relies mainly on a
self-regulating system.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed accord, U.S. companies that agree to the safe
harbor guidelines would be regarded as being in compliance with EU
privacy concerns, Mogg said. U.S. companies would guarantee
''adequate protection'' standards when dealing with data from the
15-nation EU.
</P>
<P>
   During the talks, one key problem was solved, namely the way in
which the principles of data protection will be enforced in the
United States. Agreement was also found on the possible sanctions
for non-compliance, EU officials said, though they did not provide
details.
</P>
<P>
   ''Safe harbors now looks set to become a reality,'' Mogg said.
''Companies are free to join as soon as this goes into effect,
around July or August,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The EU had agreed to postpone the data-privacy law's
implementation during the negotiations and Mogg said that he did
not anticipate any problem in data flows until the accord gets
final EU approval.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the general agreement on data flows, the two sides did
not include financial services in the safe harbor accord because
new U.S. legislation on data privacy in the sector was not in
place.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're reserving judgment on financial services until the
legislation is sorted out,'' Mogg said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government is still drafting rules protecting consumer
information under landmark banking legislation enacted last
November.
</P>
<P>
   David Aaron, U.S. Undersecretary of Commerce for International
Trade, said the two sides will continue talks on financial services
once new data privacy rules, which are part of the Financial
Modernization Act, are in place later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The safe harbor guidelines, including the ''adequate
protection'' principle, needs the support of a qualified majority
of member states. Formal approval procedures are expected to be
launched in May, the EU Commission said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
