<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Gets $1 After Police Dog Bite  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Biting a suspect has landed a canine cop in the
doghouse with a federal jury.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors on Monday awarded $1 to Jerome Jarrett after finding that
Shadow, a Belgian Malinois, used excessive force when it made the
collar during a 1994 chase.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, then 27, had sped through Yarmouth in an unregistered
and uninsured car. He eventually crashed into a post and ran from
police. Shadow bit Jarrett on his knee, which required 12 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett eventually served seven months behind bars for violating
terms of his probation on a robbery sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Leonard Kesten, who represented the Yarmouth Police
Department, said Tuesday he would either ask the judge to overturn
the verdict or appeal it. He said it is about the principle, not
the money.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no K-9 police officer in the country or the world
that would not release a dog to chase a suspected felon, like he
was, after the guy disregards warnings,'' Kesten said. ''We can't
let these guys get away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
