<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco To Buy Burmah Castrol  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE STANLEY, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC has agreed to pay $4.7 billion for
one of Britain's oldest oil companies, Burmah Castrol PLC, in hope
of bolstering its share of the world market for lubricants.
</P>
<P>
   The combination announced Tuesday is expected to generate annual
savings of around $260 million by 2003, mainly through elimination
of overlapping supply services and other operations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would result in the loss of about 1,700 jobs worldwide.
A BP Amoco spokesman said it was too soon to say where those cuts
would be made.
</P>
<P>
   London-based BP Amoco has 80,400 employees, while Burmah Castrol
has about 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco's offer of 16.75 pounds ($26.47) per share represented
a 74 percent premium over the closing price for Burmah Castrol
shares on Friday, the last day before the two companies announced
that they were in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Burmah Castrol's share price jumped 24 percent to close at 15.45
pounds ($24.41). BP Amoco shares finished trading at 536.5 pence
($8.48), down 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Burmah Castrol's board has unanimously recommended the offer to
its shareholders, although regulators in Europe and the United
States still must approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   For BP Amoco, the biggest prize of the acquisition is the
Castrol name.
</P>
<P>
   Castrol's sales have outpaced growth in the lubricants market,
especially in developing countries in Asia and Latin America, said
BP Amoco chief executive John Browne. It would become BP Amoco's
leading brand of lubricants.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies plan to merge their existing lubricants
businesses to form a new division based at Burmah Castrol's
headquarters in Swindon, England. David Baldry, now in charge of BP
Amoco's business development group, has been named to head the new
business.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco aims to sell off Burmah Castrol's chemicals division
upon completion of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco said the acquisition would result in a onetime charge
against earnings of around $390 million, to be taken this year.
Browne said he expected to complete the deal by the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
   Burmah Castrol has a colorful history, and its acquisition by BP
Amoco would be an unlikely end to a career that dates back to 1886.
</P>
<P>
   Founded as Burmah Oil, the company discovered the first
commercial quantities of oil in the Middle East. In 1909, it helped
form Anglo-Persian Oil Co. -- the precursor of British Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   Burmah acquired Castrol in 1966 but went bankrupt after fighting
in the Middle East War the following year wrecked its oil tanker
business. The Bank of England bailed the company out, and by the
1980s it had recovered and was earning most of its profits from
Castrol sales.
</P>
<P>
   BP, meanwhile, went from being a poorly managed state-owned
company to a heavyweight of British capitalism. It bought
Chicago-based Amoco Inc. in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate matter, a BP Amoco spokesman declined to comment
on a report in Tuesday's Financial Times that the company was
talking with the U.S. Federal Trade Commission about the possible
sale of its Alaskan oil holdings.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco needs FTC approval to complete a planned $30 billion
buyout of Atlantic Richfield Co. The combined company would control
70 percent of Alaska's crude oil production, and the FTC worries
that it would have too much control over the supply of Alaskan
crude to West Coast refineries.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: BP Amoco: http://www.bpamoco.com
</P>
<P>
   Burmah Castrol: http://www.burmah-castrol.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
