<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. School Shooting Hearing Starts  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH ALTMAN Jr., Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- The boy accused of fatally shooting a
6-year-old girl in an elementary school told a policeman that a
classmate told him to do it, the officer testified Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Kayla Rolland lay wounded in her first-grade classroom at
Buell Elementary School, Mount Morris Township Police Officer
Walter Greenhill asked where the gun was.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged shooter blurted out ''something to the effect of,
'(The classmate) told me to load it up and point it,''' Greenhill --
the first officer at the scene -- testified.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill was the only person who testified before a preliminary
hearing for Jamelle A. James was adjourned. The hearing will allow
a judge to decide if there is enough evidence to try James, 19, on
an involuntary manslaughter charge in Kayla's death.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say James gave the 6-year-old boy access to the
semiautomatic handgun Kayla was shot with Feb. 29. Prosecutors have
said they will not charge the boy because he is too young to
understand his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Arthur Busch said investigators believe the
.32-caliber gun used to shoot Kayla had been left under James'
blankets in a bedroom at the house where the alleged shooter stayed
with his uncle. Authorities believe the boy took the gun to school
to scare Kayla but ended up killing her with one shot.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, defense lawyer Jeffrey Skinner
questioned why Greenhill picked up the gun instead of leaving it in
the desk. He also forced the officer to admit he did not know if
anyone else handled gun before he found it.
</P>
<P>
   No date was set for the hearing to resume.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
