<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Look At Voter Thinking in Primaries  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   A look at voter thinking in Tuesday's Southern primaries,
according to interviews at polling places conducted by Voter News
Service:
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS:
</P>
<P>
   --BUSH SWEEP: As virtually the only candidate still in the race,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush took every demographic group there was to
take -- old, young, rich, poor and every religion. He took liberals,
moderates and conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   --INDEPENDENTS: Even though he's no longer running, Sen. John
McCain got votes from more than 20 percent of independent and
Democratic voters. He had similar support from liberal and moderate
voters.
</P>
<P>
   --BUSH SMARTS: About one in 10 voters said Bush does not have the
knowledge needed to serve as president, a much lower figure than in
earlier primaries when more independents were voting. Among
independents voting Tuesday, about one in five said he did not have
the necessary knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   --BUSH IN TEXAS: Bush did particularly well in his home state,
with nine in 10 GOP voters holding a favorable view of their
governor. Half of voters, both Republicans and Democrats, said Bush
was more conservative as presidential candidate than he was in
1998, when he won a landslide re-election as governor.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS:
</P>
<P>
   --GORE SWEEP: As the only candidate in the race, Vice President
Al Gore won with every group -- old and young, men and women, rich
and poor. He did particularly well among the nearly one-quarter of
voters who are black, taking 95 percent of their votes.
</P>
<P>
   --THEY REALLY LIKE HIM: Across the South, eight in 10 voters had
a favorable view of Gore. He faced his toughest road in Oklahoma
and Louisiana, where a fourth of voters said they had an
unfavorable view.
</P>
<P>
   --BRADLEY IN LOUISIANA: In Louisiana, Bill Bradley was taking
nearly three in 10 votes, running particularly strongly among
whites, conservatives and the poorest voters. Those Bradley voters
said they favored Bush over Gore in November, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   --GORE IN TENNESSEE: Gore walked away with nearly unanimous votes
of every group in his home state. And virtually all the Democratic
voters said they would support him in November.
</P>
<P>
   --CLINTON BACKLASH: Nearly four in 10 voters in the Democratic
primaries disapproved of President Clinton as a person, and about a
quarter of those voted for Bradley, though he had already dropped
out of the race. Just 15 percent disapproved of the job Clinton is
doing, and they split their votes between Gore and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   NOVEMBER MATCH-UP
</P>
<P>
   In each state, voters were asked whom they would support in the
fall Bush-Gore matchup. Across the board, exit polls found Bush in
a stronger position than Gore:
</P>
<P>
   --More than one in 10 Democratic voters said they would vote for
Bush, twice the portion of Republicans who said they'd cross over
to support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   --More than 20 percent of Democrats said they had a favorable
view of Bush. Half as many Republicans had a favorable view of
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   --Bush was attracting nearly a third of conservative Democrats.
Gore was attracting less than a fourth of the liberal Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   --Half the Democrats who voted for Bradley said they would vote
for Bush in the fall. Fewer than four in 10 of McCain voters said
they would vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   --Democrats who said they would vote for Bush tended to be
wealthier, more conservative and younger than the typical
Democratic voter. They were more likely to be white and more likely
to dislike Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   --Republicans who said they would vote for Gore tended to be
younger, poorer, more liberal and more likely to be Hispanic than
the typical GOP voter.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls were conducted by the Voter News Service, a
consortium of The Associated Press and the television networks, at
selected precincts in Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma,
Tennessee and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 3,572 voters in the GOP primaries had an error
margin of plus or minus 2 percentage points, and the poll of 2,855
voters in the Democratic primaries had an error margin of plus or
minus 2.5 points. Margins of error are larger for subgroups,
including individual states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
