<HEADLINE> Consolidated Looks To Boost Stock  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Consolidated Stores Corp., parent of the
K-B Toy store chain, said Tuesday it has hired an investment
banking firm to analyze its strategic alternatives to boost its
stock price and increase shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make sure we're looking at the right things
strategically to get the best value possible,'' Michael Potter,
chief financial officer, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston will review the structure of
Consolidated's businesses and recommend ways to improve operations.
Possibilities include restructuring, divestitures or combinations
or a stock buyback, the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it still intends to go forward with an initial
public offering of shares in its KBkids.com unit.
</P>
<P>
   Potter stressed that Consolidated Stores is not struggling
financially but needs to examine operations because the company's
management believes its stock price is undervalued.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not an expression of weakness, it's an expression of
strength,'' Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus-based company specializes in toys and close-out
merchandise and operates K-B Toy stores, Odd Lots and Big Lots.
</P>
</TEXT>
