<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush Winning McCain's Backers  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush holds a slight advantage among
likely voters in the presidential race against Al Gore and is
drawing more of the John McCain supporters that both he and Gore
are aggressively trying to attract, according to a poll released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has 49 percent to 43 percent for Gore in the
CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. Other recent polls have shown the race
very close or with the vice president slightly ahead, but many of
them polled registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Narrowing the poll to likely voters often improves the numbers
of the Republican candidate, but in this poll the margins for
registered voters and likely voters were very similar.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore effectively wrapped up the Republican and
Democratic nominations for president last week. Bush bested Sen.
McCain of Arizona, who has suspended his campaign, while Gore
defeated former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who has withdrawn
and endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The poll taken Friday through Sunday of 1,006 people had an
error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points for the entire
sample, plus or minus 5 percentage points for the sample of 502
likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   If Reform Party contender Pat Buchanan is included in the mix,
Bush has 47 percent and Gore has 43 percent, while Buchanan draws 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Likely voters were about evenly divided on whether they would
support a Democratic or Republican candidate for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appeal was strongest among men, whites and suburban
dwellers. Gore was strongest among women, minorities, voters over
age 65, urban residents and those with family incomes less than
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll found Bush picking up more of the McCain
supporters:
</P>
<P>
   -- McCain Republicans went 80 percent for Bush to 14 percent for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   -- McCain independents broke 46 percent for Bush to 37 percent
for Gore -- a slight Bush advantage.
</P>
<P>
   -- McCain Democrats favored Gore by 76 percent to 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bush were viewed favorably by about six of 10
Americans. Both were seen as having the knowledge necessary to
serve as president by more than seven in 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   They were evenly matched on the question of who would do the
best job of handling the economy, foreign affairs and the gun
issue. Gore was given better marks on the environment, education,
heath care, Social Security, campaign finance reform and
representing the interests of women. Bush was given the nod on
taxes, improving the country's moral climate, crime and the rising
price of gasoline and fuel oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 2016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000314.0181 </DOCNO>
