<HEADLINE> Magazine Co. Fined For Van Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A magazine subscription company that
employed seven young people killed in a van crash was fined $15,050
for child labor violations involving a survivor who was paralyzed,
the Labor Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still pending is a state agency's recommendation for more than
$200,000 in fines against the company as a result of the crash on
March 25, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Forgues, 15, an employee of Subscriptions Plus, was
paralyzed in the accident just after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ''This young woman should not, by law, have been in that van at
that hour,'' Secretary of Labor Alexis Herman said in a statement.
''One of the department's priorities is to ensure that when youth
work, they do so safely and legally.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen- and 15-year-olds are prohibited from working later
than 7 p.m. during the school year or later than 9 p.m. in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people were killed and five seriously injured in the crash
filled with 14 young people selling magazine subscriptions door to
door.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Jeremy Holmes of Clinton, Iowa, didn't have a valid
driver's license in Wisconsin and panicked when he saw a police
officer about to pull him over for speeding, police said. He tried
to switch places with a passenger and lost control of the van,
according to a criminal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes pleaded guilty to vehicular homicide and was sentenced to
seven years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
