<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
Parliament Gives Aboriginals Say
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Aboriginals will have a say on whether referendum
results give Quebec or any other province the right to secede from
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament passed two amendments Tuesday to Bill C-20, Ottawa's
clarity bill, allowing aboriginals to be among political actors to
pass judgment on the result of any future secession referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The two amendments, proposed by New Democrats, were among 403
changes the Commons has been considering since Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   All but eight amendments came from the Bloc Quebecois, which has
kept the Commons working around the clock to stall passage of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Aboriginals will be among those who will consider whether a
referendum question is clear and whether the result indicates a
clear expression of will to secede by a clear majority of the
population of a province.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Judge: Ludwig Trial Witness Tainted
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- The judge in the Wiebo Ludwig oilpatch
vandalism trial has described a key Crown witness as ''tainted''
and warned prosecutors they'd better have much better evidence if
they hope to secure a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sterling Sanderman made the comments Tuesday after
defense lawyer Paul Moreau became frustrated with the lack of
response from Robert Wraight when asked about the money he received
for becoming an RCMP informant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I quickly came to the conclusion within the first week of this
trial that this witness is a tainted witness, and nothing I've
heard removes this notion from my mind,'' Sanderman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''His primary motivation is monetary, and it will take an awful
lot of other corroborating evidence from Mr. Combe (Crown
prosecutor George Combe) to dispel that.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig and his friend Richard Boonstra face a series of charges
related to sabotage of oil and gas wells in northwestern Alberta.
Wraight is a former friend of the two who said he sympathized with
their environmental concerns but turned against them when he feared
they might use violence to make their point.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Quebecers Get $4.5B Income Tax Cut
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC (AP) -- After enduring years of bad-news budgets,
Quebecers were handed cuts of a different kind Tuesday -- $4.5
billion in income tax reductions over three years.
</P>
<P>
   The tax break was just one of several goodies promised by
Finance Minister Bernard Landry as he presented the 2000-2001
budget.
</P>
<P>
   While on paper the $48.3-billion budget is expected to be
balanced, Landry said the province could eventually post a surplus
of $3.3 billion over the year.
</P>
<P>
   Landry made several references in his speech to sovereignty,
saying the strong economic performance could encourage Quebecers to
be more open to leaving Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-class taxpayers and families will reap the most from the
tax reductions, which include $1 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a family of four with two incomes totaling $50,000
will see an overall tax reduction of $532 in 2000, $1,123 in 2001
and $1,733 in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Chretien Team Stacked With Loyalists
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien announced a campaign
team for the next election Tuesday, reaffirming his intent to run
again a day after some Liberal MPs had mused publicly about whether
it was time for him to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Although he described his team of backroomers as ''a fine mix of
old friends and new voices,'' the old friends were clearly in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith, a Toronto lawyer who was co-chairman the last
campaign in 1997, will do so again. His partner this time will be
Labor Minister Claudette Bradshaw of New Brunswick, whose Atlantic
roots send a signal the Liberals are determined to regain lost
ground in that region.
</P>
<P>
   Others filling key roles include John Rae, a vice-president of
Montreal-based Power Corp. and longtime Chretien confidant, Gordon
Ashworth, a veteran organizer from Toronto, party president Stephen
LeDrew and party executive director Terry Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Drugs Give Cancer Researchers Hope
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. (AP) -- A new treatment being developed by
researchers at the British Columbia Cancer Agency could allow most
cancer patients to take drugs that will stop the disease in its
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs -- which are still about six years from being marketed
-- are a potential breakthrough because they will target and
''switch off'' a gene that plays a blockbuster role in allowing
cancer cells to survive, spread and form a blood supply to keep
them nourished.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're discovering so many genes now and there isn't a single
one that does all three,'' Dr. Shoukat Dedhar said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dedhar and his cancer agency colleagues are collaborating with
Kinetek Pharmaceuticals, a Vancouver drug company.
</P>
<P>
   The gene, called integrin-linked kinase, or ILK, is hyperactive
in cancer cells when another gene that would normally switch it off
is missing, Dedhar said.
</P>
<P>
   The future drugs will be a substitute for the missing gene which
would normally keep ILK in check.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 2033 </TRAILER>
