<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge To Stay in McVeigh Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A judge on Tuesday denied a request by convicted
Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh to disqualify himself from
hearing motions for a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch ruled there was insufficient
evidence to support claims that his previous statements about the
defendant's trial attorney showed partiality and could jeopardize
McVeigh's bid for a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, McVeigh asked the court for a new trial,
claiming his previous lawyer leaked inflammatory stories about him
to the media, including a purported confession.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, McVeigh also accused lawyer Stephen Jones of
promoting a questionable theory about foreign terrorists to stoke
interest in his book about the case.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time that McVeigh has appealed his conviction
and death sentence on murder and conspiracy charges in the April
19, 1995, bombing that killed 168 people. A year ago, the U.S.
Supreme Court refused to hear arguments that his trial was tainted
by jury misconduct and news reports that he confessed.
</P>
<P>
   McVeigh's current attorney, Dennis W. Hartley, requested that
Matsch, who presided over the trial, disqualify himself from
considering motions on the effectiveness of McVeigh's trial
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit, Hartley asserted that statements made in a
memorandum opinion and at two hearings showed ''a clear
predisposition'' regarding any claim about ineffective trial
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   He also filed copies of three letters from Jones to the court
suggesting that they might be construed as an attempt ''to
influence or manipulate the Court'' and ''lend an appearance of
partiality to the proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his ruling Tuesday, Matsch said, ''Nothing in those
letters reflects any views, opinions or statements of the court
with respect to the performance of counsel, and at the times of
their writing, Mr. Jones had completed his representation of Mr.
McVeigh in this court.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Matsch said, '' ... the court concludes that the
affidavit is insufficient to warrant disqualification.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
