<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10-year-old charged with stabbing father who goaded him into it  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- A 10-year-old boy stabbed his father
to death during an argument after the father handed him a kitchen
knife, goading him into it, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was over a missing container of chocolate cake icing
that Andrew Harms, 38, accused the boy of taking.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something so stupid, and now a whole family's lives are
wrecked,'' said neighbor Carol Lightbody, 39.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, a fourth grader whose name wasn't released because he
is a juvenile, has been charged with manslaughter and illegal
possession of a weapon. He was being held without bail Tuesday in
the county's juvenile detention center.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean County Prosecutor E. David Millard said it was unlikely
the boy would get jail time for the killing, because of his age and
the circumstances of the slaying. A judge will decide how long the
boy is held.
</P>
<P>
   A welder by trade, Harms and three of his children lived
together with Harms' fiancee and three of her children in a modest
one-story home located just off Route 37.
</P>
<P>
   The argument occurred about 8:45 p.m. Monday after Harms accused
his son of taking the frosting. Harms, who is 5-foot-11 inches tall
and weighs 175 pounds, led the boy out to the family's detached
garage so they could talk without being heard by the other people
in the house, Millard said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The discussion became heated and emotional. At that point, Mr.
Harms picked up a knife and placed it in the juvenile's hand and
stated that if he hated him that much, then he wanted him to stab
him,'' Millard said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy then plunged the five-inch long kitchen knife once into
Harms' chest. He died an hour later at Community Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy conducted by the county medical examiner, Dr. Hydow
Park, determined the cause of death to be cardiac tamponade, a
condition resulting from the accumulation of excess fluid in the
pericardium around the heart. It commonly results from injuries to
the heart or to major blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Millard would not discuss the prior relationship between the boy
and his father except to say that there had been ''some emotional
turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There had been some buildup,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One person who had been in the house witnessed the slaying,
Millard said. He wouldn't identify them or say what their relation
was to Harms or the boy. The boy's mother, who is separated from
Harms, lives in Manalapan. She was notified about the killing
Monday night, Millard said.
</P>
<P>
   The knife, which has been recovered, had a three-quarter-inch
wide blade.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was arraigned before Family Court Judge Barbara Ann
Villano. He is too young to face charges as an adult -- 14 is the
minimum age in New Jersey for juveniles being waived up to adult
court -- but could get three years if convicted as a juvenile,
according to Millard.
</P>
<P>
   ''The focus with very young offenders like this is usually
toward rehabilitation,'' Millard said.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered the door at Harms' home Tuesday. Two four-wheel
drive vehicles were parked in the driveway, which had a basketball
hoop in front of the garage. Neighbors said Harms and his children
moved in about a year ago but never attracted attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never had a problem with them,'' said one man, who was
walking his dog nearby Tuesday. He didn't want to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   ''What could be so bad in the household that it could come to
this?'' said Lightbody, looking off her porch at the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-14-00 2100 </TRAILER>
