<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Leaving For Cambodia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A seven-member U.N. team was heading to
Cambodia on Tuesday for talks on setting up a U.N.-backed tribunal
to prosecute the surviving leaders of the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   The team was expected to arrive on Thursday and begin talks on
Friday, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said. U.N. officials in Phnom
Penh said they would stay until March 22.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has been negotiating for months with Cambodia
over international participation in a tribunal to judge Khmer Rouge
chieftains, blamed for the deaths of an estimated 1.7 million
Cambodians in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. blessing is crucial to Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen for
the tribunal to be viewed as legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations wants to make sure it has enough control
over the proceedings to ensure that the trial isn't manipulated by
Cambodia's corrupt and politicized judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan was dispatching his top legal and
political aides for the negotiations. He has expressed hope the
talks will produce a final agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 2109 </TRAILER>
