<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Bush's Support More Intense  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush got more intense support from
Southern voters who turned out in Tuesday's GOP primaries than Al
Gore got on the Democratic side, and Bush appears to face less of a
threat of crossover Southern voters in November, according to exit
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls conducted by Voter News Service, a consortium of
the TV networks and The Associated Press, also gave a glimpse of
voter attitudes in the candidates' home states.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, half the Republicans as well as half the Democrats
said Bush was more conservative as a presidential candidate than he
was in 1998, when he won a landslide re-election as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he would make a great president,'' said Fritzie
Faulkner, a 67-year-old resident of Lubbock, who wasn't troubled by
conservatism. ''He's got conservative views and I think you can
trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in Texas, however, were not convinced by Bush's claims that
he has successfully reformed education in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   About four in 10 voters in the Texas GOP primary said the state
has had no significant school reforms in the past six years, and
more than six in 10 voters in the Democratic primary felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, voters in the Republican primary showed a clear
dislike of native son Gore: only one in 20 among GOP voters said
they would vote for Gore in November, and more than four in five
had an unfavorable opinion of their one-time senator.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in several of Tuesday's primary states expect the
Gore campaign, which has been heartened by recent national polls
showing the presidential race is close, to make a determined effort
to carve several Southern states away from the Republicans in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls suggest Gore has plenty of work to do in the region
to compete effectively with Bush. One in eight voters in the
Democratic primaries say they would back Bush in November, while
one in 20 voters in the Republican primaries say they would back
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Margo, a Democrat from Oklahoma City, said he ''voted
against Gore'' in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm for Bush but I couldn't vote for Bush because I'm a
registered Democrat,'' he said, referring to the closed GOP primary
that only allowed party members to cast ballots. But Margo said he
would vote for Bush in November.
</P>
<P>
   One of every 10 voters in the GOP primaries said they had a
favorable view of Gore, while more than one in five voters in the
Democratic primary had a favorable view of Bush. About one in 10
voters said Bush does not have the knowledge needed to serve as
president. Among independents voting in the GOP primaries Tuesday,
about one in five said he did not have the necessary knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's no longer running, Arizona Sen. John McCain got
votes from more than 20 percent of independent and Democratic
voters. He had similar support from liberal and moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls were conducted at selected precincts in the
states of Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee and
Texas. The poll of 5,501 voters in the GOP primaries had an error
margin of plus or minus 1.5 percentage points and the poll of 4,683
voters in the Democratic primaries had an error margin of plus or
minus 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in the Democratic primaries who said they would vote for
Bush tended to be more conservative, white, younger, Bradley
supporters and people who dislike President Clinton personally. In
states where Bill Bradley got his strongest support from Democratic
primary voters, such as Louisiana and Oklahoma, those voters said
they would vote for Bush by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in the GOP primaries who said they would vote for Gore
tended to be lower income, self-described liberals, younger, and
Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will rely heavily in Florida on the support of his brother
Jeb, the governor, whose appeal seems to run along partisan lines,
according to exit polls with a big majority of Republican voters
favorable and a big majority of Democrats unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the voters, seven of 10 independents, in
the Democratic primary had an unfavorable view of President Clinton
personally and a fourth of that group said they would vote for Bush
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Athaleen Watson, a 76-year-old resident of Carthage, Tenn. -- the
same community where Gore cast his presidential primary vote -- said
she's backed Gore ''for as far back as I can remember.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got good times, she said, ''and I'd like to see that
continue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
