<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunbeam Closing Mr. Coffee Plant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Sunbeam Corp. on Tuesday confirmed it plans to
close its Mr. Coffee assembly plant in the Cleveland suburb
Glenwillow, eliminating 339 jobs there.
</P>
<P>
   The small-appliance maker from Delray, Fla., planned to close
the plant in February 1998 as part of a plan to cut costs, but
workers and community leaders campaigned to save the jobs that pay
about $9 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Then in December 1998, Sunbeam and the Teamsters agreed on a
three-year contract that seemed to indicate the jobs were secure.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam spokeswoman P.Y. Rockingham said Tuesday the decision to
close the Mr. Coffee plant followed the company's assessment of its
household products manufacturing and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on those results, the decision was made to integrate the
Glenwilow operations into other company owned facilities,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Coffee distribution and filters production will be moved to
Hattiesburg, Miss., and the assembly work is being moved to
Matamoros, Mexico, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The leased Ohio plant will be closed by the end of June, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to have pride in the work force that has been at
Mr. Coffee for many years. We can't continue to afford operations
there,'' she said. The company expects to save $7.5 million in the
first year after the closing while maintaining sales of the Mr.
Coffee machine and filters, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
