<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wisconsin To Fight Transplant Rules  </HEADLINE>
By JENNY PRICE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin will file a federal lawsuit next
week seeking to block new federal rules intended to change the way
scarce donated organs are distributed, Gov. Tommy Thompson said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said federal rules taking effect Thursday unlawfully
substitute the personal judgment of Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala for that of medical professionals in making
transplant policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''This rule won't save lives; it just allows political
appointees to decide which lives are saved,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules order the nation's transplant network to develop a
new system that would send more organs to the sickest patients.
Wisconsin stands to lose under such a system because its organ
donation rates are high and its patients generally get organs
faster than in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the lawsuit, to be filed Monday will include
several states as plaintiffs, though he could not say how many or
which states would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to comply with the new federal rules, the United Network
for Organ Sharing on Monday agreed to submit a new plan for
distributing donating livers.
</P>
<P>
   Its plan would create a more sophisticated system for ranking
patients on the transplant waiting list, so that those in most
urgent need of transplants rise faster to the top of the list. It
would also create broader areas to distribute livers, so donations
could travel further to reach a sicker patient.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin, which has developed a nationally recognized organ
donation system, opposes these plans, fearing its organs will be
siphoned to other states.
</P>
<P>
   After the proposed new rules were issued nearly two years ago,
the network and many transplant centers, including those in
Wisconsin, complained they would jeopardize small programs that
might lose locally donated organs to larger hospitals in other
communities with more of the sickest patients.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson contended the new rules do nothing to focus federal
resources on how to save more lives and also could cut down on the
number of organs that are donated in Wisconsin and other states
with successful procurement programs.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Newman, a spokesman for United Network for Organ Sharing,
said he could not comment on Thompson's claims until the
organization could review the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The states will argue in their lawsuit that Shalala is exceeding
the authority granted to her by Congress, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   But policy experts in Congress and others believe it would be
unconstitutional for Shalala to lose her authority to set policy.
Legislation pending in Congress would clarify who has authority to
set the transplant policy.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Louisiana has also tried to stop the new rules in
court in a case now on hold. South Carolina has threatened a
lawsuit as well.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, patients in some parts of the country get transplants
much quicker than those in other areas. That's partly because
donated livers are distributed to local patients first, even if a
sicker patient needs one in a neighboring community or region.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,800 people died in 1998 waiting for transplants.
More than 68,000 patients are waiting now, including almost 15,000
waiting for livers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
