<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Million Muslims Begin Pilgrimage  </HEADLINE>
By BASSEM MROUE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MECCA, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Chanting ''at thy service, my God, at
thy service,'' more than 2 million Muslims began trekking to a
desert plain outside Mecca on Tuesday for an annual pilgrimage that
fulfills one of the most sacred duties of their faith.
</P>
<P>
   On foot and packed in cars, buses and trucks -- some even
clinging to the roofs of vehicles -- the pilgrims streamed toward a
tent city in Mina, where they will spend Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's overwhelming. Especially since this is the first time I
experienced the pilgrimage,'' said George Gorin, a 60-year-old
native of San Francisco who converted from Catholicism to Islam
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hajj, or pilgrimage, is required at least once of every
able-bodied Muslim who can afford it. It involves several rituals
including praying at the desert plain of Mina -- three miles from
Mecca -- where Muslim faithful believe the Prophet Abraham intended
to sacrifice his son Ishmael to prove his faith in God. In
Christian and Jewish tradition, Abraham tried to sacrifice his
other son, Isaac.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no idea that the pilgrimage is totally demanding. But,
God willing, when I finish the hajj I hope I will be closer to
God,'' said Gorin, who was introduced to the Koran, the Muslim holy
book, by his Iranian-American wife.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn Wednesday, pilgrims will pray at Mina and resume their
journey to Mount Arafat, a gentle hill 12 miles southwest of Mecca
where Muslims believe the last passage of the Koran was revealed to
Islam's Prophet Mohammed during his final sermon.
</P>
<P>
   After a day spent praying at Arafat, pilgrims return to Mina to
throw stones at three pillars representing the devil as part of
another ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the pilgrims began arriving in Mecca weeks earlier. In
Mecca, they must circle the Kaaba, a large cubic stone structure
covered with a black cloth made of about 1,000 pounds of silk, and
Islam's most sacred site. Muslims around the world turn toward its
geographical position while praying.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 2.1 million people are taking part in the hajj, one
of the five pillars of Islam, which has 1 billion followers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's King Abdullah and a host of dignitaries from around the
world will be among the pilgrims, mingling in rituals that are
meant to blur the difference between prince and pauper.
</P>
<P>
   Men must arrive wearing identical two-piece seamless white
robes, and women must dress modestly and cover their hair.
</P>
<P>
   Shaaban Hassan Ahmed of Egypt said that the discomforts of the
hajj, including long hours spent under the desert heat of 97
degrees inspire compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ''During hajj we feel very tired and this makes us remember that
there are people suffering around the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hajj has frequently been marred by tragedy, the most recent
in 1998 when more than 100 pilgrims were trampled to death in a
stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Two women pilgrims from the Russian republic of Dagestan were
killed and four others injured in a bus accident Tuesday and a
Kuwaiti boy and his parents died in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, six Palestinian and Jordanian pilgrims were crushed
to death inside Mecca's Grand Mosque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
