<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Cut Plan Said Unconstitutional  </HEADLINE>
By REBECCA COOK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Washington state's version of a tax revolt has
been quashed.
</P>
<P>
   A judge ruled Tuesday that a voter-approved measure scrapping a
progressive tax on automobiles and motor homes in favor of a $30
flat fee was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, passed by 56 percent of voters in November, also
required a public vote for all tax and fee increases.
</P>
<P>
   King County Superior Court Judge Robert Alsdorf said Initiative
695 violated the state constitution's ''single-subject rule'' by
dealing with two topics.
</P>
<P>
   The car registration fee will remain $30, at least until the
state Supreme Court rules on the case. The public vote requirement
was struck down immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a representative democracy, citizens delegate authority to
their elected representatives ... to decide certain questions on
behalf of the citizenry,'' the judge wrote. ''A representative
democracy does not contemplate, let alone necessitate, a direct
vote of the citizens on every act of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision touched off a flurry of activity in the state
capital, with lawmakers rushing to declare their intent to maintain
the $30 car tabs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The voters were very clear that they do not like, they hated,
the high license tab fees that existed in the State of
Washington,'' Gov. Gary Locke said. ''Despite the court's ruling,
$30 license tabs are here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office plans to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think today's ruling was despicable,'' said the measure's
sponsor, Tim Eyman, who runs a mail-order fraternity watch
business.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of groups challenged the initiative. Transit union
workers were the first to file suit on Nov. 18, just weeks after
the initiative's passage.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative tore a $750 million hole in the budgets of state
and local programs, and hit transit programs especially hard. Bus
routes have been cut and transit workers have lost jobs as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Mike Subit, who represented Amalgamated Transit Union
Local 587 in the challenge, said the ruling upheld the integrity of
the initiative process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Judge Alsdorf courageously recognized that whatever the
popular sentiment is, the constitution should be enforced,'' Subit
said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Washington State Courts site:
http://www.courts.wa.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
