<HEADLINE> Raptors 85, Warriors 78  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Vince Carter scored 23 points, including 11 in
the fourth quarter after returning from a sprained left ankle, as
the Toronto Raptors dealt the Golden State Warriors their seventh
straight loss, 85-78, on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy McGrady added 20 points and Kevin Willis had 12 points and
15 rebounds for the Raptors, who have won nine of 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Carter got tangled up with teammate Charles Oakley midway
through the third quarter. He immediately fell to the floor and
laid there for three minutes before a trainer and two teammates
helped him off the court.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to a huge ovation at the start of the fourth
quarter, with the Raptors down by five. Toronto outscored the
Warriors 29-17 in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter made a fadeway jumper and three 3-pointers to lead the
comeback. His final shot from beyond the arc gave Toronto an 83-73
lead with 2:06 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hughes had a game-high 25 points for the Warriors, who led
45-39 at halftime.
Notes: Toronto's Antonio Davis (strained right calf) did not play,
and coach Butch Carter gave no timetable for a return. John Thomas
started in his place. ... The Raptors activated forward Michael
Stewart and announced they placed 3-point specialist Dee Brown on
the injured list with an upper respiratory infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
