<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors Hear Tapes in Edwards Trial  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIE GOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Jurors in the corruption trial of Edwin
Edwards on Tuesday heard tapes of the former governor assuring a
NFL franchise owner that they could get their hands on a
confidential state gambling document.
</P>
<P>
   The document was a state police report on applicants for the
state's final riverboat casino license.
</P>
<P>
   Former San Francisco 49ers owner Edward DeBartolo Jr. was one of
those applicants and hoped the report would give him helpful inside
information, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a four-term governor who had left office, is accused of
extorting $400,000 from DeBartolo, whose involvement in the case
cost him control of the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if you're able to get a copy of this and it might
be difficult but maybe you can find out what'' some of the
questions are, DeBartolo says in the February 1997 telephone
conversation taped by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm already working on that,'' Edwards replied.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Edwards tells DeBartolo, ''Hey, I'll have that
summary in my hands about five this evening. You want me to Fed-Ex
it to you?''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Edwards mailed a copy of the report to
DeBartolo the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and six others -- including his son, Stephen, and state
Sen. Greg Tarver -- are accused in a scheme to extort money from
applicants for valuable casino licenses. They have been on trial
since Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say most of the schemes began during Edwards' final
term in office, which ended in January 1996. However, the DeBartolo
scheme allegedly happened after Edwards left office but retained
considerable political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, DeBartolo is expected to testify that Edwards
demanded the $400,000 in return for helping him land the riverboat
license. Defense lawyers say it was a legal consulting fee.
</P>
<P>
   On the tapes played Tuesday, Edwards also tells DeBartolo that
he was rounding up support from the state gambling board.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm talking to members of the commission and others that are
interested in this thing to see if I can get them to consider
granting a license,'' Edwards said in an Oct. 18, 1996, telephone
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent Geoffrey Santini, who took the witness stand to
interpret the tapes, noted that members of the gambling board that
awarded riverboat casino licenses were banned by gambling board
rules from discussing the applications.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeBartolo eventually received the license, he dropped
the project after he was summoned before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo pleaded guilty in 1998 to one count of failing to
report a felony. He received a suspended sentence, was fined $1
million and agreed to testify against Edwards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
