<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Aims For Fast Peace Deployments  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Despite a campaign aimed at speeding up
the deployment of peacekeepers, a U.N. official said Tuesday that
it still takes three to four months to get the troops to world
trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons is that countries are offering foot
soldiers and not enough transport and logistical support, said
Erkki Platan of the U.N. Department of Peacekeeping Operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to push toward rapid deployment, which is still
far away,'' he said, adding that the world body has been successful
in getting more countries to put troops on standby.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has never had support for establishing a
standing army. But since 1992, it has been trying to get member
states to make advance commitments of troops so it can respond
quickly to threats to peace.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 88 countries have expressed their willingness, and 32
have made formal commitments -- most importantly, NATO members
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Denmark, and
Spain, plus Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the United Nations has commitments for 147,500
personnel, the bulk of them infantry units, some of which have been
deployed. Britain has offered a brigade with about 8,000 troops and
France has offered 5,000 troops -- with major logistical support.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual report on standby peacekeeping arrangements
circulated Tuesday, Secretary-General Kofi Annan welcomed the
increased participation, compared to December 1998, when 81
countries expressed willingness to take part, 22 made formal
commitments, and some 104,000 personnel could be called on.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations is handicapped in its peacekeeping
operation because countries who have made formal commitments still
have the right to say yes or no to any U.N. request for help.
</P>
<P>
   According to Annan's report, some 60 percent of the confirmed
standby resources can be ready to embark within 30 days of a formal
request from the United Nations -- but that leaves the question of
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the only country with strategic aircraft
that can transport heavy military equipment and large numbers of
troops, Platan said. But the United States has not made a formal
commitment to the U.N. standby program, although it has provided it
with a list of capabilities that could be used.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to go through commercial transportation, and this is
taking a lot of time, and especially sea transportation is very
time consuming,'' said Platan, who heads the peacekeeping
department's one-man Standby Arrangements Unit.
</P>
<P>
   As of the end of January, the United Nations had one brigade
with a command staff based in Denmark ready for deployment. It was
formed by a number of small and medium-size countries participating
in the standby program. Their troops have trained and their
equipment is ready -- minus transport.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is pushing for this model to be used
elsewhere, and Platan cited efforts in central Asia, southern
Africa and the Baltic countries to create combined forces for
possible U.N. deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overall goal is to achieve wider participation in, and
support for, the standby arrangements,'' Annan said. ''While the
United Nations still does not have a true rapid reaction
capability, the standby arrangements have been a positive step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
