<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mogilny, Barrasso Traded  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Ray Bourque and Doug Gilmour already landing in new places,
the NHL's trade deadline passed with little fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest names to be dealt before Tuesday's 3 p.m. EST
deadline were Tom Barrasso and Alexander Mogilny.
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso was traded by the Pittsburgh Penguins to the Ottawa
Senators for fellow goalie Ron Tugnutt and defenseman Janne
Laukkanen.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel Tom Barrasso can help us win,'' Ottawa general manager
Marshall Johnston said. ''In the end, we felt this would help our
hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny, who starred with the Buffalo Sabres, was sent by the
Vancouver Canucks to the Eastern Conference-leading New Jersey
Devils for centers Brendan Morrison and Denis Pederson.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve trades were made Tuesday involving 23 players. It is the
fewest deals made on deadline day since 1993. Last year, 30 players
changed teams in a record 21 trades.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque and Gilmour were both dealt in the days leading up to
the deadline. The Colorado Avalanche acquired Bourque, who played
his first 21 NHL seasons with Boston. Gilmour was sent from Chicago
to the Buffalo Sabres, who also acquired Chris Gratton in a
separate trade with Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso, who won the Stanley Cup with the Penguins in 1991 and
1992, has only played in 18 games this season. He hasn't played in
over a month after taking a leave of absence to be with his ailing
father, who died last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins are in a tight playoff race and felt trading the
potential free agent now was the best move. The deal was the last
in a series of five -- in less than 24 hours -- that saw Pittsburgh
turn over its roster.
</P>
<P>
   ''We brought in a group of players we feel could be key
components not just to get us into the playoffs, but for years to
come,'' Penguins GM Craig Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Tugnutt will share goalie duties in Pittsburgh with
Jean-Sebastien Aubin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had two or three good years,'' Tugnutt said of his time
with Ottawa. ''It's kind of disappointing. There were some rumors,
but it was continuously said we wouldn't be making a move for a
goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins also acquired goalie Tyler Moss and forward Rene
Corbet from Calgary for defenseman Brad Werenka; left wing Josef
Beranek from Edmonton for left wing German Titov; and defenseman
Dan Trebil from Anaheim for a fifth-round pick in this year's
draft.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Pittsburgh sent Pavel Skrbek to Nashville for fellow
defenseman Bob Boughner.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils and Canucks got together on a trade, but Mark Messier
is still in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny, who had his best season in 1992-93 with Buffalo when he
scored 76 goals, has 21 goals and 17 assists this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to a good hockey club that has the chance to go all
the way this year,'' Mogilny said. ''It's very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Messier, rumored to be heading to New Jersey, stayed put. He has
a no-trade clause and Burke didn't ask him to waive it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is a testament to Mark's character that he did not
ask for a trade and he wants to continue to lead this charge and
I'm thrilled with that,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   The Canucks are six points behind San Jose for the final playoff
spot in the West.
</P>
<P>
   In other deals Tuesday, Atlanta traded right wing Ed Ward to
Anaheim for a conditional 2001 draft pick. The Thrashers then sent
right wing Kirby Law to Philadelphia for Vancouver's sixth-round
pick in 2000 and a conditional selection in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers, who lost out in last week's bidding for Bourque,
also made a second trade. Philadelphia sent enforcer Sandy
McCarthy, who recently saw his playing time cut, to Carolina for
center Kent Manderville.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville sent right wing Sergei Krivokrasov to Calgary for
defenseman Cale Hulse and a third-round pick in the 2001 draft. The
Predators also traded goalie Corey Hirsch to Anaheim for future
considerations and acquired center Petr Sachl for the New York
Islanders for a ninth-round pick in the June draft.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sillinger relocated in Florida as the Tampa Bay Lightning
sent him to the Panthers for forwards Ryan Johnson and Dwayne Hay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 2215 </TRAILER>
