<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell Wednesday morning after
sharp drops on Wall Street. The dollar slipped against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 230.79 points,
or 1.21 percent, to 18,911.05 at the end of the morning session. On
Tuesday, the average fell 48.09 points, or 0.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.01 yen at late morning, down 0.14 yen from
late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of
105.05 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, high-priced high technology issues and
telecommunication stocks were leading the market down, dampened by
the Nasdaq composite index's plunge Tuesday on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Nasdaq fell 200.61, or 4.1 percent, to close at
4,706.63, its second-worst point drop in history. The Dow Jones
industrial average closed down 135.89, to 9,811.24.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market looks set to test the downside,'' said Hiroichi
Nishi, an equities manager at Nikko Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 10.86 points, or 0.69 percent, to 1,592.83.
The TOPIX closed up 23.82 points, or 1.5 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar's slip came after major
Japanese banks sold the greenback and amid some profit-taking in
early Tokyo trading.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the dollar moved as low as 104.96 yen at one point
in the morning, but recovered some of its early losses as players
bought back the U.S. currency amid concern over possible central
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The yen's strength in recent days has been based on some
positive factors such as rising machine orders and capital
expenditure, despite a 1.4 percent contraction in gross domestic
product in the October-December quarter.
</P>
<P>
   GDP is a major indicator representing the total amount of goods
and services produced in a given period.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the Bank of Japan intervened on the foreign
exchange market in Tokyo in an attempt to stem the yen's rise.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese government officials have said a strong yen could hurt
the country's already ailing economy by making exports more
expensive, and cutting into earnings of exporting companies.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 101.48 yen, up from
101.22 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.8000 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.7950 percent. Its
price fell 0.04 point to 100.00.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
