<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressRachel Cohen:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rachel Cohen, a young mayoral employee who
helped organize the city's millennium celebrations, died Tuesday of
meningitis. She was 27.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Cohen, who worked on the NYC2000
mayoral committee, contracted meningitis over the weekend and
became ill Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He said that for 14 months, Cohen was ''an integral part'' of
NYC2000, which organized the celebrations that drew worldwide
praise, including last year's Times Square fashion show.
Richard Collier:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Richard Collier, a character actor who
appeared in more than 1,000 television shows and such movies as
''Hello, Dolly!'' and ''Blazing Saddles,'' died Saturday. He was
80.
</P>
<P>
   Collier, whose credits include the children's television show
''Mr. Giggles,'' died at the Motion Picture &AMP; Television Hospital,
where he had been living since April.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston native, Collier performed in theaters and clubs in
Massachusetts before an Army stint during World War II. After the
war, Collier began acting.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared in early TV shows such as ''Playhouse 90,'' ''Lux
Video Theater'' and ''Philco Theater,'' and had had guest spots on
''Bonanza,'' ''The Andy Griffith Show,'' ''Batman,'' ''The Beverly
Hillbillies'' and ''The Big Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier played Dr. Sam Johnson in ''Blazing Saddles,'' and
Walter Matthau's barber in ''Hello, Dolly!''
Paul Jolles:
</P>
<P>
   BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- Paul R. Jolles, a Swiss diplomat who
played a key role in postwar economic accords, died Friday. He was
80.
</P>
<P>
   A notice signed by the family in Swiss newspapers Tuesday said
Jolles died unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   Jolles was secretary to the chief of the Swiss delegation in the
negotiations that led to the so-called Washington accord of 1946.
That agreement was meant to wrap up neutral Switzerland's
obligations to the Allies at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview with The Associated Press in 1996 that
Swiss and U.S. officials missed an opportunity at the time to find
a solution to missing Holocaust-era assets.
</P>
<P>
   Jolles is credited with being the most important architect of
Swiss economic foreign policy since the war, culminating with a
1972 free trade treaty with the European Common Market.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement from government service in 1984, Jolles
became chairman of the board of Swiss food giant Nestle. He also
was a board member of the Art Museum of Bern.
Robert H. Kaul:
</P>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) -- Robert H. Kaul, a state Supreme Court
justice from 1965 to 1977, died Monday. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Before his appointment to the state's highest court by former
Gov. William Avery, Kaul served as Pottawatomie County attorney,
assistant state insurance commissioner and a district court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Kay McFarland, who joined the Supreme Court the
year Kaul retired, said she was most impressed by his humor,
analytical ability and common sense.
Joseph ''Bo'' Sullivan:
</P>
<P>
   MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) -- Joseph ''Bo'' Sullivan, a former
gubernatorial candidate and state Republican Party leader, died
Monday of a stroke. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Sullivan ran in the Republican primary for the New
Jersey gubernatorial nomination, losing to future Gov. Thomas Kean.
</P>
<P>
   From 1982 to 1988, he served as chairman of the New Jersey
Turnpike Authority and was later appointed finance chairman of the
New Jersey Republican Party. Sullivan also served as co-chairman of
former President Bush's New Jersey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 40 years, Sullivan was president and chief
executive officer of Bomont Industries of Pennsylvania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
