<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Attacks Gore After Primary  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Nomination in hand, George W. Bush had two
victorious words for his home-state supporters Tuesday night:
''Mission accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he quickly added that he was only halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   After sealing the Republican presidential nomination in a sweep
of Southern primaries, including his home state, the Texas governor
celebrated his triumph but said he knew he faced a tough battle
with Vice President Al Gore, who also wrapped up the Democratic
nomination Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his comments during an evening rally that was briefly
interrupted by death-penalty protesters. Earlier in the evening,
Texas put to death a killer who spit out a handcuff key as lethal
drugs took effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I filed for president, I pledged I'd come home to Texas
with the nomination of my party. Well, tonight we can say: Mission
accomplished,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose father lost the White House to Bill Clinton in the
1992 election, said, ''Tonight we are halfway to our goal -- but
only halfway -- halfway to ending the Clinton-Gore era in
Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   ''To get there, we must face one more Clinton-Gore campaign.
This last week has been a preview. It's been a preview that the
Gore campaign will say anything to try to win at any cost. We will
confront their tactics one more time, and this time, we will
prevail and they will fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing ahead to the general election campaign, Bush used part
of his victory speech to criticize Gore for focusing on an
education plan that centers on building more schools and hiring
more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed phasing out federal funding of failing schools
and giving the money to parents in the form of vouchers so they can
seek alternative schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in his approach is student testing devised and
administered by local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to solve our education problems; Al Gore wants to
subsidize them. I will work for children and their parents; he will
work for the entrenched interests that funds his campaigns,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   He had other criticism of the vice president, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore can't solve campaign finance problems when he
symbolizes them. He can't talk about rebuilding the military when
his administration has dismantled our military. And he can't
distance himself from the president when, for eight years, he's
served as cheerleader-in-chief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was joined on stage by a bevy of Texas politicians,
including Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison. As the crowd waited for him to
come on the stage, it booed heartily when a large-screen TV showed
Democratic former Gov. Ann Richards, whom Bush defeated in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's big day started at 6:30 a.m., when his cats
scratched at his bedroom door and he went downstairs in the
Governor's Mansion to feed them.
</P>
<P>
   He later ran three miles, before spending the rest of the
afternoon with his wife, Laura, at the Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   As he concluded his speech, he used a line that brought a huge
ovation from the crowd and put a smile to his face: ''I'm proud to
stand before you as Republican nominee for president of the United
States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-14-00 2239 </TRAILER>
