<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Vows To Halt Soft Money Ads  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Al Gore promised to hold off on ''soft
money'' TV ads in the general election as long as George W. Bush
does the same, issuing a fresh challenge to his rival after barely
a moment to celebrate Southern victories that assured the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore put Republican Bush on notice for ''a very tough fight''
between now and November -- especially in Florida, a state some
Democrats had once written off because Bush's brother, Jeb, is the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the night that we crossed the delegate threshold and I
wanted to symbolize by my presence here that Florida is a key
battleground state in November,'' Gore said. The former senator
from Tennessee declared himself a grateful ''son of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring previous calls for banning unregulated soft money
campaign donations -- a stance Republicans suggest is merely an
attempt to neutralize Bush's money advantages -- Gore said he was
instructing his party to hold off on ''issue ads'' on his behalf
unless the Republicans start them first for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Such ads, paid for with the unlimited interest-group
contributions called soft money, have been used by the parties as a
way of aiding their presidential candidates without technically
violating campaign finance rules.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a playful mood all day, had aides find him a computer
at Leon High School in Tallahassee so that, before his Election
Night victory speech, he could type the challenge in an e-mail to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the message's subject line, which Gore read aloud from the
screen, he typed, ''Hello and congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor and son of the former president, also
secured enough Republican delegates in Tuesday's balloting to
guarantee him the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will take the first step,'' Gore wrote. ''It's up to you and
your party whether you want to start the ad war arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush proved his fund-raising clout last year with a record $70
million haul and, even though he spent most of that during the
primaries, can doubtless raise more. Gore is accepting federal
matching funds and must therefore abide by fund-raising and
spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore reached out to Bush, he slapped him for advancing
what Gore habitually calls a ''risky tax scheme'' assembled by
special-interest campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally of supporters in the Leon High gymnasium, Gore
contrasted his agenda -- ''using our prosperity wisely,'' he said --
to what he saw as Bush's approach: ''putting (the budget surplus)
into that special-interest roulette wheel from the 1980s that drove
our economy into the ditch.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Gore voted for himself in rural Tennessee,
where he and his wife, Tipper, keep a small farm. After 2{ grueling
months of virtually nonstop travel, Gore promised to keep up the
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's a falloff of attention in the news media, that's
fine,'' Gore told a reporter at the Forks River School where he
cast his vote in the Tennessee primary. ''But in terms of my effort
to communicate directly with voters, there will be no letup at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Gore would contest not just Florida, which he visited
twice in as many days this week, but other Southern states
considered traditional Republican strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   As if to symbolize his commitment, Gore was fortified throughout
the day Tuesday by Southern home cooking -- bacon and eggs for
breakfast, fried chicken for lunch, ribs and barbecue for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he was spending this momentous day, the man who ran
for the Democratic nomination in 1988 and has been angling for the
presidency at least that long, responded with a jokingly exhaustive
accounting:
</P>
<P>
   ''I got up early, read my CIA briefings, the newspapers, went
for an hour-long run back in the hills behind my house and then I
showered and shaved and got dressed and put on my boots, visited my
mother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
