<DOCNO> APW20000314.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-14 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs 94, Hawks 79  </HEADLINE>
By KELLEY SHANNON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Sean Elliott completed his comeback to the
NBA on Tuesday, returning to play for San Antonio seven months
after a kidney transplant as the Spurs defeated Atlanta 94-79.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who played 12 minutes and shot 1-for-3 from the field,
missed a 22-foot jumper and a layup in the third quarter. Then,
with a quick step around defender Roshown McLeod, he brought wildly
cheering Alamodome fans to their feet with a dramatic dunk five
minutes into the period.
</P>
<P>
   He drove the lane and slammed the ball down with his right hand.
Spurs teammate Mario Elie joined in the applause, clapping as he
ran back down the court. Hawks center Dikembe Mutombo simply
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's basket sparked a 6-0 scoring scoring spurt for San
Antonio, though Atlanta quickly recovered and pulled ahead 66-64 by
the end of the third.
</P>
<P>
   The score remained close as the fourth quarter got under way,
but the Spurs moved ahead 76-75 on a basket by David Robinson with
7:21 left to play. Robinson followed by scoring the next five
points, upping San Antonio's edge to 81-75 with 3:40 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta could get no closer the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson led San Antonio with 26 points and eight rebounds,
while Avery Johnson had 22 points and 10 assists and Tim Duncan had
21 points and 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jackson scored 22 points for the Hawks, and Mutombo had 14
points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   As the final seconds of the game clocked ticked away, the fans
shouted, ''We want Sean! We want Sean!''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott became the first pro athlete in a major sport to return
to competition after a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Although Spurs coach Gregg Popovich had been saying he would use
Elliott as a reserve, he started at small forward and played the
first five minutes, grabbing a defensive rebound and recording one
assist.
</P>
<P>
   On the Spurs' first possession, he slipped slightly as he passed
to Johnson. Later on, he fell again as he drew rough contact from
Mutombo under the Spurs' basket.
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott seemed unfazed and played on until he was replaced
by Jerome Kersey. Elliott started the third quarter, playing seven
minutes that period.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, 32, now in his 11th season, received a kidney from his
older brother Noel in transplant surgery Aug. 16. He said from the
start he hoped to resume his basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott wanted to make his comeback at a home game in front of
family, friends, his doctors and San Antonio fans. A total of
26,708 spectators showed up to watch, filling some upper sections
of the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs got off to a quick start, leading 23-14 by late in the
first quarter. But the Hawks closed to 25-22 by the end of the
period and, thanks to a barrage of jumpers by Jim Jackson and
LaPhonso Ellis in the second, led 47-44 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The National Kidney Foundation announced Tuesday that
Elliott will serve as spokesperson for its 2000 U.S. Transplant
Games to be held June 21-24 in Orlando, Fla. The Olympic-style
competition is for athletes who have had all types of organ
transplants. ... San Antonio shot 51 percent compared with 42
percent for Atlanta, but the Hawks outrebounded the Spurs 42-39.
... Steve Kerr (right knee) and Terry Porter (left knee sprain)
were on the injured list for the Spurs. The Hawks had no one on the
injured list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
