<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, March 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nominations Clinched, Bush With Advantage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As both presidential candidates clinched their party's
nominations in the Southern primaries tonight, a new poll shows George W. Bush
with a slight advantage among likely voters in the presidential race against Al
Gore. Bush is also drawing more of the John McCain supporters that both he and
Gore are aggressively trying to attract, according to the poll released today.
The Texas governor has 49 percent to 43 percent for Gore in the CNN-USA
Today-Gallup poll. Other recent polls have shown the race very close or with the
vice president slightly ahead, but many of them polled registered voters.
Narrowing the poll to likely voters often improves the numbers of the Republican
candidate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S., Britain Urge Open Gene Access
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shares in biotechnology companies hoping to profit from
the sale of genetic data were hammered today after the United States and Britain
agreed to openly share data from a groundbreaking project to decode the human
genetic pattern. The two governments are the leading players in the nonprofit
Human Genome Project, which plans to publish a full genetic map on the Internet
by 2003. The information, which President Clinton called ''the scientific
breakthrough of the century, perhaps of all time,'' would be available free to
scientists and researchers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Tosses School Voucher Law
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A judge today threw out the nation's first
statewide school voucher system, ruling that Florida's Constitution bars public
money from being spent on private education. Gov. Jeb Bush, who championed the
program, promised to find the money to keep it going despite what happens in
court. An appeal is certain. ''We'll raise the money,'' Bush said. ''This is the
first inning of a long drawn out legal battle.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Releases China Trade Text
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, under pressure from Congress,
released the text of its landmark trade agreement with China today and pledged
intensive enforcement to ensure that China opens its markets. Administration
officials insisted the 250 pages of detailed text that it sent to each member of
Congress and released to news organizations confirm its claims that U.S.
exporters stand to reap billions of dollars from lowered trade barriers promised
by China. Opponents quickly seized on what they view as serious shortcomings of
the agreement: the lack of protections for workers, the environment or human
rights.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge To Stay in McVeigh Appeal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A judge today denied a request by convicted Oklahoma City
bomber Timothy McVeigh to disqualify himself from hearing motions for a new
trial. U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch ruled there was insufficient evidence
to support claims that his previous statements about the defendant's trial
attorney showed partiality and could jeopardize McVeigh's bid for a new trial.
Earlier this month, McVeigh asked the court for a new trial, claiming his
previous lawyer leaked inflammatory stories about him to the media, including a
purported confession.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Aims For Fast Peace Deployments
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Despite a campaign aimed at speeding up the deployment
of peacekeepers, a U.N. official said today that it still takes three to four
months to get the troops to world trouble spots. One of the main reasons is that
countries are offering foot soldiers and not enough transport and logistical
support, said Erkki Platan of the U.N. Department of Peacekeeping Operations.
''We're trying to push toward rapid deployment, which is still far away,'' he
said, adding that the world body has been successful in getting more countries
to put troops on standby.
</P>
