<HEADLINE> Part of Tivoli Gardens For Sale  </HEADLINE>
By JAN M. OLSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Part of the famed Tivoli gardens,
Copenhagen's landmark amusement park and an inspiration for
Disney's theme parks, was put on sale Tuesday by the Carlsberg
breweries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a professional corporate decision'' to put Carlsberg's
43 percent share in the park on sale, said Carlsberg chief
executive Flemming Lindeloev. ''We wouldn't have done so if we
should have acted with our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindeloev, whose company is seeking to sell of non-core
operations to concentrate on beer production, said he already had
several foreign and Danish bidders, but he declined to identify
them.
</P>
<P>
   Potential buyers include the Disney group, pop singer Michael
Jackson and the Oklahoma City-based Premier Parks, which owns some
30 amusement parks in the United States and in Europe, Danish media
said.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1843, the 100,000 square-yard park with hundreds of
trees and thousands of flowers is an oasis in the heart of
Copenhagen. Its roller coaster dates from 1914, the merry-go-round
turns to old-fashioned hurdy-gurdy music and the pantomime theater
is one of Europe's last stages keeping Commedia dell'Arte
traditions alive.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 3.7 million people visited the park -- one-third of
them foreigners -- making it the third most-visited amusement park
in Europe, behind Disneyland Paris and Britain's Blackpool Pleasure
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney visited Tivoli in the 1950s and took away some ideas
for his theme parks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark's largest banking group, Den Danske Bank, controls the
remaining shares of the park and said it would be willing to part
with some.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
