<HEADLINE> Knicks 91, Rockets 85  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN, AP Basketball Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Uninhibited by a microphone and unburdened from
controversy after a late compromise by the commissioner's office,
Jeff Van Gundy and the New York Knicks had everything go their way
Tuesday -- on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell scored 27 points, reserve John Wallace added
17, and Marcus Camby returned from the injured list and made a big
defensive play as the Knicks beat the Houston Rockets 91-85.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours before tipoff, the Knicks learned the league
office had temporarily dropped its requirement that coaches wear a
microphone for nationally televised games. It was good news to Van
Gundy, who had been one of the most outspoken critics of the
league's policy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Van Gundy wearing a microphone, a boom microphone was
positioned near the Knicks' bench. The only time Van Gundy was
closely miked was during timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's much less intrusive,'' said Van Gundy, who thought that a
wave of negative publicity had something to do with the league's
shift on the microphone matter. Teams had been facing fines
beginning at $100,000 for coaches refusing to be miked. The matter
will be revisited Wednesday by the league office and the coaches'
association after they review how well the compromise worked in
this game.
</P>
<P>
   TNT used just one snippet of sound from Van Gundy as he exhorted
his team to protect the ball better and take quality shots late in
the third quarter as the Rockets were making a run.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace gave the Knicks a quick lift when he came in early in
the first quarter after Allan Houston picked up two quick fouls.
Wallace scored nine points in less than three minutes, making all
four of his shots, to help the Knicks pull ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by as many as 17 early in the third quarter, the
Rockets made a run in the fourth and pulled to 64-63 on an
alley-oop dunk by Kelvin Cato with 9:40 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks missed two shots on their next possession, and Walt
Williams was leading the fast break when Camby prevented the
Rockets from getting a shot that could have put them ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Camby, activated earlier in the day after missing more than five
weeks with a strained knee ligament, reached in and poked the ball
away from Williams, leading to a steal by Sprewell, who then turned
downcourt and hit a jumper. Kurt Thomas followed with a layup for a
five-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Houston pulled within two points with 5:15 left on a three-point
play by Cuttino Mobley, but Sprewell had a steal and jumper to end
the threat. The Rockets got no closer the rest of the way as
Patrick Ewing scored six of his 16 points in the final three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Francis led Houston with 32 points and Shandon Anderson
had 17. The Rockets lost their fourth straight.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich wore a microphone and wasn't
inhibited, unleashing a stream of vulgarities at his players as
they left the court following the first quarter. ... Team doctor
Norman Scott advised Camby to rest the knee for a couple more days
after it swelled following the team's morning shootaround, but
Camby ignored the advice. He had two points and two rebounds in 15
minutes. ... Houston's Hakeem Olajuwon sat out the first 9:49 of
the fourth quarter and spent one late timeout clipping his
fingernails. He finished 0-for-7 from the field. ... The Knicks'
Allan Houston scored just six points before fouling out with 4:58
left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
