<HEADLINE> No Arbitration Decision on Starks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- An arbitrator heard arguments for 2{ hours
Tuesday night but didn't reach a decision on whether Chicago Bulls
guard John Starks can leave the team and join a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrator Roger Kaplan said he would inform the NBA and the
players' union at a later date when he will announce his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan held a conference call Tuesday night that included
lawyers Rick Buchanan for the NBA and Jeff Kessler for the players'
association.
</P>
<P>
   Starks has offered to forfeit the rest of his $4 million salary
-- about $900,000 -- if the rebuilding Bulls would waive him,
clearing the way for him to sign with a team headed for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the union argued that if Starks was willing to give up
his salary, the league shouldn't stand in his way of joining a team
with a shot at a championship.
</P>
<P>
   The league countered that there is no provision in the
collective bargaining agreement for such a move, so it shouldn't be
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Dam, a systems arbitrator, agreed with the league
earlier this month, ruling that the NBA didn't circumvent the
collective bargaining agreement. But he said a grievance arbitrator
should hear the case and that's what Kaplan did.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls could still release Starks and let him sign with
another team, but they'd have to pay the remainder of his salary.
That would also make Starks ineligible for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Players released after 11:59 p.m. on March 1 who then sign with
another team are not eligible to compete in the playoffs. Starks
wanted his release retroactive to before the deadline so he would
be eligible for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Starks returned home to Tulsa, Okla., earlier this month to
await the decision. He's missed nine straight games with the Bulls,
played in just four games for Chicago and averaged 7.5.
</P>
<P>
   Starks came to Chicago from the Golden State Warriors last month
as part of a three-team trade that sent Toni Kukoc to Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
