<HEADLINE> Group Complains of Attacks on Press  </HEADLINE>
By ELOY O. AGUILAR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANCUN, Mexico (AP) -- A leading press group on Tuesday said it
was ''open season'' on journalists in the Americas, citing the
killings of eight journalists in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing declaration of a conference here, the
Inter-American Press Association said five journalists had been
killed in Colombia, and one each in Guatemala, Uruguay and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the assassinations, the IAPA said, journalists
face ''new forms of manipulation or muzzling that have appeared in
presumably democratic countries.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In Peru, the government appears to be prepared to remove any
vestige of legitimacy from the upcoming elections with constant
attacks on journalists and newspapers,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   The IAPA also said the press faces attacks from drug
traffickers, guerrillas and paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   It also said that certain court decisions were violating free
press ideals: In Costa Rica, the Supreme Court required the daily
La Nacion to publish the full text of a ruling against the
newspaper that took the first ten full pages of the edition; in
Peru, the newspaper El Comercio of Lima ''has been the object of
verbal abuse that presages ostensibly legal actions ... to silence
the independent press.''
</P>
<P>
   The IAPA also said that in Colombia, ''murders, threats,
kidnappings and exile continue to haunt journalists. Courage is
called for to work as a journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization also criticized the Mexican government's
decision to use its government news agency Notimex to distribute
the advertising of federal agencies. After a heated debate, IAPA
approved a resolution asking the government to dissolve or sell
Notimex.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the government reversed itself and said Notimex
would not distribute advertising. It said it reached its decision
after meeting with media leaders and hearing their ''legitimate
concerns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
