<HEADLINE> Ernst &AMP; Young Hires Ex-Adversary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Accounting giant Ernst &AMP; Young has turned to a
former adversary to help the firm win back a $185 million
settlement paid to a client last year.
</P>
<P>
   The small Pikesville law firm of Snyder, Weiner, Weltchek,
Vogelstein &AMP; Brown was on the other side of the table when the Big
Five accounting firm agreed last April to settle a lawsuit with the
now-defunct Merry-Go-Round clothing chain.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ernst &AMP; Young has hired the firm to recover the $185 million
from Swidler, Berlin, Shereff and Friedman LLP, the Washington,
D.C., law firm that served as Merry-Go-Round's legal counsel in its
efforts to reorganize under Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,400 store clothier, which was liquidated in 1996, had
blamed Ernst &AMP; Young's accountants for its failed turnaround bid
and said the firm concealed a business relationship with Swidler &AMP;
Berlin that represented a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young filed a lawsuit Monday in Baltimore Circuit Court,
blamed Swidler Berlin managing partner Roger Frankel for failing to
disclose the ties between the law firm and the accounting firm when
he recommended that Merry-Go-Round hire Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm had received more than $4 million in fees from
Ernst &AMP; Young, the suit contends, and Swidler Berlin was afraid the
disclosure might prevent Ernst &AMP; Young from winning the
Merry-Go-Round assignment, the suit claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal bankruptcy law requires that such relationships in a
bankruptcy be disclosed, the lawsuit alleged.
</P>
<P>
   When Ernst &AMP; Young agreed last year to settle claims it provided
incompetent and fraudulent advice to Merry-Go-Round, the accounting
firm said it believed ''other parties bear substantial
responsibility for the failure of Merry-Go-Round to survive'' and
that it would ''look to these parties for contribution to the
settlement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
